(151, 'multiplechoice', 26583782, 'Generic Parent', 'Surgery', 'No', 'Tumours of the posterior third of the tongue will typically metastasise early and bilateral nodal involvement is well recognised, this is most often true of centrally located tumours and those adjacent to the midline as the lymph vessels may cross the median plane at this location.[color=#0000FF]Lymphatic drainage of the tongue[/color][ul][li]The lymphatic drainage of the anterior two thirds of the tongue shows only minimal communication of lymphatics across the midline, so metastasis to the ipsilateral nodes is usual.[/li][/ul][ul][li]The lymphatic drainage of the posterior third of the tongue have communicating networks, as a result early bilateral nodal metastases are more common in this area.[/li][/ul][ul][li]Lymphatics from the tip of the tongue usually pass to the sub mental nodes and from there to the deep cervical nodes.[/li][/ul][ul][li]Lymphatics from the mid portion of the tongue usually drain to the submandibular nodes and then to the deep cervical nodes. Mid tongue tumours that are laterally located will usually drain to the ipsilateral deep cervical nodes, those from more central regions may have bilateral deep cervical nodal involvement.[/li][/ul]', 'Tumours of the posterior third of the tongue will typically metastasise early and bilateral nodal involvement is well recognised, this is most often true of centrally located tumours and those adjacent to the midline as the lymph vessels may cross the median plane at this location.[color=#0000FF]Lymphatic drainage of the tongue[/color][ul][li]The lymphatic drainage of the anterior two thirds of the tongue shows only minimal communication of lymphatics across the midline, so metastasis to the ipsilateral nodes is usual.[/li][/ul][ul][li]The lymphatic drainage of the posterior third of the tongue have communicating networks, as a result early bilateral nodal metastases are more common in this area.[/li][/ul][ul][li]Lymphatics from the tip of the tongue usually pass to the sub mental nodes and from there to the deep cervical nodes.[/li][/ul][ul][li]Lymphatics from the mid portion of the tongue usually drain to the submandibular nodes and then to the deep cervical nodes. Mid tongue tumours that are laterally located will usually drain to the ipsilateral deep cervical nodes, those from more central regions may have bilateral deep cervical nodal involvement.[/li][/ul]', 5, 'A 73 year old man presents with a tumour at the central aspect of the posterior third of the tongue. To which of the following lymph node groups is it most likely to metastasise?', 'E', 'Submental', 'Submandibular', 'Ipsilateral deep cervical nodes', 'Contralateral deep cervical nodes', 'Bilateral deep cervical nodes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(152, 'multiplechoice', 26584449, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', '[color=#0000FF]Symptoms[/color][ul][li]dysphagia for solids and liquids[/li][li]regurgitation[/li][li]difficulty belching[/li][li]vomiting[/li][li]heartburn/substernal chest pain[/li][li]weight loss[/li][/ul][color=#0000FF]Investigations[/color][b]Barium esophagram[/b]: not a sensitive test for achalasia, as it may be interpreted as normal in up to 1/3 of patients[ul][li]positive findings include-  dilation of the proximal esophagus “[color=#FF4500]bird-beak[/color]” appearance at the esophageal sphincter, delayed emptying of barium[/li][/ul][b]Upper endoscopy[/b]    [ul][li]esophageal mucosa usually appears normal[/li][/ul][ul][li]often performed after esophageal manometry to rule out malignancy[/li][/ul]', '[color=#0000FF]Symptoms[/color][ul][li]dysphagia for solids and liquids[/li][li]regurgitation[/li][li]difficulty belching[/li][li]vomiting[/li][li]heartburn/substernal chest pain[/li][li]weight loss[/li][/ul][color=#0000FF]Investigations[/color][b]Barium esophagram[/b]: not a sensitive test for achalasia, as it may be interpreted as normal in up to 1/3 of patients[ul][li]positive findings include-  dilation of the proximal esophagus “[color=#FF4500]bird-beak[/color]” appearance at the esophageal sphincter, delayed emptying of barium[/li][/ul][b]Upper endoscopy[/b]    [ul][li]esophageal mucosa usually appears normal[/li][/ul][ul][li]often performed after esophageal manometry to rule out malignancy[/li][/ul]', 5, 'A 45-year-old man presents to his primary care physician complaining of difficulty swallowing solids and liquids for the past 5 months. He also reports unintentional weight loss of 20 lbs over the past 3 months. The patient denies any fever, diarrhea, or dyspnea but endorses chest pain that is worse following food ingestion. His past medical history is unremarkable except for an episode of dengue fever when he was traveling in South America 1 year ago. A barium study is subsequently ordered. What is the diagnosis according to this x-ray?[cmimg]0/9406627_KXG641TI.jpg[/cmimg]', 'A', 'Achalasia', 'Diffuse esophageal spasm', 'Esophageal cancer', 'Barrett Esophagus', 'Boerhaave Syndrome', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(153, 'multiplechoice', 26584536, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'This patient is presenting with profuse bleeding from his esophageal varices. His Glasgow coma scale is less than 8 (eyes - 2, verbal - 2, and motor - 3) making intubation a priority in his resuscitation.Hematemesis can occur secondary to peptic ulcer disease, gastritis, esophageal varices, a Mallory-Weiss tear, and Boerhaave syndrome. Variceal bleeding is common in cirrhotics given the high resistance of the liver. Initial management should focus on the ABC\'s of trauma as these patients are prone to rapid decompensation. Once the patient\'s airway is secure/protected, the patient is breathing/oxygenating/ventilating well, and blood pressure is being maintained, specific treatment for a variceal bleed can be performed. This may involve transfusing clotting factors (given cirrhotics have an abnormal PT/PTT), proton pump inhibitors, ceftriaxone (as prophylaxis against spontaneous bacterial peritonitis), octreotide, and endoscopy with banding of the varices. Nadolol can be given for prophylaxis against future bleeds.[b]Incorrect Answers[/b]:Answer 1: Emergency surgery would be indicated to stop the bleeding in abdominal trauma with known bleeding but would only take place after the patient\'s airway had been secured.Answer 2: Emergency variceal banding would be appropriate after the patient\'s airway had been secured while the patient is receiving fluids, blood products, and clotting factors.Answer 4: IV fluids and fresh frozen plasma could be appropriate management of this patient if he was presenting with only minor hematemesis with a protected airway.Answer 5: Transfuse blood products would be appropriate if this patient was actively bleeding and his hemoglobin was < 7.0 g/dL or he was losing blood rapidly.', 'This patient is presenting with profuse bleeding from his esophageal varices. His Glasgow coma scale is less than 8 (eyes - 2, verbal - 2, and motor - 3) making intubation a priority in his resuscitation.Hematemesis can occur secondary to peptic ulcer disease, gastritis, esophageal varices, a Mallory-Weiss tear, and Boerhaave syndrome. Variceal bleeding is common in cirrhotics given the high resistance of the liver. Initial management should focus on the ABC\'s of trauma as these patients are prone to rapid decompensation. Once the patient\'s airway is secure/protected, the patient is breathing/oxygenating/ventilating well, and blood pressure is being maintained, specific treatment for a variceal bleed can be performed. This may involve transfusing clotting factors (given cirrhotics have an abnormal PT/PTT), proton pump inhibitors, ceftriaxone (as prophylaxis against spontaneous bacterial peritonitis), octreotide, and endoscopy with banding of the varices. Nadolol can be given for prophylaxis against future bleeds.[b]Incorrect Answers[/b]:Answer 1: Emergency surgery would be indicated to stop the bleeding in abdominal trauma with known bleeding but would only take place after the patient\'s airway had been secured.Answer 2: Emergency variceal banding would be appropriate after the patient\'s airway had been secured while the patient is receiving fluids, blood products, and clotting factors.Answer 4: IV fluids and fresh frozen plasma could be appropriate management of this patient if he was presenting with only minor hematemesis with a protected airway.Answer 5: Transfuse blood products would be appropriate if this patient was actively bleeding and his hemoglobin was < 7.0 g/dL or he was losing blood rapidly.', 5, 'A 55-year-old man presents to the emergency department with hematemesis that started 1 hour ago but has subsided. His past medical history is significant for cirrhosis with known esophageal varices which have been previously banded. His blood pressure is 110/60 mmHg, pulse is 130/min. During the patient\'s physical exam, he begins vomiting again and his heart rate increases with a worsening blood pressure. He develops mental status changes and on exam he opens his eyes and flexes his arms only to sternal rub and and is muttering incoherent words. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?', 'C', 'Emergency surgery', 'Emergency variceal banding', 'Intubation', 'IV fluids and fresh frozen plasma', 'Transfuse blood products', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(154, 'multiplechoice', 26584696, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'This patient with a history of atherosclerotic disease, presents with signs and symptoms of acute mesenteric ischemia (AMI), likely due to arterial thrombosis secondary to new onset atrial fibrillation. The best step in diagnosis for mesenteric ischemia is CT angiography.Figure shows an abnormal EKG with atrial fibrillation (irregularly irregular QRS interval spacing with absence of P-Waves).[b]Incorrect Answers[/b]Answer 1: Diagnostic peritoneal lavage is a largely historical procedure, that has been replaced almost completely by the bedside ultrasound, and readily available CT imaging. It has no role in the diagnosis of acute mesenteric ischemia.Answer 3: Technetium-99 tagged RBC scintigraphy is sometimes used to help evaluate for lower GI bleeding of an unknown source.Answer 4: Upper endoscopy is used to evaluate intraluminal pathology of the foregut. It has very limited role in the diagnosis of acute mesenteric ischemia.Answer 5: An upper GI radiograph series with follow through is useful in diagnosing ileus or delayed gastric emptying. Patients with suspected mesenteric ischemia should remain strictly NPO.', 'This patient with a history of atherosclerotic disease, presents with signs and symptoms of acute mesenteric ischemia (AMI), likely due to arterial thrombosis secondary to new onset atrial fibrillation. The best step in diagnosis for mesenteric ischemia is CT angiography.Figure shows an abnormal EKG with atrial fibrillation (irregularly irregular QRS interval spacing with absence of P-Waves).[b]Incorrect Answers[/b]Answer 1: Diagnostic peritoneal lavage is a largely historical procedure, that has been replaced almost completely by the bedside ultrasound, and readily available CT imaging. It has no role in the diagnosis of acute mesenteric ischemia.Answer 3: Technetium-99 tagged RBC scintigraphy is sometimes used to help evaluate for lower GI bleeding of an unknown source.Answer 4: Upper endoscopy is used to evaluate intraluminal pathology of the foregut. It has very limited role in the diagnosis of acute mesenteric ischemia.Answer 5: An upper GI radiograph series with follow through is useful in diagnosing ileus or delayed gastric emptying. Patients with suspected mesenteric ischemia should remain strictly NPO.', 5, 'A 68-year-old male smoker with a history of peripheral vascular disease and a below the knee amputation, presents to the emergency room with excruciating abdominal pain and vomiting for the last 6 hours. Vital signs are T 101.0 F, HR 136 BP 150/95, RR 18 Sat 93% on room air. Abdominal exam shows a non-distended, tender abdomen. Pulses are irregular. Laboratory values are notable for a leukocytosis and a lactic acid of 6.8 mmol/L (Normal: 0.5-1 mmol/L). An ECG is shown in Figure. What is the next best step in diagnosis?[cmimg]0/9406627_5UCUYNJQ.jpg[/cmimg]', 'B', 'Diagnostic peritoneal lavage', 'CT Angiography', 'Technetium-99 tagged RBC scintigraphy', 'Upper Endoscopy', 'Upper GI with follow through', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
