(155, 'multiplechoice', 26584937, 'Generic Parent', 'Surgery', 'No', 'This elderly patient presents with signs and symptoms of sigmoid volvulus (SV), and requires prompt derotation and decompression with a sigmoidoscopy or colonoscopy, followed by rectal tube placement and observation for signs of bowel ischemia.SV is the third leading cause of colonic obstruction in adults. It manifests as a result of redundant sigmoid loops, which can rotate about their narrow mesentery leading to obstruction and ischemia. Initial management of SV is as described above, with definitive surgery following initial successful decompression. Detorsion and decompression is successful in well over 50% of patients, allowing for time to electively operate on the patient. Once detorsed, sigmoid resection with primary anastomosis is the procedure of choice, though more extensive procedures may be required, depending on the extent of colonic damage. Detorsion should be attempted in patients who present with no signs of rupture (i.e. peritonitis), and who are hemodynamically stable.Figure/Illusration shows an abdominal x-ray demonstrating dilated loops of large bowel, with characteristic coffee bean sign (red line), concerning for sigmoid volvulus.[b]Incorrect Answers[/b]:Answer 2: A barium enema is not indicated in this patient, as a diagnosis is readily made via abdominal x-ray.Answer 3: Immediate laparotomy with hartmann\'s procedure is not the management of choice for sigmoid volvulus, especially given that this patient shows no signs of hemodynamic instability.Answer 4: Though sigmoidectomy and primary anastomosis is the procedure of choice, detorsion and decompression via sigmoidoscopy should be attempted first.Answer 5: NPO, NG tube decompression, and neostigmine are possible treatments for colonic pseudo-obstruction (Ogilvie\'s Syndrome).[cmimg]0/9406627_RSRWC7W9.jpg[/cmimg]', 'This elderly patient presents with signs and symptoms of sigmoid volvulus (SV), and requires prompt derotation and decompression with a sigmoidoscopy or colonoscopy, followed by rectal tube placement and observation for signs of bowel ischemia.SV is the third leading cause of colonic obstruction in adults. It manifests as a result of redundant sigmoid loops, which can rotate about their narrow mesentery leading to obstruction and ischemia. Initial management of SV is as described above, with definitive surgery following initial successful decompression. Detorsion and decompression is successful in well over 50% of patients, allowing for time to electively operate on the patient. Once detorsed, sigmoid resection with primary anastomosis is the procedure of choice, though more extensive procedures may be required, depending on the extent of colonic damage. Detorsion should be attempted in patients who present with no signs of rupture (i.e. peritonitis), and who are hemodynamically stable.Figure/Illusration shows an abdominal x-ray demonstrating dilated loops of large bowel, with characteristic coffee bean sign (red line), concerning for sigmoid volvulus.[b]Incorrect Answers[/b]:Answer 2: A barium enema is not indicated in this patient, as a diagnosis is readily made via abdominal x-ray.Answer 3: Immediate laparotomy with hartmann\'s procedure is not the management of choice for sigmoid volvulus, especially given that this patient shows no signs of hemodynamic instability.Answer 4: Though sigmoidectomy and primary anastomosis is the procedure of choice, detorsion and decompression via sigmoidoscopy should be attempted first.Answer 5: NPO, NG tube decompression, and neostigmine are possible treatments for colonic pseudo-obstruction (Ogilvie\'s Syndrome).[cmimg]0/9406627_RSRWC7W9.jpg[/cmimg]', 5, 'A 73-year-old woman with a history of diabetes presents to the emergency department with severe abdominal pain and constipation for 24 hours. Vital signs are T: 100.3 F, HR: 80 bpm, BP: 140/80 mmHg, RR: 24/min, O2 Sat: 95%. Abdominal examination reveals diffuse abdominal tenderness without rebound or guarding. Laboratory studies are notable for leukocytosis. Abdominal x-ray is shown in Figure. Which of the following are the best next management steps for this patient?[cmimg]0/9406627_VG0T85AK.jpg[/cmimg]', 'A', 'Sigmoidoscopy and placement of a rectal tube for 48-72 hours', 'Barium Enema with abdominal x-ray', 'Immediate laparotomy with Hartmann\'s procedure', 'Immediate laparotomy with sigmoidectomy and primary anastomosis', 'NPO, NG tube decompression and neostigmin', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(156, 'multiplechoice', 26585010, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'This patient is suffering from a GI bleed, as evidenced by her hematochezia (bright red blood per rectum). A patient presenting with a GI bleed should undergo a type and screen to allow for prompt blood transfusion if it becomes necessary.The initial management of a patient with a GI bleed is to first assess the ABC\'s including managing their airway and ensuring the patient has good IV access and is able to receive fluids/blood products if needed. If the patient is actively and rapidly bleeding or has a hemoglobin < 7.0 g/dL, they should be transfused. Otherwise, they should receive a type and screen to prepare for a transfusion if it is required. Subsequent management will involve a colonoscopy to determine the source of the bleeding.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Colonoscopy is indicated for evaluation of a suspected lower GI bleed after this patient has been appropriately stabilized and a type and screen has been obtained.Answer 2: CT abdomen can be used to visualize bleeding in the peritoneal cavity or retroperitoneum. An abdominal CT with contrast can be used to localize a source of bleeding in some circumstances; however, colonoscopy is the preferred diagnostic test for a lower GI bleed.Answer 3: Fresh frozen plasma might be indicated if this patient were on warfarin (or thought to be anticoagulated for some other reason); however, it does not take priority over preparing to transfuse the patient if they start bleeding again.Answer 4: Packed red blood cells would be indicated if this patient had a hemoglobin < 7.0 g/dL or if they were actively and rapidly bleeding (since the hemoglobin would likely drop precipitously in this situation). This patient\'s resolved bleeding and hemoglobin > 7.0 g/dL makes this a less dire step.', 'This patient is suffering from a GI bleed, as evidenced by her hematochezia (bright red blood per rectum). A patient presenting with a GI bleed should undergo a type and screen to allow for prompt blood transfusion if it becomes necessary.The initial management of a patient with a GI bleed is to first assess the ABC\'s including managing their airway and ensuring the patient has good IV access and is able to receive fluids/blood products if needed. If the patient is actively and rapidly bleeding or has a hemoglobin < 7.0 g/dL, they should be transfused. Otherwise, they should receive a type and screen to prepare for a transfusion if it is required. Subsequent management will involve a colonoscopy to determine the source of the bleeding.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Colonoscopy is indicated for evaluation of a suspected lower GI bleed after this patient has been appropriately stabilized and a type and screen has been obtained.Answer 2: CT abdomen can be used to visualize bleeding in the peritoneal cavity or retroperitoneum. An abdominal CT with contrast can be used to localize a source of bleeding in some circumstances; however, colonoscopy is the preferred diagnostic test for a lower GI bleed.Answer 3: Fresh frozen plasma might be indicated if this patient were on warfarin (or thought to be anticoagulated for some other reason); however, it does not take priority over preparing to transfuse the patient if they start bleeding again.Answer 4: Packed red blood cells would be indicated if this patient had a hemoglobin < 7.0 g/dL or if they were actively and rapidly bleeding (since the hemoglobin would likely drop precipitously in this situation). This patient\'s resolved bleeding and hemoglobin > 7.0 g/dL makes this a less dire step.', 5, 'A 71-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department following a syncopal episode. Earlier in the day, the patient had multiple bowel movements that filled the toilet bowl with copious amounts of bright red blood. Minutes later, she felt dizzy and lightheaded and collapsed. The patient has a medical history of diabetes mellitus and hypertension. Fecal occult blood test is positive; however, the patient is no longer having bloody bowel movements. The patient\'s abdomen is soft and non-tender. Labs are ordered as seen below.Hemoglobin: 7.1 g/dLHematocrit: 25%Leukocyte count: 5,300/mm^3 with normal differentialPlatelet count: 182,500/mm^3Two large bore IV\'s are placed and the patient is given normal saline. What is the best next step in management?', 'E', 'Colonoscopy', 'CT abdomen', 'Packed red blood cells', 'Fresh frozen plasma', 'Blood grouping and transfusion', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(157, 'multiplechoice', 26585113, 'Generic Parent', 'Surgery', 'No', 'CT scan shows hugely distended large gut loop suggestive of large bowel obstruction.', 'CT scan shows hugely distended large gut loop suggestive of large bowel obstruction.', 5, 'A 65-year-old man presents to the emergency room for increased abdominal pain and distention. He has a history of diverticulosis and chronic constipation. He last had a bowel movement 1 week ago and has not had any flatus in the past day. He reports 2 episodes of vomiting at home. On physical exam, his abdomen is distended and there is diffuse tenderness to palpation. DRE showed empty rectum. A CT of his abdomen and pelvis was done. What is the most probably diagnosis?[cmimg]0/9406627_0MSIZBOI.jpg[/cmimg]', 'C', 'Ectopic pregnancy', 'Appendicitis', 'Large bowel obstruction', 'Small bowel obstruction', 'Intestinal perfiration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(158, 'multiplechoice', 26585175, 'Generic Parent', 'Surgery', 'No', 'This patient is presenting with peritoneal signs on abdominal exam, increased NSAID use (back pain with increased use of pain medications), and free air under the diaphragm on radiography which is concerning for a perforated viscus.A perforated peptic ulcer is the most common cause of bowel perforation. If there is high clinical suspicion, an abdominal or chest radiograph should be ordered to look for pneumoperitoneum, which is free air in the abdomen under the diaphragm. If present, the diagnosis is confirmed and the patient should be taken to the operating room emergently. Emergent exploratory laparotomy with surgical repair is indicated for all patients with bowel perforation.Radiograph demonstrating free air under the diaphragm which is concerning for a perforated viscus.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Gastritis would present with chronic and gnawing epigastric pain that is worse with meals. Treatment can include proton pump inhibitors. Radiography would be normal in this condition; however, the diagnosis can be supported with endoscopy.Answer 2: Peptic ulcer disease is likely the preceding risk factor for this patient\'s condition. It often presents with epigastric pain that is worse with eating. Alcohol and NSAID use are risk factors. This patient likely had peptic ulcer disease which worsened as the patient continually took NSAIDs for his back pain leading to perforation. Peritoneal signs and free air are not seen in peptic ulcer disease.Answer 4: Pneumothorax would present with pleuritic chest pain and hypoxia. Chest radiograph would demonstrate an absence of lung markings that extend to the periphery.Answer 5: Ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm would present with sudden abdominal/back pain, hypotension, and tachycardia and requires blood products and emergency vascular surgery. It would not present with free air under the diaphragm.', NULL, 5, 'A 60-year-old man with a history of chronic back pain presents to the emergency department with abdominal pain. He states his back pain has been worsening recently requiring more pain medications. His temperature is 97.6°F (36.4°C), blood pressure is 122/80 mmHg, pulse is 120/min, respirations are 12/min, and oxygen saturation is 98% on room air. The patient is laying still on his back and is moaning in pain. There is notable tenderness in all quadrants with rebound tenderness. The patient\'s heart rate is 90/min after receiving hydromorphone. A radiograph is performed as seen in Figure. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?[cmimg]0/9406627_M3B23BX6.jpg[/cmimg]', 'C', 'Gastritis', 'Peptic ulcer disease', 'Perforated viscus', 'Pneumothorax', 'Ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(159, 'multiplechoice', 26585385, 'Generic Parent', 'Surgery', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 71-year-old female presents to her primary care physician with a four-day history of left lower quadrant abdominal pain. The patient also complains of diarrhea and mild nausea. On exam, her vitals are T: 101F, HR 86, BP 130/92, RR 15, and SaO2 100%. Abdominal exam is notable for left lower quadrant tenderness to palpation without rebound or guarding. Urine dipstick is normal and complete blood count shows a minor leukocytosis. An abdominal CT was done. What is the diagnosis?[cmimg]0/9406627_56Z4BII5.jpg[/cmimg]', 'B', 'Perforation of sigmoid colon', 'Diverticulitis', 'Renal stone', 'Gut perforation', 'Appendicitis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(160, 'multiplechoice', 26600526, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'The clinical features and raised ESR is suggestive of polymyalgia rheumatica. Thepainful mastication indicates that the patient may also be suffering from temporalarteritis. It would be important to treat promptly with high dose steroids.To differentiate between polymyalgia rheumatica and statin induced myopathy, ESRis usually measured. Patients with polymyalgia rheumatica will have a significantlyelevated ESR, whereas patients with statin myopathy would have a normal ESR.', 'The clinical features and raised ESR is suggestive of polymyalgia rheumatica. Thepainful mastication indicates that the patient may also be suffering from temporalarteritis. It would be important to treat promptly with high dose steroids.To differentiate between polymyalgia rheumatica and statin induced myopathy, ESRis usually measured. Patients with polymyalgia rheumatica will have a significantlyelevated ESR, whereas patients with statin myopathy would have a normal ESR.', 5, 'An 84 year old female presents with pain and stiffness of her pelvic andshoulder girdle. She also complains of painful mastication. She drinksapproximately 15 units of alcohol per week. Her current medication includeatorvastatin and amlodipine. Investigations demonstrate an ESR of95mm/hour.What is the most likely diagnosis?', 'B', 'Polymyositis', 'Polymyalgia rheumatica', 'Fibromyalgi', 'Alcoholic myopathy', 'Statin induced myopathy', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(161, 'multiplechoice', 26605143, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', '“feeling something is wrong in his body”, anxiety, palpitation – thesesymptoms are clearly in favor of that this patient is having Panic Attack.There are 3 most important organic cause of Panic attack:1. Hyperthyroidism2. Phaeochromocytoma3. HypoglycemiaNow, the most important question is why it is not Hyperthyroidism?Ans: In case of Hyperthyroidism a patient can present with all of thesesymptoms, except headache. Moreover, in hyperthyroidism, a patient willrarely present with HTN and most of them will have systolic hypertension.', '“feeling something is wrong in his body”, anxiety, palpitation – thesesymptoms are clearly in favor of that this patient is having Panic Attack.There are 3 most important organic cause of Panic attack:1. Hyperthyroidism2. Phaeochromocytoma3. HypoglycemiaNow, the most important question is why it is not Hyperthyroidism?Ans: In case of Hyperthyroidism a patient can present with all of thesesymptoms, except headache. Moreover, in hyperthyroidism, a patient willrarely present with HTN and most of them will have systolic hypertension.', 5, 'A 22 years old man brought to ED after a syncopal attack. He complaints ofsevere headache and complaint of “feeling something is wrong in his body”.On examination‐ patient is anxious, BP 160/100, heart rate is 130, patient wassweating profusely. What will you do?', 'B', 'Give beta blockers', 'Investigate for pheochromocytoma', 'Investigate for hyperthyroidism', 'Arrange psychiatric counselling', 'MRI of brain', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(162, 'multiplechoice', 26605171, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', '[cmimg]0/9406627_E4KMSFRN.jpeg[/cmimg]', '[cmimg]0/9406627_E4KMSFRN.jpeg[/cmimg]', 5, 'Girl with type‐1 Diabetes, on intermediate insulin at night, short acting insulin in the morning. Her parents concerned about her high glucose levels of 15 at morning. what is the most appropriate next step?', 'C', 'Increase intermediate insulin at night', 'Increase short acting insulin in the morning', 'Measure glucose levels at 2am and 3am', 'In addition to insulin start oral hypoglycemic agent', 'Change to “long acting + short acting” insulin', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(163, 'multiplechoice', 26605200, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', '“an opacity with well defined round margin” – this is called “Halo Sign” – acharacteristic feature of Aspergilloma.This is a case of Aspergillus Meningitis, which is one of the most commoninfection after renal transplant.[cmimg]0/9406627_SI0PKURZ.jpg[/cmimg]', '“an opacity with well defined round margin” – this is called “Halo Sign” – acharacteristic feature of Aspergilloma.This is a case of Aspergillus Meningitis, which is one of the most commoninfection after renal transplant.[cmimg]0/9406627_SI0PKURZ.jpg[/cmimg]', 5, '50 year old man with H/O renal transplant present to you with mild fever,headache, nausea and vomiting for 3 days. On examination, neck stiffness ispresent. On chest x‐ray there is an opacity with well defined round margin inmiddle zone of right lung. What is the cause?', 'A', 'Aspergillus', 'TB', 'Pneumocystis Pneumonia', 'Lymphoma', 'Nocardiasis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(164, 'multiplechoice', 26605222, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'It is a case of “Boerhaave Syndrome”', 'It is a case of “Boerhaave Syndrome”', 5, 'A 19‐year‐old college student presents to the emergency department withexcruciating retrosternal chest pain that radiates to the back. She describesthe pain as sharp and worsens with swallowing. She reports that hersymptoms began after vomiting 1 hour ago. Medical history is significant foranorexia nervosa. Which of the following investigation will you order to reachdiagnosis?', 'B', 'CT chest', 'Gastrograffin swallow', 'Ultrasound', 'Echo', 'Chest Xray', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(165, 'multiplechoice', 26613686, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', '[color=#FF0000]\'Fasciculations’ ‐ think motor neuron disease[/color][b][u][i]Motor neuron disease: features[/i][/u][/b]Motor neuron disease is a neurological condition of unknown cause which can present withboth upper and lower motor neuron signs. It rarely presents before 40 years and variouspatterns of disease are recognized including amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, progressivemuscular atrophy and bulbar palsy.There are a number of clues which point towards a diagnosis of motor neuron disease:‐ fasciculation‐ absence of sensory signs/symptoms*(*vague sensory symptoms may occur early in the disease (e.g. limb pain) but \'never\' sensorysigns)‐ lower motor neuron signs in arms and upper motor neuron signs in legs‐ wasting of the small hand muscles/tibialis anterior is common[u][b][i]Other features[/i][/b][/u]‐ doesn\'t affect external ocular muscles‐ no cerebellar signs‐ abdominal reflexes are usually preserved and sphincter dysfunction if presentis a late featureThe diagnosis of motor neuron disease is clinical, but nerve conduction studieswill show normal motor conduction and can help exclude a neuropathy.Electromyography shows a reduced number of action potentials with anincreased amplitude. MRI is usually performed to exclude the differentialdiagnosis of cervical cord compression and myelopathy.', '[color=#FF0000]\'Fasciculations’ ‐ think motor neuron disease[/color][b][u][i]Motor neuron disease: features[/i][/u][/b]Motor neuron disease is a neurological condition of unknown cause which can present withboth upper and lower motor neuron signs. It rarely presents before 40 years and variouspatterns of disease are recognized including amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, progressivemuscular atrophy and bulbar palsy.There are a number of clues which point towards a diagnosis of motor neuron disease:‐ fasciculation‐ absence of sensory signs/symptoms*(*vague sensory symptoms may occur early in the disease (e.g. limb pain) but \'never\' sensorysigns)‐ lower motor neuron signs in arms and upper motor neuron signs in legs‐ wasting of the small hand muscles/tibialis anterior is common[u][b][i]Other features[/i][/b][/u]‐ doesn\'t affect external ocular muscles‐ no cerebellar signs‐ abdominal reflexes are usually preserved and sphincter dysfunction if presentis a late featureThe diagnosis of motor neuron disease is clinical, but nerve conduction studieswill show normal motor conduction and can help exclude a neuropathy.Electromyography shows a reduced number of action potentials with anincreased amplitude. MRI is usually performed to exclude the differentialdiagnosis of cervical cord compression and myelopathy.', 5, 'A 64yearold man presents with a eight month history of generalizedweakness. On examination he has fasciculation and weakness in both armswith absent reflexes. Examination of the lower limbs reveal increased tone andexaggerated reflexes. Sensation was normal and there were no cerebellarsigns. What is the most likely diagnosis?', 'B', 'Lead poisoning', 'Motor neuron disease', 'Vitamin B12 deficiency', 'Syringomyelia', 'Multiple sclerosis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(166, 'multiplechoice', 26613710, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'This is a case of [b][i]Lymphomatous Meningitis[/i][/b]Lymphomatous meningitis is a progressive disease caused by the spread oflymphoma (cancer of the lymph nodes or thymus) cells into theleptomeninges, the protective membrane of the brain and spinal cord.Diagnosis of lymphomatous meningitis usually includes a neurologicalexam, imaging of the central nervous system and lumbar punctures(spinal taps) ‐ MRI of the brain and study of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).However, in this patient there is a symptom of raised ICP (fundoscopyexam shows bilateral optic disc swelling). Therefore, LP iscontraindicated. So, MRI of brain is the best option here.', 'This is a case of [b][i]Lymphomatous Meningitis[/i][/b]Lymphomatous meningitis is a progressive disease caused by the spread oflymphoma (cancer of the lymph nodes or thymus) cells into theleptomeninges, the protective membrane of the brain and spinal cord.Diagnosis of lymphomatous meningitis usually includes a neurologicalexam, imaging of the central nervous system and lumbar punctures(spinal taps) ‐ MRI of the brain and study of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).However, in this patient there is a symptom of raised ICP (fundoscopyexam shows bilateral optic disc swelling). Therefore, LP iscontraindicated. So, MRI of brain is the best option here.', 5, 'A 36yr old woman comes to the emergency dept. because of severeheadache that woke her from sleep 6 hours ago, and was not relieved byaspirin or acetaminophen. She also noticed that she has neck stiffness andthat it hurts during neck extension and flexion. She was recently diagnosed ofHodgkin\'s disease. Her temp is 39, BP is 130/80mmhg, Pulse 75, respirations is17/m. Physical exam shows nuchal rigidity, fundoscopy exam shows bilateraloptic disc swelling. She appears lethargic has eye tenderness with movement,mild photosensitivity. After obtaining blood cultures, next step?', 'D', 'Order CT scan', 'IV ceftriaxone', 'MRI angiogram of head', 'MRI of the head', 'Perform lumbar puncture', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(167, 'multiplechoice', 26614052, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'Here, PaO2 is decreasing and PaCO2 is increasing.CPAP is a non‐invasive ventilation.Continuous positive airway pressure therapy (CPAP) will maintain a sustainpositive pressure which will help to prevent airway collapse and washout CO2.', 'Here, PaO2 is decreasing and PaCO2 is increasing.CPAP is a non‐invasive ventilation.Continuous positive airway pressure therapy (CPAP) will maintain a sustainpositive pressure which will help to prevent airway collapse and washout CO2.', 5, 'A patient with chronic lung disease (COPD) develops respiratory distress, cough and fever was admitted to hospital. Ipratropium and salbutamol given 8 hourly. Oral prednisolone, oral roxithromycin and IV amoxicillin given.ABG was done and showing: pH 7.3, PaO2 80mmHg, PaCO2: 55mmHg,HCO3‐ 35mmHg.What is your next management?', 'C', 'Give IV hydrocortisone', 'Increase bronchodilator to 4 hourly', 'CPAP', 'Admit to ICU', 'Change to IV Cefotaxime', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(168, 'multiplechoice', 26614067, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'According to UK guidelines, in case of AF, after basic ABC assessment, patients areclassified as being stable or unstable according to the presence of any adverse signs:‐ shock: hypotension (systolic blood pressure < 90 mmHg), pallor, sweating,‐ cold, clammy extremities, confusion or impaired consciousness‐ syncope‐ myocardial ischaemia‐ heart failureIf any of the above adverse signs are present, then synchronised DC shocks should begiven.Though here BP is 100/60, it will eventually fall and patient will go to shock suddenly.So, to prevent that, DC sock is a must here.', 'According to UK guidelines, in case of AF, after basic ABC assessment, patients areclassified as being stable or unstable according to the presence of any adverse signs:‐ shock: hypotension (systolic blood pressure < 90 mmHg), pallor, sweating,‐ cold, clammy extremities, confusion or impaired consciousness‐ syncope‐ myocardial ischaemia‐ heart failureIf any of the above adverse signs are present, then synchronised DC shocks should begiven.Though here BP is 100/60, it will eventually fall and patient will go to shock suddenly.So, to prevent that, DC sock is a must here.', 5, 'You are asked to urgently review a 61 year old female on the cardiologyward due to difficulty in breathing. On examination she has a raised JVP withbilateral fine crackles to the mid zones. Blood pressure is 100/60 mmHg andthe pulse is 140‐150 and irregular. ECG confirms atrial fibrillation.What is the most appropriate management?', 'C', 'IV amiodarone', 'IV digoxin', 'Synchronized DC cardioversion', 'Oral digoxin', 'IV flecainide', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(169, 'multiplechoice', 26614086, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'Note there is no association between the P waves and QRS complexes in theECG. This is the hallmark of Third Degree (complete) heart block.[cmimg]0/9406627_LVRU7UQZ.png[/cmimg]', 'Note there is no association between the P waves and QRS complexes in theECG. This is the hallmark of Third Degree (complete) heart block.[cmimg]0/9406627_LVRU7UQZ.png[/cmimg]', 5, 'A 72-year-old presents to the emergency department complaining of dizziness. An ECG is taken and shows the following[cmimg]0/9406627_SUBENHZV.png[/cmimg]According to this ECG finding, which one of the following is the diagnosis?', 'E', 'Ventricular tachycardia', 'Second degree heart block Mobitz type 2', 'First degree heart block', 'Second degree heart block Mobitz type 1', 'Third degree heart block', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(170, 'multiplechoice', 26614137, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'Rapid Malaria Test is 98% sensitive and 96% specific. On the other hand, thickand thin film is much less sensitive and specific than Rapid Test. Though test isnegative, however, scenario is of typical Malaria. Test can be negative if thereis no parasite in drawn blood.So, draw blood when fever is at peak and test again... because when the feveris at peak, that\'s the time when merozoites break the RBC and come to blood.Therefore, has much higher possibility to get positive result.', 'Rapid Malaria Test is 98% sensitive and 96% specific. On the other hand, thickand thin film is much less sensitive and specific than Rapid Test. Though test isnegative, however, scenario is of typical Malaria. Test can be negative if thereis no parasite in drawn blood.So, draw blood when fever is at peak and test again... because when the feveris at peak, that\'s the time when merozoites break the RBC and come to blood.Therefore, has much higher possibility to get positive result.', 5, 'A man returned from Asia. Now complains intermittent fever with chillsand rigor. He said that he used mosquito net during sleep at night. He has mildsplenomegaly with thrombocytopenia.Rapid Malaria Rest (98% sensitive and 96% specific) is negative. Now what todo?', 'C', 'Repeat the test', 'Thick and thin film', 'Draw blood when fever is at peak and test again', 'Test for other infectious disease', 'Test for TB', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(171, 'multiplechoice', 26614165, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A patient came to you with complaints of profuse sweating and someweight loss. Thyroid hormone level was done. Report said‐ T3 and T4 level isnormal, TSH level is mildly decreased. What is the diagnosis?', 'C', '2ndary hyperthyroidism', 'Euthyroidism', 'Sub‐clinical hyperthyroidism', 'Compensatory thyroid disease', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(172, 'multiplechoice', 26614183, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 34‐year‐old man comes to the clinic for an evaluation of strangespontaneous movements of hand that have been occurring lately. He has alsogait problem which developed recently on a sudden. His father died at the ageof 41 from “dementia.” What is the diagnosis?', 'D', 'Familial Alzheimer disease', 'Parkinson disease', 'Parkinson disease', 'Huntington disease', 'Motor neurone disease', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(173, 'multiplechoice', 26614218, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'The nub of this question is emergency management of haemorrhage inpatients on warfarin. This patient has an INR greater than 8 and is activelybleeding. Therefore the answer is D.Patients on warfarin have reduced levels of Factor X, IX, VII and II. Rapidcorrection is most effectively achieved through administration of prothrombincomplex concentrates.Please read JM‐1440', 'The nub of this question is emergency management of haemorrhage inpatients on warfarin. This patient has an INR greater than 8 and is activelybleeding. Therefore the answer is D.Patients on warfarin have reduced levels of Factor X, IX, VII and II. Rapidcorrection is most effectively achieved through administration of prothrombincomplex concentrates.Please read JM‐1440', 5, '77 year old man with known atrial fibrillation is admitted following an uppergastrointestinal hemorrhage. His atrial fibrillation is managed using bisoprolol and warfarin. Since his admission he has had four large episodes of hematemesis. You, the emergency department foundation doctor, request the patients INR to be checked as one of a series of investigations. The hematology laboratory phone through and inform you his INR is 8.5. He is currently hypotensive (90/45 mmHg) and tachycardic (120 beats per minute). You begin resuscitation using 0.9% saline, and send a cross match, group and save. What is the most appropriate treatment of this patients INR?', 'D', 'Fresh frozen plasma + stop warfarin', 'Vitamin K + stop warfarin', 'Prothrombin complex concentrates', 'Prothrombin complex concentrates + vitamin K + stop warfarin', 'Stop warfarin', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(174, 'multiplechoice', 26614376, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, '1 year old child diagnosed with bacterial meningitis was admitted tohospital.blood culture taken and iv ceftriaxone started .after 1 day ofadmission child had a seizure of <1min duration.long labsWere given sodium and bicarbonate low.all others in normal range.What is thecause of seizure?', 'A', 'SIADH', 'Dehydration', 'Adrenal failure', 'Primary polydipsia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(175, 'multiplechoice', 26614414, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A patient with history of claudication, smoke 30 pack cigarette per day, drink alcohol,obese with diabetic history. he refuse surgery although he was fit for it. He asked youfor the appropriate advice that will improve his symptoms of claudication?', 'A', 'Reduce smoking', 'reduce alcohol drinking', 'supervised exercise', 'control his hypercholesterolemia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(176, 'multiplechoice', 26614677, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'ECG of an adult presented with chest pain cardiac enzyme and 1st ECG normal andBp was 120/70 after 8 hrs of observation his BP goes down 89/50 and ECG showingSVT with HR 150,what would you do?', 'D', 'Adenosine', 'Flecianide', 'Atropine', 'Synchronized cardioversion', 'defibrilation', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(177, 'multiplechoice', 26614692, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 32 year old woman presented with bilateral joint swellings of her proximal interphalangeal jointsassociated with a 45 minutes period of early morning stiffness of joints. She has obvious rheumatoidnodules and a high rheumatoid factor positive assay . She got raynoud phenomenon treated withnifedipine. Rhematoid positive, ds DNA positive but negative CCP. Which of the following is the best longterm management?', 'E', 'infliximab', 'sulfasalazine', 'methotrexate', 'prednisolone', 'Hydroxychloroquin', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
