potential cause of this disorder is excessive water drinking', 'Urinary sodium will be > 20 and fractional excretion of sodium will be >1%', 'Urinary sodium will be < 10, and fractional excretion of sodium will be <1%', 'Urinary sodium will be > 20 and another potential cause of this disorder is renal failure', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(188, 'multiplechoice', 26653650, 'Generic Parent', 'Generic', 'No', '[b]Dx[/b]: Trigeminal Neuralgia[b]Introduction[/b][ul][li]Severe, sharp, stabbing pain in one or more trigeminal nerve (CN V) divisions[/li][ul][li]onset and termination is abrupt[/li][li]commonly involving V2 and V3 branches of CN V[/li][/ul][/ul][b]Presentation[/b][ul][li]Symptoms [/li][ul][li]sharp, shock-like pain in one more more CN V divisions typically unilateral[/li][li]usually lasts seconds long[/li][li]can be triggered by mechanical stimuli; e.g., brushing teeth, smiling, chewing[/li][/ul][/ul][b]Treatment[/b][ul][li]Medical[/li][ul][li]carbamazepine (first-line)[/li][/ul][/ul][ul][li]Surgical - for refractory cases[/li][ul][li]microvascular decompression[/li][li]rhizotomy[/li][li]radiosurgery[/li][/ul][/ul]', '[b]Dx[/b]: Trigeminal Neuralgia[b]Introduction[/b][ul][li]Severe, sharp, stabbing pain in one or more trigeminal nerve (CN V) divisions[/li][ul][li]onset and termination is abrupt[/li][li]commonly involving V2 and V3 branches of CN V[/li][/ul][/ul][b]Presentation[/b][ul][li]Symptoms [/li][ul][li]sharp, shock-like pain in one more more CN V divisions typically unilateral[/li][li]usually lasts seconds long[/li][li]can be triggered by mechanical stimuli; e.g., brushing teeth, smiling, chewing[/li][/ul][/ul][b]Treatment[/b][ul][li]Medical[/li][ul][li]carbamazepine (first-line)[/li][/ul][/ul][ul][li]Surgical - for refractory cases[/li][ul][li]microvascular decompression[/li][li]rhizotomy[/li][li]radiosurgery[/li][/ul][/ul]', 5, 'A 54-year-old female presents with severe, stabbing pain on her left mandible. The pain lasts a few seconds and is triggered by brushing her teeth or chewing food. The pain episodes lasts a few seconds and occur 20 times per day. She denies any recent trauma or dental procedures. Over the counter simple analgesics do not improve the pain. On physical exam, touching the mandibular region reproduces the pain. Neurological exam is otherwise normal.What is the most probably diagnosis?', 'D', 'Dental pain', 'Cluster headache', 'Temporomandibular joint (TMJ) inflammation', 'Trigeminal Neuralgia', 'Glossopharyngeal neuralgia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(189, 'multiplechoice', 26653858, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'The patient is presenting with a resting tremor, rigidity, reduced facial expressions, and dementia, which are consistent with Parkinson disease.Parkinson disease is a progressive neurodegenerative movement disorder. Age of onset is on average 60 years of age. The disorder affects dopaminergic neurons in the basal ganglia, which leads to a group of classic cardinal symptoms. Patients present with a resting “pill-rolling” tremor, bradykinesia, shuffling gait, hypomimia (mask-like facies), soft voice, slowed speech, “cogwheel” muscle rigidity, and dementia. First-line pharmacologic treatment usually involves carbidopa-levodopa.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Essential tremor most commonly affects the hands, but the tremor occurs and worsens with posturing and voluntary movement. Unlike the parkinsonian tremor, an essential tremor often improves with rest as well as with alcohol consumption.Answer 2: Dementia with Lewy bodies can present with parkinsonism but is also characteristically associated with visual hallucinations.Answer 4: Progressive supranuclear palsy can present with parkinsonism but is also characteristically associated with vertical gaze palsy, dysphagia, and frontal lobe abnormalities (i.e., apathy and disinhibition)Answer 5: Tardive dyskinesia is an extrapyramidal side effect of dopaminergic antipsychotics. Patients present with involuntary, repetitive, stereotypical writhing movements years after being on an antipsychotic.', 'The patient is presenting with a resting tremor, rigidity, reduced facial expressions, and dementia, which are consistent with Parkinson disease.Parkinson disease is a progressive neurodegenerative movement disorder. Age of onset is on average 60 years of age. The disorder affects dopaminergic neurons in the basal ganglia, which leads to a group of classic cardinal symptoms. Patients present with a resting “pill-rolling” tremor, bradykinesia, shuffling gait, hypomimia (mask-like facies), soft voice, slowed speech, “cogwheel” muscle rigidity, and dementia. First-line pharmacologic treatment usually involves carbidopa-levodopa.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Essential tremor most commonly affects the hands, but the tremor occurs and worsens with posturing and voluntary movement. Unlike the parkinsonian tremor, an essential tremor often improves with rest as well as with alcohol consumption.Answer 2: Dementia with Lewy bodies can present with parkinsonism but is also characteristically associated with visual hallucinations.Answer 4: Progressive supranuclear palsy can present with parkinsonism but is also characteristically associated with vertical gaze palsy, dysphagia, and frontal lobe abnormalities (i.e., apathy and disinhibition)Answer 5: Tardive dyskinesia is an extrapyramidal side effect of dopaminergic antipsychotics. Patients present with involuntary, repetitive, stereotypical writhing movements years after being on an antipsychotic.', 5, 'A 70-year-old man is accompanied by his wife to the primary care clinic for hand tremors. He states that he first noticed the tremor of his left hand 1 year ago. Since then, the tremor has been worsening and now he can hardly relax when trying to read. His wife says that she is also worried about his memory. The patient’s medical history is significant for hypertension. He takes aspirin and amlodipine. His mother had schizophrenia. On physical examination, he speaks softly and has reduced facial expressions. He has a resting tremor that is worse on the left, and he resists manipulation of his bilateral upper extremities. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'B', 'Essential tremor', 'Dementia with Lewy bodies', 'Parkinson disease', 'Progressive supranuclear palsy', 'Tardive dyskinesia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(190, 'multiplechoice', 26653975, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'This patient is presenting with weakness and diplopia at the end of the day with her upper extremities affected more than her lower extremities suggesting a diagnosis of myasthenia gravis.Myasthenia gravis occurs secondary to autoimmune destruction of acetylcholine receptors. This leads to proximal muscle weakness (with the upper extremities affected more than the lower), ptosis, and diplopia that is typically worsened with repeat stimulation or at the end of the day. The ice pack test or edrophonium test can improve symptoms and support the diagnosis. The treatment is administration of long-acting acetylcholinesterase inhibitors such as pyridostigmine.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis typically occurs in men and presents with both upper and lower motor symptoms including limb spasticity, hyperreflexia, emotional lability, limb muscle weakness, atrophy, fasciculations, dysarthria, and dysphagia.Answers 2 & 5: Guillain-Barre syndrome and tick paralysis would both present with an ascending flaccid paralysis. Guillain-Barre syndrome presents with more severe symptoms, increased frequency of respiratory and autonomic symptoms, and a gradual onset of symptoms with a preceding diarrheal illness. Tick-born paralysis occurs after tick exposure and presents with more sudden onset symptoms (the morning after the bite) with ascending flaccid paralysis with a lower incidence of severe symptoms.Answer 3: Lambert-Eaton syndrome presents with muscle weakness that improves with repeat use in contrast to myasthenia gravis which presents with muscle weakness that worsens with repeat use (such as weakness and diplopia at the end of the day).', 'This patient is presenting with weakness and diplopia at the end of the day with her upper extremities affected more than her lower extremities suggesting a diagnosis of myasthenia gravis.Myasthenia gravis occurs secondary to autoimmune destruction of acetylcholine receptors. This leads to proximal muscle weakness (with the upper extremities affected more than the lower), ptosis, and diplopia that is typically worsened with repeat stimulation or at the end of the day. The ice pack test or edrophonium test can improve symptoms and support the diagnosis. The treatment is administration of long-acting acetylcholinesterase inhibitors such as pyridostigmine.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis typically occurs in men and presents with both upper and lower motor symptoms including limb spasticity, hyperreflexia, emotional lability, limb muscle weakness, atrophy, fasciculations, dysarthria, and dysphagia.Answers 2 & 5: Guillain-Barre syndrome and tick paralysis would both present with an ascending flaccid paralysis. Guillain-Barre syndrome presents with more severe symptoms, increased frequency of respiratory and autonomic symptoms, and a gradual onset of symptoms with a preceding diarrheal illness. Tick-born paralysis occurs after tick exposure and presents with more sudden onset symptoms (the morning after the bite) with ascending flaccid paralysis with a lower incidence of severe symptoms.Answer 3: Lambert-Eaton syndrome presents with muscle weakness that improves with repeat use in contrast to myasthenia gravis which presents with muscle weakness that worsens with repeat use (such as weakness and diplopia at the end of the day).', 0, 'A 33-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with weakness. She states that at the end of the day she feels so fatigued and weak that she can hardly care for herself. She currently feels this way. The patient has had multiple illnesses recently and has been traveling, hiking, and camping. Her vital signs are normal. Physical exam is notable for 2/5 strength of the upper extremities and 4/5 strength of the lower extremities. Visual exam is notable for mild diplopia. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'D', 'Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis', 'Guillain-Barre syndrome', 'Lambert-Eaton syndrome', 'Myasthenia gravis', 'Tick paralysis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(191, 'multiplechoice', 26654207, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'This patient is presenting with a sudden decline in cognitive function in the setting of hypertension, which is suggestive of vascular dementia.Vascular dementia is the second most common cause of dementia. It typically occurs in patients with risk factors such as hypertension, atherosclerosis, and vasculitis. Typically, there is a multifocal infarction that leads to the subsequent injury. The presentation of vascular dementia is unique in that there is a stepwise decline in cognitive ability with discrete events in contrast to Alzheimer dementia which is a gradual decline. There is no treatment for vascular dementia other than treating the underlying etiology, which would involve interventions such as treatment of hypertension and dyslipidemia and smoking cessation.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Alzheimer dementia presents with an insidious and gradual decline in cognitive function that may present initially with minor forgetfulness and can progress over years to an inability for the patient to care for themselves.Answer 2: Frontotemporal dementia is associated with memory loss and changes in personality with loss of social awareness and poor impulse control.Answer 3: Lewy body dementia presents with both dementia as well as visual hallucinations, delusions, and Parkinson-like features.Answer 4: Normal pressure hydrocephalus presents with “wacky, wet, and wobbly,” which corresponds to changes in behavior, urinary incontinence, and ataxia.', 'This patient is presenting with a sudden decline in cognitive function in the setting of hypertension, which is suggestive of vascular dementia.Vascular dementia is the second most common cause of dementia. It typically occurs in patients with risk factors such as hypertension, atherosclerosis, and vasculitis. Typically, there is a multifocal infarction that leads to the subsequent injury. The presentation of vascular dementia is unique in that there is a stepwise decline in cognitive ability with discrete events in contrast to Alzheimer dementia which is a gradual decline. There is no treatment for vascular dementia other than treating the underlying etiology, which would involve interventions such as treatment of hypertension and dyslipidemia and smoking cessation.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Alzheimer dementia presents with an insidious and gradual decline in cognitive function that may present initially with minor forgetfulness and can progress over years to an inability for the patient to care for themselves.Answer 2: Frontotemporal dementia is associated with memory loss and changes in personality with loss of social awareness and poor impulse control.Answer 3: Lewy body dementia presents with both dementia as well as visual hallucinations, delusions, and Parkinson-like features.Answer 4: Normal pressure hydrocephalus presents with “wacky, wet, and wobbly,” which corresponds to changes in behavior, urinary incontinence, and ataxia.', 5, 'A 77-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a change in his mental status. He is having problem with remembering things. Yesterday the patient seemed fine; however, this morning she noticed that he struggled to perform simple tasks and was forgetful while cooking, leaving the stove on. The patient has a past medical history of hypertension and diabetes. His temperature is 97.5°F (36.4°C), blood pressure is 180/120 mmHg, pulse is 90/min, respirations are 16/min, and oxygen saturation is 100% on room air. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'E', 'Alzheimer dementia', 'Frontotemporal dementia', 'Lewy body dementia', 'Normal pressure hydrocephalus', 'Vascular dementia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(192, 'multiplechoice', 26654269, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'An elderly female with dementia, urinary incontinence, and hallucinations does not have a clear diagnosis for her deficits. Since she denies any recent trauma, a MRI scan will provide the most information for diagnosis and ruling out other causes.Dementia increases in prevalence with old age. Risk factors for dementia include family history of dementia, apolipoprotein E4 genotypes, cardiovascular disease, lower educational levels, and chronic anticholinergic use. Commonly, a mini-mental exam is used to differentiate between those who have dementia or normal aging, and scores below 24/30 suggest the former. Lewy body dementia typically presents with cognitive decline along with hallucinations while dementia due to normal pressure hydrocephalus presents with the triad of ataxia, dementia, and urinary incontinence. In the case above, the patient\'s diagnosis is unclear and therefore requires a MRI to evaluate and rule out other causes.Incorrect Answers:Answer 2: The patient denies any recent falls and does not have focal neurological deficits. All of her symptoms have been present for some time and do not seem acute. Therefore, MRI is a better answer as it provides more detail.Answer 3: The patient does not have a fever or any symptoms of meningitis. A lumbar puncture may be useful when assessing CNS pressure, but an MRI should be the next test so rule out potential herniation if that is a concern.Answer 4: The patient does not present with symptoms of a malignancy and does not need a PET scan.Answer 5: The patient has no focal neurological symptoms and therefore is unlikely to require angiography for a stroke.', 'An elderly female with dementia, urinary incontinence, and hallucinations does not have a clear diagnosis for her deficits. Since she denies any recent trauma, a MRI scan will provide the most information for diagnosis and ruling out other causes.Dementia increases in prevalence with old age. Risk factors for dementia include family history of dementia, apolipoprotein E4 genotypes, cardiovascular disease, lower educational levels, and chronic anticholinergic use. Commonly, a mini-mental exam is used to differentiate between those who have dementia or normal aging, and scores below 24/30 suggest the former. Lewy body dementia typically presents with cognitive decline along with hallucinations while dementia due to normal pressure hydrocephalus presents with the triad of ataxia, dementia, and urinary incontinence. In the case above, the patient\'s diagnosis is unclear and therefore requires a MRI to evaluate and rule out other causes.Incorrect Answers:Answer 2: The patient denies any recent falls and does not have focal neurological deficits. All of her symptoms have been present for some time and do not seem acute. Therefore, MRI is a better answer as it provides more detail.Answer 3: The patient does not have a fever or any symptoms of meningitis. A lumbar puncture may be useful when assessing CNS pressure, but an MRI should be the next test so rule out potential herniation if that is a concern.Answer 4: The patient does not present with symptoms of a malignancy and does not need a PET scan.Answer 5: The patient has no focal neurological symptoms and therefore is unlikely to require angiography for a stroke.', 5, 'A 75-year-old female presents to your office with her daughter. The patient states that she feels perfectly well and that she does not know why she is present. The daughter states that over the last several years, the patient has become forgetful and recently forgot her grandchild\'s name, along with the groceries she was supposed to buy. She was also found lost 10 miles away from her house last week. The daughter also states that the patient has had urinary incontinence over the last few months and has been seeing little children in the morning that are not present. The patient denies any recent falls. Her vitals are normal and her physical exam does not reveal any focal neurological deficits. Her mini-mental status exam is scored 22/30. What is the most accurate test for this patient?', 'A', 'MRI scan of head', 'CT scan of head', 'Lumbar puncture', 'PET scan of head', 'CT angiography of head', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(193, 'multiplechoice', 26654359, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'This patient most likely has frontotemporal dementia, also known as Pick disease, given that his initial symptoms were disturbances in behavior and changes in personality, followed by worsening memory that developed later on.Frontotemporal dementia is a form of dementia characterized by atrophy of the frontal and temporal lobes. Patients typically present initially with behavioral and personality changes or disinhibition, while later symptoms may include speech disturbance, inattentiveness, compulsive behaviors, or extrapyramidal signs. Diagnosis is often clinical, but evidence of frontotemporal atrophy can be seen on magnetic resonance imaging or computed tomography.Picture is a MRI of the brain showing atrophy of the frontal and temporal lobes.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Alzheimer dementia will present with amnesia of newly acquired information as the initial symptom while distant memory usually remains intact. Additionally, patients may develop visuospatial deficits, language deficits, and steady cognitive decline associated with depression and agitation. Magnetic resonance imaging or computed tomography imaging may show diffuse cortical atrophy with enlarged ventricles. This patient\'s initial presentation of personality change and disinhibition are more consistent with frontotemporal dementia.Answer 3: Lewy body dementia is often characterized by progressive cognitive decline, visual hallucinations, and Parkinson-like movement abnormalities. Physical and cognitive symptoms may present around the same time, and psychiatric symptoms are common, including hallucinations, delusions, anxiety, and depression. Diagnosis is typically clinical, while the definitive diagnosis is achieved via brain biopsy or autopsy. This patient does not describe hallucinations or Parkinson-like movement abnormalities that would be associated with Lewy body dementia, though he is experiencing progressive cognitive decline.Answer 4: Normal pressure hydrocephalus symptoms include the classic triad of dementia, gait apraxia, and urinary incontinence. Gait is typically described as \"magnetic\", and computed tomography or magnetic resonance imaging show enlarged ventricles out of proportion to sulcal atrophy. Lumbar puncture would reveal normal cerebrospinal fluid pressures and may be therapeutic. This patient does not have the typical symptoms of gait abnormality and urinary incontinence that are associated with normal pressure hydrocephalus.Answer 5: Vascular dementia is associated with a history of cerebrovascular disease or stroke, typically manifesting as a stepwise decline in cognitive function. Symptom onset would typically be abrupt or related to a known stroke. Focal neurologic signs may be present on examination. Although this patient has some risk factors including age, hypertension, and diabetes, he has no history of stroke, and his cognitive decline is gradual rather than stepwise, making vascular dementia less likely.', 'This patient most likely has frontotemporal dementia, also known as Pick disease, given that his initial symptoms were disturbances in behavior and changes in personality, followed by worsening memory that developed later on.Frontotemporal dementia is a form of dementia characterized by atrophy of the frontal and temporal lobes. Patients typically present initially with behavioral and personality changes or disinhibition, while later symptoms may include speech disturbance, inattentiveness, compulsive behaviors, or extrapyramidal signs. Diagnosis is often clinical, but evidence of frontotemporal atrophy can be seen on magnetic resonance imaging or computed tomography.Picture is a MRI of the brain showing atrophy of the frontal and temporal lobes.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Alzheimer dementia will present with amnesia of newly acquired information as the initial symptom while distant memory usually remains intact. Additionally, patients may develop visuospatial deficits, language deficits, and steady cognitive decline associated with depression and agitation. Magnetic resonance imaging or computed tomography imaging may show diffuse cortical atrophy with enlarged ventricles. This patient\'s initial presentation of personality change and disinhibition are more consistent with frontotemporal dementia.Answer 3: Lewy body dementia is often characterized by progressive cognitive decline, visual hallucinations, and Parkinson-like movement abnormalities. Physical and cognitive symptoms may present around the same time, and psychiatric symptoms are common, including hallucinations, delusions, anxiety, and depression. Diagnosis is typically clinical, while the definitive diagnosis is achieved via brain biopsy or autopsy. This patient does not describe hallucinations or Parkinson-like movement abnormalities that would be associated with Lewy body dementia, though he is experiencing progressive cognitive decline.Answer 4: Normal pressure hydrocephalus symptoms include the classic triad of dementia, gait apraxia, and urinary incontinence. Gait is typically described as \"magnetic\", and computed tomography or magnetic resonance imaging show enlarged ventricles out of proportion to sulcal atrophy. Lumbar puncture would reveal normal cerebrospinal fluid pressures and may be therapeutic. This patient does not have the typical symptoms of gait abnormality and urinary incontinence that are associated with normal pressure hydrocephalus.Answer 5: Vascular dementia is associated with a history of cerebrovascular disease or stroke, typically manifesting as a stepwise decline in cognitive function. Symptom onset would typically be abrupt or related to a known stroke. Focal neurologic signs may be present on examination. Although this patient has some risk factors including age, hypertension, and diabetes, he has no history of stroke, and his cognitive decline is gradual rather than stepwise, making vascular dementia less likely.', 5, 'A 64-year-old man is brought to the clinic by his daughter, who is concerned that her father has not been acting himself in the past year. He has been uncharacteristically impulsive and acting inappropriately in social situations. More recently, she has noticed that he has had worsening memory and trouble with managing his finances. His past medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and benign prostatic hyperplasia. His vital signs are normal. He appears mildly disheveled and continuously eats candy out of the jar on the exam room desk throughout the interview. An MRI demonstrates the findings shown in the Figure. What is the most likely diagnosis?[cmimg]0/9406627_UWJQOPD7.jpg[/cmimg]', 'B', 'Alzheimer dementia', 'Frontotemporal dementia (Pick disease)', 'Lewy body dementia', 'Normal pressure hydrocephalus', 'Vascular dementia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(194, 'multiplechoice', 26654502, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', 'This pediatric patient is presenting with fever, irritability, and a positive Kernig sign suggesting a diagnosis of meningitis. A lumbar puncture is the best initial step in management.Meningitis in the pediatric population typically presents with fever and irritability. Specific physical exam findings that can suggest the diagnosis include meningeal signs such as a positive Kernig sign (inability to extend the knee while the hip is flexed) and Brudzinski sign (flexion of the neck results in flexion of lower extremities). For the USMLE, the best initial step in management is a lumbar puncture followed promptly by IV broad spectrum antibiotics. Once the diagnosis/infectious agent is confirmed, the antibiotic agents can be refined.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Blood and urine cultures would be appropriate initial management for a fever of unknown origin; however, this patient\'s meningeal signs suggest a CNS etiology.Answer 2: Head CT could be indicated prior to a lumbar puncture if there are signs of increased intracranial pressure (such as papilledema on fundoscopy).Answer 4: Vancomycin and ceftriaxone are an appropriate initial antibiotic regimen for meningitis in children and adults.Answer 5: Vancomycin, ceftriaxone, and prednisone are an appropriate initial regimen for meningitis in adults. Steroids have been shown to reduce inflammation and improve outcomes.', 'This pediatric patient is presenting with fever, irritability, and a positive Kernig sign suggesting a diagnosis of meningitis. A lumbar puncture is the best initial step in management.Meningitis in the pediatric population typically presents with fever and irritability. Specific physical exam findings that can suggest the diagnosis include meningeal signs such as a positive Kernig sign (inability to extend the knee while the hip is flexed) and Brudzinski sign (flexion of the neck results in flexion of lower extremities). For the USMLE, the best initial step in management is a lumbar puncture followed promptly by IV broad spectrum antibiotics. Once the diagnosis/infectious agent is confirmed, the antibiotic agents can be refined.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Blood and urine cultures would be appropriate initial management for a fever of unknown origin; however, this patient\'s meningeal signs suggest a CNS etiology.Answer 2: Head CT could be indicated prior to a lumbar puncture if there are signs of increased intracranial pressure (such as papilledema on fundoscopy).Answer 4: Vancomycin and ceftriaxone are an appropriate initial antibiotic regimen for meningitis in children and adults.Answer 5: Vancomycin, ceftriaxone, and prednisone are an appropriate initial regimen for meningitis in adults. Steroids have been shown to reduce inflammation and improve outcomes.', 5, 'A 1-year-old boy presents to the emergency department for several days of irritability and poor feeding. His parents are very concerned that he has been acting differently. The patient has an unremarkable past medical history and has been followed by a pediatrician. His temperature is 102°F (38.9°C), blood pressure is 57/38 mmHg, pulse is 170/min, respirations are 35/min, and oxygen saturation is 99% on room air. During the exam the infant is irritable and is crying. Musculoskeletal exam reveals that the patient\'s knee can not be extended while the patient\'s hip is in a flexed position without significant patient irritation. Fundoscopy is within normal limits. Abdominal, cardiac, and pulmonary exam are within normal limits. Which of the following is the next best step in management?', 'C', 'Blood and urine cultures', 'Head CT', 'Lumbar puncture', 'Vancomycin and ceftriaxone', 'Vancomycin, ceftriaxone, and prednisone', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(195, 'multiplechoice', 26659330, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'The patient is presenting with hand stiffness, joint swelling, and evidence of boutonniere deformity, which suggests the diagnosis of rheumatoid arthritis (RA). Anti-CCP is the most specific antibody for RA.Rheumatoid arthritis (RA) presents with morning stiffness, pain and swelling of the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) and proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joints as well as decreased grip strength. Some classic physical exam findings include subcutaneous rheumatoid nodules, ulnar deviation of the fingers (Illustration A), swan neck deformity (distal interphalangeal joint (DIP) flexed while PIP is hyperextended) and boutonniere deformity (PIP joint flexed while DIP is hyperextended). The most specific antibody for RA is anti-CCP.Figure illustrates a boutonniere deformity of the thumb, early ulnar deviation, and joint swelling, seen in RA.[cmimg]0/9406627_ENEK2IE8.jpg[/cmimg][cmimg]0/9406627_SYPXY6OP.jpg[/cmimg][color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 2: Anti-centromere antibody is a specific antibody for limited scleroderma or CREST syndrome.Answer 3: Antinuclear antibody is a highly sensitive antibody for systemic lupus erythematosus but is largely non-specific.Answer 3: Anti-Smith antibody is the most specific antibody for systemic lupus erythematosus.Answer 4: Rheumatoid factor can be seen in elevated levels in RA but is non-specific.', 'The patient is presenting with hand stiffness, joint swelling, and evidence of boutonniere deformity, which suggests the diagnosis of rheumatoid arthritis (RA). Anti-CCP is the most specific antibody for RA.Rheumatoid arthritis (RA) presents with morning stiffness, pain and swelling of the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) and proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joints as well as decreased grip strength. Some classic physical exam findings include subcutaneous rheumatoid nodules, ulnar deviation of the fingers (Illustration A), swan neck deformity (distal interphalangeal joint (DIP) flexed while PIP is hyperextended) and boutonniere deformity (PIP joint flexed while DIP is hyperextended). The most specific antibody for RA is anti-CCP.Figure illustrates a boutonniere deformity of the thumb, early ulnar deviation, and joint swelling, seen in RA.[cmimg]0/9406627_ENEK2IE8.jpg[/cmimg][cmimg]0/9406627_SYPXY6OP.jpg[/cmimg][color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 2: Anti-centromere antibody is a specific antibody for limited scleroderma or CREST syndrome.Answer 3: Antinuclear antibody is a highly sensitive antibody for systemic lupus erythematosus but is largely non-specific.Answer 3: Anti-Smith antibody is the most specific antibody for systemic lupus erythematosus.Answer 4: Rheumatoid factor can be seen in elevated levels in RA but is non-specific.', 5, 'A 42-year-old painter presents to the clinic with worsening arthritis. She reports that for the past 2 years she has experienced pain, swelling, and morning stiffness within the joints of her hands. The patient states that this has resulted in decreased grip strength, which is affecting her work. The patient’s only medication is ibuprofen. Physical examination shows hand deformities. The patient’s right hand is pictured in Figure A. Which of the following antibodies is the most specific for this patient’s current condition?', 'A', 'Anti-CCP antibody', 'Anti-centromere antibody', 'Antinuclear antibody', 'Anti-Smith antibody', 'Rheumatoid factor', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(196, 'multiplechoice', 26659458, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'This radiograph demonstrates complete loss of the articular cartilage at all four distal interphalangeal (DIP) joints, large osteophytes, and ankylosis of the DIP joint of the middle finger, making OA (answer 2) the most likely diagnosis.OA is a degenerative joint disease that typically occurs after age 40. The proximal interphalangeal joint (PIP)/DIP, foot, knee, and hip joints are commonly affected, while the metacarpophalangeal (MCP), shoulder, wrist, and elbow joints are rarely implicated. Symptoms include pain and stiffness that worsens with activity (and, if occurring upon awakening in the morning, lasts less than an hour). Classic radiographic findings include joint space narrowing, subchondral sclerosis, subchondral cysts, and osteophytes.While these clinical characteristics are more suggestive of OA over other arthritides, Peat et al. note that OA has no absolute clinical criteria. Thus, a clinical diagnosis of OA is supported by the presence of typical symptoms, physical examination, imaging features, and, occasionally, laboratory findings.Classic method for diagnosing OA is the presence of pain plus several clinical characteristics including being greater than 50 years old, having morning stiffness for less than 30 minutes, crepitus on active motion (especially in the knee), bony tenderness, bony enlargement, and no palpable warmth.Figure demonstrates the classic radiographic findings seen in OA.The radiographic hallmarks of primary osteoarthritis include nonuniform joint space loss, osteophyte formation, cyst formation and subchondral sclerosis. The initial radiographs may not show all of the findings. At first, only minimal, nonuniform joint space narrowing may be present.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Gouty arthritis is usually monoarticular and tophi may appear on imaging.Answer 3, 5: RA and SLE would present with constitutional symptoms and different radiographic findings.Answer 4: Psoriatic arthritis shows a pencil-in-a-cup deformity on imaging.', 'This radiograph demonstrates complete loss of the articular cartilage at all four distal interphalangeal (DIP) joints, large osteophytes, and ankylosis of the DIP joint of the middle finger, making OA (answer 2) the most likely diagnosis.OA is a degenerative joint disease that typically occurs after age 40. The proximal interphalangeal joint (PIP)/DIP, foot, knee, and hip joints are commonly affected, while the metacarpophalangeal (MCP), shoulder, wrist, and elbow joints are rarely implicated. Symptoms include pain and stiffness that worsens with activity (and, if occurring upon awakening in the morning, lasts less than an hour). Classic radiographic findings include joint space narrowing, subchondral sclerosis, subchondral cysts, and osteophytes.While these clinical characteristics are more suggestive of OA over other arthritides, Peat et al. note that OA has no absolute clinical criteria. Thus, a clinical diagnosis of OA is supported by the presence of typical symptoms, physical examination, imaging features, and, occasionally, laboratory findings.Classic method for diagnosing OA is the presence of pain plus several clinical characteristics including being greater than 50 years old, having morning stiffness for less than 30 minutes, crepitus on active motion (especially in the knee), bony tenderness, bony enlargement, and no palpable warmth.Figure demonstrates the classic radiographic findings seen in OA.The radiographic hallmarks of primary osteoarthritis include nonuniform joint space loss, osteophyte formation, cyst formation and subchondral sclerosis. The initial radiographs may not show all of the findings. At first, only minimal, nonuniform joint space narrowing may be present.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Gouty arthritis is usually monoarticular and tophi may appear on imaging.Answer 3, 5: RA and SLE would present with constitutional symptoms and different radiographic findings.Answer 4: Psoriatic arthritis shows a pencil-in-a-cup deformity on imaging.', 5, 'A 67-year-old male with no significant medical history comes to your office complaining of pain and stiffness in his hands upon wakening in the morning. You perform an x-ray. What is the most likely diagnosis?[cmimg]0/9406627_EG4VZ9WU.jpg[/cmimg]', 'B', 'Gouty arthritis', 'Osteoarthritis (OA)', 'Rheumatoid arthritis (RA)', 'Psoriatic arthritis', 'Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
