(197, 'multiplechoice', 26660076, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'A 39-year-old woman with a rash around her eyes (heliotrope rash), along with a rash on her shoulders (shawl sign), elevated CK, ESR, and ferritin, in the setting of proximal muscle weakness is most likely suffering from dermatomyositis.Dermatomyositis is an inflammatory myopathy with characteristic skin manifestations involving the eyes, the upper neck and shoulders, and the dorsum of hands. It has an association with other connective tissue disorders along with a higher risk of future and concurrent malignancy. Patient management includes long-term physical therapy along with antihistamines, sunscreen for the rashes, and oral corticosteroids for musculoskeletal pain. The goal of therapy is typically to maintain function without significant side effects.[cmimg]0/9406627_6FLR5PMD.jpg[/cmimg][color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Inclusion body myositis typically affects distal forearm and arm muscles and may cause bulbar symptoms of dysphagia.Answers 2 and 3: The patient may have corticosteroid or statin induced myopathy, but her heliotrope rash (around the eyes) and the shawl sign are more typical of an inflammatory myositis.Answer 5: Polymyositis also commonly affects proximal muscles and results in weakness, but it more commonly affects the lungs and the GI tract. It also does not present with a rash.', 'A 39-year-old woman with a rash around her eyes (heliotrope rash), along with a rash on her shoulders (shawl sign), elevated CK, ESR, and ferritin, in the setting of proximal muscle weakness is most likely suffering from dermatomyositis.Dermatomyositis is an inflammatory myopathy with characteristic skin manifestations involving the eyes, the upper neck and shoulders, and the dorsum of hands. It has an association with other connective tissue disorders along with a higher risk of future and concurrent malignancy. Patient management includes long-term physical therapy along with antihistamines, sunscreen for the rashes, and oral corticosteroids for musculoskeletal pain. The goal of therapy is typically to maintain function without significant side effects.[cmimg]0/9406627_6FLR5PMD.jpg[/cmimg][color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Inclusion body myositis typically affects distal forearm and arm muscles and may cause bulbar symptoms of dysphagia.Answers 2 and 3: The patient may have corticosteroid or statin induced myopathy, but her heliotrope rash (around the eyes) and the shawl sign are more typical of an inflammatory myositis.Answer 5: Polymyositis also commonly affects proximal muscles and results in weakness, but it more commonly affects the lungs and the GI tract. It also does not present with a rash.', 5, 'A 39-year-old woman comes into your office with multiple complaints of recent onset. She has been feeling fatigued and has started having leg and thigh pain bilaterally, along with weakness and mild muscle wasting in proximal part of hand. In addition, she states that she recently started noticing some redness around her eyes along with a rash on her shoulders. Of note, she takes simvastatin for her hyperlipidemia, and took a short course of steroids recently for an allergic reaction. Her vitals are within normal limits. Her CK is 400 U/L, ESR is 70 mm/hr, and ferritin is 500 mcg/L. What is the most likely diagnosis?', 'D', 'Inclusion body myositis', 'Corticosteroid induced myopathy', 'Statin induced myopathy', 'Dermatomyositis', 'Polymyositis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(198, 'multiplechoice', 26660373, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'This vignette describes an antepartum patient presenting with premature rupture of membranes, painless vaginal bleeding, and fetal decelerations and bradycardia suggestive of vasa previa. In the setting of vasa previa, treatment requires immediate cesarean section.Vasa previa can present with painless vaginal bleeding, which if prolonged can lead to fetal hypoxemia and demise. Risk factors include previous abnormal placental attachment and history of cesarean section. It can be detected early using ultrasound in high-risk patients, for whom elective surgical delivery should be offered. Emergency cesarean section will be necessary to rescue the fetus and remove the placenta.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Betamethasone is indicated to support fetal maturation when premature delivery is expected at 28 to 32 weeks. More urgent, however, is the ultimate delivery of the fetus.Answer 3: Pudendal nerve blockade is often performed during the second stage of labor (pushing) for analgesia. It would not provide meaningful anesthesia for a cesarean section. Depending on the parturient\'s risks of emergent induction of general anesthesia (specifically risks of airway compromise or aspiration), emergent cesarean sections can be performed under general anesthesia, spinal anesthesia, or epidural anesthesia.Answer 4: Red blood cell transfusion would not be needed in this case as this patient\'s vitals are stable and she has not had significant blood loss.Answer 5: Vaginal delivery with or without induction of labor can be offered if fetal death occurs in the setting of vasa previa.', 'This vignette describes an antepartum patient presenting with premature rupture of membranes, painless vaginal bleeding, and fetal decelerations and bradycardia suggestive of vasa previa. In the setting of vasa previa, treatment requires immediate cesarean section.Vasa previa can present with painless vaginal bleeding, which if prolonged can lead to fetal hypoxemia and demise. Risk factors include previous abnormal placental attachment and history of cesarean section. It can be detected early using ultrasound in high-risk patients, for whom elective surgical delivery should be offered. Emergency cesarean section will be necessary to rescue the fetus and remove the placenta.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Betamethasone is indicated to support fetal maturation when premature delivery is expected at 28 to 32 weeks. More urgent, however, is the ultimate delivery of the fetus.Answer 3: Pudendal nerve blockade is often performed during the second stage of labor (pushing) for analgesia. It would not provide meaningful anesthesia for a cesarean section. Depending on the parturient\'s risks of emergent induction of general anesthesia (specifically risks of airway compromise or aspiration), emergent cesarean sections can be performed under general anesthesia, spinal anesthesia, or epidural anesthesia.Answer 4: Red blood cell transfusion would not be needed in this case as this patient\'s vitals are stable and she has not had significant blood loss.Answer 5: Vaginal delivery with or without induction of labor can be offered if fetal death occurs in the setting of vasa previa.', 5, 'A 25-year-old at 32 weeks gestation presents to the hospital with painless vaginal bleeding. The patient states that she was taking care of laundry at home when she experienced a sudden sensation of her water breaking and saw that her groin was covered in blood. Her prenatal history is unremarkable according to the clinic records, but she has not seen an obstetrician for the past 14 weeks. Her previous delivery was by urgent cesarean section for placenta previa. Her temperature is 95°F (35°C), blood pressure is 125/75 mmHg, pulse is 79/min. Cervical exam shows gross blood in the vaginal os. The fetal head is not palpable. Fetal heart rate monitoring demonstrates decelerations and bradycardia. Labs are pending. IV fluids are started. What is the best step in management?', 'B', 'Betamethasone', 'Cesarean section', 'Pudendal nerve block', 'Red blood cell transfusion', 'Vaginal delivery', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(199, 'multiplechoice', 26660871, 'Generic Parent', 'ENT', 'No', 'This patient is presenting with vertigo that is positional (as he is going to bed) that is subsequently exacerbated by the Dix-Hallpike maneuver suggesting a diagnosis of benign paroxysmal positional vertigo.Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV) presents with vertigo that is positional (such as occurring at night when the patient lays down to sleep or sits up rapidly). Situations when it can occur include when a patient experiences a position change such as going to bed or waking up. Patients are often asymptomatic between episodes; however, the Dix-Hallpike maneuver can reposition the otoliths causing acute symptoms. Subsequently, BPPV can be treated with the Epley maneuver. Patients can have their symptoms controlled with anticholinergics such as meclizine and can be taught the Epley maneuver to perform on their own.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 2: Labyrinthitis presents with symptoms of continuous vertigo after a viral illness; however, hearing loss is also present thus differentiating it from vestibular neuritis.Answer 3: Meniere disease presents with vertigo in a relapsing and remitting fashion with tinnitus, unilateral hearing loss, and a sensation of fullness in the affected ear. Symptoms are episodic in nature often with continuous hearing loss/ear fullness.Answer 4: Vertebrobasilar stroke would present in a high risk patient (elderly, diabetes, hypertension, and peripheral vascular disease) with continuous neurological deficits including vertigo. The diagnosis can further be worked up with a MRI.Answer 5: Vestibular neuritis presents with vertigo after a viral infection (or secondary to an inflammatory process) without hearing loss (thus differentiating it from labyrinthitis). The only treatment needed is symptomatic (such as diphenhydramine) as this condition self-resolves.', 'This patient is presenting with vertigo that is positional (as he is going to bed) that is subsequently exacerbated by the Dix-Hallpike maneuver suggesting a diagnosis of benign paroxysmal positional vertigo.Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV) presents with vertigo that is positional (such as occurring at night when the patient lays down to sleep or sits up rapidly). Situations when it can occur include when a patient experiences a position change such as going to bed or waking up. Patients are often asymptomatic between episodes; however, the Dix-Hallpike maneuver can reposition the otoliths causing acute symptoms. Subsequently, BPPV can be treated with the Epley maneuver. Patients can have their symptoms controlled with anticholinergics such as meclizine and can be taught the Epley maneuver to perform on their own.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 2: Labyrinthitis presents with symptoms of continuous vertigo after a viral illness; however, hearing loss is also present thus differentiating it from vestibular neuritis.Answer 3: Meniere disease presents with vertigo in a relapsing and remitting fashion with tinnitus, unilateral hearing loss, and a sensation of fullness in the affected ear. Symptoms are episodic in nature often with continuous hearing loss/ear fullness.Answer 4: Vertebrobasilar stroke would present in a high risk patient (elderly, diabetes, hypertension, and peripheral vascular disease) with continuous neurological deficits including vertigo. The diagnosis can further be worked up with a MRI.Answer 5: Vestibular neuritis presents with vertigo after a viral infection (or secondary to an inflammatory process) without hearing loss (thus differentiating it from labyrinthitis). The only treatment needed is symptomatic (such as diphenhydramine) as this condition self-resolves.', 5, 'A 59-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a sudden-onset sensation that the room is spinning causing him to experience several episodes of nausea and vomiting. Upon arriving, the patient’s symptoms have resolved. He states his symptoms occurred as he was going to bed. His vital signs are normal. Physical exam is unremarkanle. The patient has a physiologic nystagmus and his cranial nerve exam is unremarkable. The patient’s head is turned to the left and he is laid back on the stretcher, which exacerbates severe symptoms with a nystagmus notable. The patient’s symptoms improve after 2 minutes of being in this position. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'A', 'Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo', 'Labyrinthitis', 'Meniere disease', 'Vertebrobasilar stroke', 'Vestibular neuritis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(200, 'multiplechoice', 26661125, 'Generic Parent', 'ENT', 'No', 'This patient\'s episodic true vertigo, sensorineural hearing loss, and tinnitus are characteristic for Meniere disease.Meniere disease is characterized by paroxysmal “attacks” of vertigo, along with fluctuating tinnitus and sensorineural hearing loss. It is believed that these symptoms are secondary to endolymphatic hydrops, where there is an increased endolymph volume with subsequent distention of the endolymphatic system. This increased endolymph volume explains the fullness sensation within the ear. Vertigo can last several minutes to hours and can result in nausea and vomiting. These “attacks” vary in frequency and severity and may result in abrupt falls in a small percentage of patients.[cmimg]0/9406627_WCNYFGD9.png[/cmimg][color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo is less likely given that the vertigo episodes are much shorter (10-20 seconds) and are positional.Answer 3: Migraines can result in episodes of vertigo; however, the patient will likely have a migraine headache during vertigo. In these patients, one also would not find inner ear fullness or sensorineural hearing loss.Answer 4: Transient ischemic attack is usually shorter than Meniere attacks. Also, patients rarely present with dizziness, persistent tinnitus, or hearing loss.Answer 5: Vestibular neuritis is characterized by vertigo, nystagmus, and falling towards the side of the lesion. It typically occurs in post- or peri-infection periods. Patients with this condition do not have hearing loss.', 'This patient\'s episodic true vertigo, sensorineural hearing loss, and tinnitus are characteristic for Meniere disease.Meniere disease is characterized by paroxysmal “attacks” of vertigo, along with fluctuating tinnitus and sensorineural hearing loss. It is believed that these symptoms are secondary to endolymphatic hydrops, where there is an increased endolymph volume with subsequent distention of the endolymphatic system. This increased endolymph volume explains the fullness sensation within the ear. Vertigo can last several minutes to hours and can result in nausea and vomiting. These “attacks” vary in frequency and severity and may result in abrupt falls in a small percentage of patients.[cmimg]0/9406627_WCNYFGD9.png[/cmimg][color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo is less likely given that the vertigo episodes are much shorter (10-20 seconds) and are positional.Answer 3: Migraines can result in episodes of vertigo; however, the patient will likely have a migraine headache during vertigo. In these patients, one also would not find inner ear fullness or sensorineural hearing loss.Answer 4: Transient ischemic attack is usually shorter than Meniere attacks. Also, patients rarely present with dizziness, persistent tinnitus, or hearing loss.Answer 5: Vestibular neuritis is characterized by vertigo, nystagmus, and falling towards the side of the lesion. It typically occurs in post- or peri-infection periods. Patients with this condition do not have hearing loss.', 5, 'A 56-year-old woman presents to her primary care physician for dizziness. She says that her symptoms began approximately 1 month prior to presentation and are associated with nausea and ringing of the ears. She describes her dizziness as a spinning sensation that has a start and end and lasts approximately 25 minutes. This dizziness is severe enough that she cannot walk or stand. Medical history is significant for a migraine with aura treated with zolmitriptan, type 2 diabetes managed with metformin, and hypertension managed with lisinopril. Her vital signs are normal. On physical exam, when words are whispered into her right ear, she is unable to repeat the whispered words aloud; however, this is normal in the left ear.  Air conduction is greater than bone conduction with Rinne testing, and the sound of the tuning fork is loudest in the left ear on Weber testing. Which of the following is most likely the diagnosis?', 'B', 'Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo', 'Meniere disease', 'Migraine', 'Transient ischemic attack', 'Vestibular neuritis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(201, 'multiplechoice', 26664699, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', '[color=#0000FF]Clinical features[/color]• Adolescent 10–15 years, often obese• Most common in the oversized and undersexed (e.g. the heavy prepubertal boy)• Bilateral in 20%• Limp and irritability of hip on movement• Anterior hip (groin) pain• Knee pain• Hip rotating into external rotation on flexion and often lies in external rotation (ER)• Most movements restricted, especially IRAny adolescent with a limp or knee pain should have X-rays (AP and frog view) of both hips. Otherwise, this important condition will be overlooked. SCFE is graded I to IV.One problem of the displaced capital epiphysis of the femoral head (SCFE) is when some patients develop avascular necrosis despite expert treatment. Diagnosis of the condition before major slipping is important. This necessitates early consultation with the teenager experiencing hip or knee discomfort and then accurate interpretation of X-rays.[cmimg]0/9406627_JRDQIZSO.png[/cmimg]', '[color=#0000FF]Clinical features[/color]• Adolescent 10–15 years, often obese• Most common in the oversized and undersexed (e.g. the heavy prepubertal boy)• Bilateral in 20%• Limp and irritability of hip on movement• Anterior hip (groin) pain• Knee pain• Hip rotating into external rotation on flexion and often lies in external rotation (ER)• Most movements restricted, especially IRAny adolescent with a limp or knee pain should have X-rays (AP and frog view) of both hips. Otherwise, this important condition will be overlooked. SCFE is graded I to IV.One problem of the displaced capital epiphysis of the femoral head (SCFE) is when some patients develop avascular necrosis despite expert treatment. Diagnosis of the condition before major slipping is important. This necessitates early consultation with the teenager experiencing hip or knee discomfort and then accurate interpretation of X-rays.[cmimg]0/9406627_JRDQIZSO.png[/cmimg]', 5, 'A 13-year-old boy presents with pain in his left groin, hip, and thigh. His mother notices a limp when he walks. The patient denies any recent significant trauma to his left lower extremity. On physical exam, his gait is antalgic. With the patient in the supine position, there is external rotation and abduction of the thigh with passive flexion of the hip.What is the most probable diagnosis?', 'E', 'Legg-Calve-Perthes disease', 'Transient Synovitis of Hip', 'Septic arthritis', 'Developmental dysplasia of the hip', 'Slipped Capital Femoral Epiphysis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(202, 'multiplechoice', 26664802, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', 'This patient is presenting with mild hip pain after a viral infection suggesting a diagnosis of transient synovitis of the hip. This pathology only requires conservative therapy (NSAIDs and rest) and tends to self-resolve.Transient synovitis of the hip presents with hip pain, worse with weight-bearing. The symptoms of transient synovitis of the hip tend to occur after a viral infection and are less severe than septic arthritis. Management includes conservative therapy including NSAIDs (for acute symptoms) and rest.[cmimg]0/9406627_0ZDZWFY0.png[/cmimg][color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answers 1-3: Radiography followed by CT scan/MRI would be indicated for ruling out trauma or avascular necrosis to the hip. This patient\'s mild symptoms occurring after a viral infection make transient synovitis of the hip a more likely diagnosis (the question asked for management of the most likely diagnosis).Answer 4: Aspiration and broad spectrum antibiotics would be appropriate management of septic arthritis, which would present with joint pain, an antalgic gain, and a hot/inflamed joint. This diagnosis is certainly possible, but is less likely in this patient given his symptoms.', 'This patient is presenting with mild hip pain after a viral infection suggesting a diagnosis of transient synovitis of the hip. This pathology only requires conservative therapy (NSAIDs and rest) and tends to self-resolve.Transient synovitis of the hip presents with hip pain, worse with weight-bearing. The symptoms of transient synovitis of the hip tend to occur after a viral infection and are less severe than septic arthritis. Management includes conservative therapy including NSAIDs (for acute symptoms) and rest.[cmimg]0/9406627_0ZDZWFY0.png[/cmimg][color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answers 1-3: Radiography followed by CT scan/MRI would be indicated for ruling out trauma or avascular necrosis to the hip. This patient\'s mild symptoms occurring after a viral infection make transient synovitis of the hip a more likely diagnosis (the question asked for management of the most likely diagnosis).Answer 4: Aspiration and broad spectrum antibiotics would be appropriate management of septic arthritis, which would present with joint pain, an antalgic gain, and a hot/inflamed joint. This diagnosis is certainly possible, but is less likely in this patient given his symptoms.', 5, 'A 6-year-old boy presents to his primary care physician with sudden hip pain that started this morning. The patient recently recovered from a upper respiratory infection that he caught from his siblings but has otherwise been healthy. His vital signs are normal. Inspection of the hip reveals no abnormalities or swelling. The hip exhibits a limited range of all movement with pain. Which of the following is the best next step in management for this patient\'s most likely diagnosis?', 'E', 'Radiography', 'CT scan', 'MRI', 'Aspiration and broad spectrum antibiotics', 'Ibuprofen and rest', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(203, 'multiplechoice', 26665488, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', 'This patient is presenting with a morbiliform rash in the setting of recently starting a new medication (ibuprofen) suggesting that this is a morbiliform rash from a drug reaction.A morbiliform rash presents with macular lesions that are red, small, and sometimes confluent in places. This rash looks very similar to the rash of measles and rubella, but is not associated with systemic symptoms. Many medications can cause this rash, including NSAIDs, sulfa-drugs, and anti-epileptics. The treatment of choice is to remove the offending agent.Figure demonstrates a morbiliform rash that could be seen with drug exposure or in measles/rubella.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Measles could present with a rash like this but would also present with systemic symptoms, as well as cough, conjunctivitis, coryza, and Koplik\'s spots. The rash begins behind the ears; on the first day it spreads to the face, the next day to the trunk and later to the limbs. It may become confluent and blanches under pressure. The patient’s fever usually subsides within 5 days of the onset of the rash.Answer 2: Rubella would present with a rash similar to this but would also present with systemic symptoms, in particular, postauricular lymphadenopathy, arthralgias, and a spreading of the rash that starts on the face and spreads centrifugally.[cmimg]0/9406627_6BKCXXDV.png[/cmimg]Answer 3: Atopic dermatitis presents with intense pruritus and red, itchy plaques over the flexor surfaces.Answer 4: Urticaria presents with elevated papules or plaques which are erythematous and pruritic. It can occur in response to a new medication but would appear different from a morbiliform rash.', 'This patient is presenting with a morbiliform rash in the setting of recently starting a new medication (ibuprofen) suggesting that this is a morbiliform rash from a drug reaction.A morbiliform rash presents with macular lesions that are red, small, and sometimes confluent in places. This rash looks very similar to the rash of measles and rubella, but is not associated with systemic symptoms. Many medications can cause this rash, including NSAIDs, sulfa-drugs, and anti-epileptics. The treatment of choice is to remove the offending agent.Figure demonstrates a morbiliform rash that could be seen with drug exposure or in measles/rubella.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Measles could present with a rash like this but would also present with systemic symptoms, as well as cough, conjunctivitis, coryza, and Koplik\'s spots. The rash begins behind the ears; on the first day it spreads to the face, the next day to the trunk and later to the limbs. It may become confluent and blanches under pressure. The patient’s fever usually subsides within 5 days of the onset of the rash.Answer 2: Rubella would present with a rash similar to this but would also present with systemic symptoms, in particular, postauricular lymphadenopathy, arthralgias, and a spreading of the rash that starts on the face and spreads centrifugally.[cmimg]0/9406627_6BKCXXDV.png[/cmimg]Answer 3: Atopic dermatitis presents with intense pruritus and red, itchy plaques over the flexor surfaces.Answer 4: Urticaria presents with elevated papules or plaques which are erythematous and pruritic. It can occur in response to a new medication but would appear different from a morbiliform rash.', 5, 'A 13-year-old male presents to his primary care physician for a rash.  The patient states that he discovered the rash when he woke up this morning.  The patient has a past medical history of asthma and seasonal allergies. He recently visited his physician for pain associated with running and was prescribed ibuprofen. His temperature is 99.5°F (37.5°C), blood pressure is 120/80 mmHg, pulse is 71/min, respirations are 12/min, and oxygen saturation is 99% on room air.  On physical exam you note the findings in Figure. The patient\'s cardiac exam is notable for a physiologic murmur. Which of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\'s presentation?[cmimg]0/9406627_K6N4OE5Z.jpg[/cmimg]', 'E', 'Measles', 'Rubella', 'Atopic dermatitis', 'Uticaria', 'Drug reaction', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(204, 'multiplechoice', 26665553, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', 'This patient is presenting with a low-grade fever, cold-like symptoms, a characteristic rash (with macules and papules), and is well appearing suggesting a diagnosis of rubella.Rubella is caused by the rubella virus (a togavirus) that is transmitted via respiratory droplets following an incubation period of 14-21 days. Prior to the appearance of the rash, patients typically experience the prodrome of malaise, mild conjunctivitis, low-grade fever, adenopathy, and cold symptoms. The rash begins on the face as pink macules. After 1 day, the rash typically spreads to the trunk and extremities. In contrast to measles, these patients are usually well appearing and have symptoms that begin to resolve around day 3.Figure: is the rash with pink macules/papules that are commonly seen in rubella.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Kawasaki disease is characterized by \"CRASH and burn\" corresponding to symptoms of conjunctivitis, rash, adenopathy, strawberry tongue, and hand/foot desquamation with a fever.Answer 2: Parvovirus can present with \"slapped-cheek fever\" in children, minor arthralgias in adults, and aplastic crisis in patients with hereditary spherocytosis/sickle cell anemia.Answer 4: Rubeola or measles presents with a cough, conjunctivitis, coryza, and Koplik spots on the buccal mucosa. Usually, these patients have a high fever and become progressively more ill in contrast to rubella, where patients have mild symptoms and tend to improve around day 3.Answer 5: Roseola is caused by human herpesvirus 6 and presents with a high fever (which can cause febrile seizures) followed by resolution of the fever then a maculopapular rash.', 'This patient is presenting with a low-grade fever, cold-like symptoms, a characteristic rash (with macules and papules), and is well appearing suggesting a diagnosis of rubella.Rubella is caused by the rubella virus (a togavirus) that is transmitted via respiratory droplets following an incubation period of 14-21 days. Prior to the appearance of the rash, patients typically experience the prodrome of malaise, mild conjunctivitis, low-grade fever, adenopathy, and cold symptoms. The rash begins on the face as pink macules. After 1 day, the rash typically spreads to the trunk and extremities. In contrast to measles, these patients are usually well appearing and have symptoms that begin to resolve around day 3.Figure: is the rash with pink macules/papules that are commonly seen in rubella.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Kawasaki disease is characterized by \"CRASH and burn\" corresponding to symptoms of conjunctivitis, rash, adenopathy, strawberry tongue, and hand/foot desquamation with a fever.Answer 2: Parvovirus can present with \"slapped-cheek fever\" in children, minor arthralgias in adults, and aplastic crisis in patients with hereditary spherocytosis/sickle cell anemia.Answer 4: Rubeola or measles presents with a cough, conjunctivitis, coryza, and Koplik spots on the buccal mucosa. Usually, these patients have a high fever and become progressively more ill in contrast to rubella, where patients have mild symptoms and tend to improve around day 3.Answer 5: Roseola is caused by human herpesvirus 6 and presents with a high fever (which can cause febrile seizures) followed by resolution of the fever then a maculopapular rash.', 5, 'A 7-year-old boy presents to an urgent care center for a rash that began approximately 2 days ago.  According to his mother, it began as a pink rash on his face and has subsequently spread to his trunk.  The child was adopted and has not yet begun care with his pediatrician.  His temperature is 100.2°F (37.9°C), blood pressure is 100/70 mmHg, pulse is 99/min, respirations are 19/min, and oxygen saturation is 99% on room air. Physical exam is notable for the rash in Figure and posterior auricular lymphadenopathy.  The child is otherwise interactive and is quietly playing with toys.  Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?[cmimg]0/9406627_KII4RR9N.jpg[/cmimg]', 'C', 'Kawasaki disease', 'Parvovirus', 'Rubella', 'Rubeola', 'Roseola', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(205, 'multiplechoice', 26666098, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', 'Dx: ChickenpoxThe classic symptom of chickenpox is a rash that turns into itchy, fluid-filled blisters that eventually turn into scabs. The rash may first show up on the chest, back, and face, and then spread over the entire body, including inside the mouth, eyelids, or genital area. It usually takes about one week for all of the blisters to become scabs.[color=#FF0000]It is not Impetigo[/color].Impetigo rash usually appears around the mouth.[cmimg]0/9406627_RYV146DM.jpg[/cmimg]', 'Dx: ChickenpoxThe classic symptom of chickenpox is a rash that turns into itchy, fluid-filled blisters that eventually turn into scabs. The rash may first show up on the chest, back, and face, and then spread over the entire body, including inside the mouth, eyelids, or genital area. It usually takes about one week for all of the blisters to become scabs.[color=#FF0000]It is not Impetigo[/color].Impetigo rash usually appears around the mouth.[cmimg]0/9406627_RYV146DM.jpg[/cmimg]', 5, 'A 3-year-old girl is brought to the urgent care clinic for a rash. She attends daycare, where several other children had a similar rash and fever about 2 weeks ago. The patient began having a fever last night, and the itchy rash erupted this morning on the head and chest. On physical exam, she has multiple vesicles on her face, chest, and back, as well as excoriations from scratching.What is the cause of these presentations?[cmimg]0/9406627_5SNJ2XPW.jpg[/cmimg]', 'A', 'Chickenpox', 'Impetigo', 'Measles', 'Rubella', 'Contact dermatitis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(206, 'multiplechoice', 26666244, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', 'This 3-day old infant is experiencing jaundice due to insufficient nutritional intake, known as \"breastfeeding jaundice\". This type of indirect hyperbilirubinemia occurs when inadequate intake leads to infrequent bowel movements, leading to decreased excretion of bilirubin from the body.Neonates are physiologically predisposed to develop jaundice. Breastfeeding jaundice presents in the first week of life and is caused by inadequate nutritional intake, which leads to dehydration, an insufficient number of bowel movements, and decreased excretion of bilirubin. Neonates are expected to lose 5-7% of their birth weight within the first week of life, but a greater than 10% weight loss is abnormal. The treatment is increased dietary intake. In contrast, breast milk jaundice begins after days 4-7 of life. The cause of breast milk jaundice is not completely understood, but it is thought to be related to high levels of B-glucuronidase and lipase within breast milk. No specific intervention is needed for breast milk jaundice, and continued breast milk feeding is recommended. (Note, neonates will need to be fed every 2-3 hours, will consume about 2-3 ounces of milk, and will tend to latch on average between 10-15 minutes on each breast.)[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 2: As discussed above, breast milk jaundice typically appears in the first 3-5 days of life and is caused by inadequate liver enzyme activity. As these infants are being fed an appropriate amount, they typically appear healthy and active without signs of dehydration.Answer 3: Gilbert syndrome is a genetic disorder in which there is decreased glucuronidation activity in the liver, leading to unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia. The average age of onset is 21 years of life.Answer 4: Jaundice from ABO incompatibility typically appears within the first 24-48 hours of life.Answer 5: Biliary atresia often not evident until 2-4 weeks of life. If this patient\'s symptoms did not resolve with increased nutritional intake, biliary atresia would be a reasonable diagnosis to work up. Hepatomegaly is frequently noted.', 'This 3-day old infant is experiencing jaundice due to insufficient nutritional intake, known as \"breastfeeding jaundice\". This type of indirect hyperbilirubinemia occurs when inadequate intake leads to infrequent bowel movements, leading to decreased excretion of bilirubin from the body.Neonates are physiologically predisposed to develop jaundice. Breastfeeding jaundice presents in the first week of life and is caused by inadequate nutritional intake, which leads to dehydration, an insufficient number of bowel movements, and decreased excretion of bilirubin. Neonates are expected to lose 5-7% of their birth weight within the first week of life, but a greater than 10% weight loss is abnormal. The treatment is increased dietary intake. In contrast, breast milk jaundice begins after days 4-7 of life. The cause of breast milk jaundice is not completely understood, but it is thought to be related to high levels of B-glucuronidase and lipase within breast milk. No specific intervention is needed for breast milk jaundice, and continued breast milk feeding is recommended. (Note, neonates will need to be fed every 2-3 hours, will consume about 2-3 ounces of milk, and will tend to latch on average between 10-15 minutes on each breast.)[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 2: As discussed above, breast milk jaundice typically appears in the first 3-5 days of life and is caused by inadequate liver enzyme activity. As these infants are being fed an appropriate amount, they typically appear healthy and active without signs of dehydration.Answer 3: Gilbert syndrome is a genetic disorder in which there is decreased glucuronidation activity in the liver, leading to unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia. The average age of onset is 21 years of life.Answer 4: Jaundice from ABO incompatibility typically appears within the first 24-48 hours of life.Answer 5: Biliary atresia often not evident until 2-4 weeks of life. If this patient\'s symptoms did not resolve with increased nutritional intake, biliary atresia would be a reasonable diagnosis to work up. Hepatomegaly is frequently noted.', 5, 'A 3-day old baby boy is brought to the pediatrician by his mother for his first post-natal visit. He was born via vaginal delivery at 39.2 weeks with Apgar scores of 7 and 9 at 1 and 5 minutes, respectively. The mother\'s pregnancy was uncomplicated. He stayed in the well-baby nursery for two nights and was discharged without incident. On physical exam, the neonate appears lethargic with a soft, open fontanelle and soft abdomen. His skin is notable for a yellowish tinge. Mom is exclusively feeding him breastmilk for 5-10 minutes every 4 hours. At birth his weight was 7lbs 6oz and his current weight is down to 6lbs 8oz. What process is most likely causing his skin yellowing?', 'A', 'Breastfeeding jaundice', 'Breast milk jaundice', 'Gilbert\'s syndrome', 'ABO incompatibility', 'Bilitary atresia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(207, 'multiplechoice', 26666367, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', 'This patient\'s presentation is consistent with hypertrophic pyloric stenosis. Hypertrophic pyloric stenosis occurs secondary to thickening of the pylorus muscle with resultant gastric outlet obstruction.Hypertrophic pyloric stenosis typically presents between 4-6 weeks of life and is more common in first-born male patients. Symptoms include a palpable, movable mass in the right side of the epigastrium, non-bilious vomiting after most or every feeding, weight loss, failure to thrive, and abdominal pain. Patients may present with dehydration and electrolyte imbalances if left untreated.Some research found the relationship of oral erythromycin and hypertrophic pyloric stenosis. They found that infants who are exposed to oral erythromycin within the first two weeks of life have a significantly increased risk of developing hypertrophic pyloric stenosis. This relationship is hypothesized to be related to the action of erythromycin on motilin receptors in the pylorus.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Gastroesophageal reflux in infants presents with spitting and emesis after feeding without any other pathology.Answer 3: Milk-protein allergy may present with vomiting, blood in stool, or anemia.Answer 4: Midgut volvulus presents with bilious vomiting and sudden acute abdominal pain.Answer 5: Instussusception presents with vomiting, intermittent acute abdominal pain, and bloody stool typically between 5-9 months of age. A right upper quadrant mass is sometimes palpated.', 'This patient\'s presentation is consistent with hypertrophic pyloric stenosis. Hypertrophic pyloric stenosis occurs secondary to thickening of the pylorus muscle with resultant gastric outlet obstruction.Hypertrophic pyloric stenosis typically presents between 4-6 weeks of life and is more common in first-born male patients. Symptoms include a palpable, movable mass in the right side of the epigastrium, non-bilious vomiting after most or every feeding, weight loss, failure to thrive, and abdominal pain. Patients may present with dehydration and electrolyte imbalances if left untreated.Some research found the relationship of oral erythromycin and hypertrophic pyloric stenosis. They found that infants who are exposed to oral erythromycin within the first two weeks of life have a significantly increased risk of developing hypertrophic pyloric stenosis. This relationship is hypothesized to be related to the action of erythromycin on motilin receptors in the pylorus.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Gastroesophageal reflux in infants presents with spitting and emesis after feeding without any other pathology.Answer 3: Milk-protein allergy may present with vomiting, blood in stool, or anemia.Answer 4: Midgut volvulus presents with bilious vomiting and sudden acute abdominal pain.Answer 5: Instussusception presents with vomiting, intermittent acute abdominal pain, and bloody stool typically between 5-9 months of age. A right upper quadrant mass is sometimes palpated.', 5, 'A 5-week-old male infant is brought to the Emergency Department with the complaint of vomiting. His parents state he has been unable to keep normal feedings down for the past week and now has projectile non-bilious vomiting after each meal. Physical examination is significant for sunken fontanelles and dry mucous membranes. A palpable, ball shaped mass is noted just to the right of the epigastrium. Which of the following conditions is most likely in this patient?', 'B', 'Gastroesophageal reflux', 'Hypertrophic pyloric stenosis', 'Milk-protein allergy', 'Midgut volvulus', 'Intussusception', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(208, 'multiplechoice', 26666552, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', 'This pediatric patient presents with features of Down syndrome (trisomy 21), bilious vomiting, and colonic distention on abdominal radiograph, which suggests a diagnosis of Hirschsprung disease.Hirschsprung disease is associated with Down syndrome and presents with bilious vomiting, failure to pass meconium in the first 48 hours of life, and abdominal distension. Digital rectal exam may temporarily relieve the obstruction and lead to expulsion of gas and stool (the “squirt sign”). Abdominal radiograph typically demonstrates signs of distal intestinal obstruction such as proximal dilation and an absence of air in the rectum. Contrast enema may reveal a transition zone between the dilated proximal megacolon and the narrow rectosigmoid colon.Figure demonstrates colonic distension on abdominal radiograph, which is consistent with a diagnosis of Hirschsprung disease. Illustration demonstrates the \"double bubble\" sign of duodenal atresia, which reflects air in both the stomach and first portion of the duodenum.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Duodenal atresia is associated with Down syndrome (trisomy 21) and may also present in the first 48 hours of life with bilious vomiting. However, abdominal radiograph will demonstrate the “[color=#0000FF][b]double bubble[/b][/color]” sign, which reflects air trapping in the stomach and first portion of the duodenum.[cmimg]0/9406627_ZO7FMF40.jpg[/cmimg]Answer 3: Intestinal malrotation may preset with bilious vomiting in a neonate due to development of a midgut volvulus. Abdominal radiograph may show extension of the nasogastric tube into an abnormally positioned duodenum and would not show diffuse colonic distension.Answer 4: Meconium ileus is associated with cystic fibrosis and also presents with delayed (> 48 hours) passing of meconium. However, the distal obstruction in these patients will not be temporarily relieved by digital rectal exam. Contrast enema will demonstrate a microcolon involving the entire large bowel.', 'This pediatric patient presents with features of Down syndrome (trisomy 21), bilious vomiting, and colonic distention on abdominal radiograph, which suggests a diagnosis of Hirschsprung disease.Hirschsprung disease is associated with Down syndrome and presents with bilious vomiting, failure to pass meconium in the first 48 hours of life, and abdominal distension. Digital rectal exam may temporarily relieve the obstruction and lead to expulsion of gas and stool (the “squirt sign”). Abdominal radiograph typically demonstrates signs of distal intestinal obstruction such as proximal dilation and an absence of air in the rectum. Contrast enema may reveal a transition zone between the dilated proximal megacolon and the narrow rectosigmoid colon.Figure demonstrates colonic distension on abdominal radiograph, which is consistent with a diagnosis of Hirschsprung disease. Illustration demonstrates the \"double bubble\" sign of duodenal atresia, which reflects air in both the stomach and first portion of the duodenum.[color=#FF0000]Incorrect Answers[/color]:Answer 1: Duodenal atresia is associated with Down syndrome (trisomy 21) and may also present in the first 48 hours of life with bilious vomiting. However, abdominal radiograph will demonstrate the “[color=#0000FF][b]double bubble[/b][/color]” sign, which reflects air trapping in the stomach and first portion of the duodenum.[cmimg]0/9406627_ZO7FMF40.jpg[/cmimg]Answer 3: Intestinal malrotation may preset with bilious vomiting in a neonate due to development of a midgut volvulus. Abdominal radiograph may show extension of the nasogastric tube into an abnormally positioned duodenum and would not show diffuse colonic distension.Answer 4: Meconium ileus is associated with cystic fibrosis and also presents with delayed (> 48 hours) passing of meconium. However, the distal obstruction in these patients will not be temporarily relieved by digital rectal exam. Contrast enema will demonstrate a microcolon involving the entire large bowel.', 5, 'A 2-day-old male has an episode of vomiting in the hospital nursery. The vomitus was described as “bright green” without any traces of blood. The patient has urinated several times since he was born, but has not passed any stool. He was born at 37 weeks of gestation. On physical exam, the patient has up-slanting palpebral fissures, epicanthal folds, and a single transverse palmar crease. His abdomen is non-tender, firm, and distended. Bowel sounds are sluggish. Digital rectal exam evacuates a small amount of stool and flatulence. The patient’s abdominal radiograph can be seen in Figure.Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?[cmimg]0/9406627_KZM9YYZP.jpg[/cmimg]', 'B', 'Duodenal atresia', 'Hirschsprung disease', 'Intestinal malrotation', 'Meconium ileus', 'Pyloric stenosis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(209, 'multiplechoice', 26666983, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', '[cmimg]0/9406627_PS9PMGAR.png[/cmimg][cmimg]0/9406627_C7YMM59K.jpg[/cmimg]', '[cmimg]0/9406627_PS9PMGAR.png[/cmimg][cmimg]0/9406627_C7YMM59K.jpg[/cmimg]', 5, 'A neonatal boy is found to be cyanotic a few hours after delivery. The mother noticed the neonate turning blue when crying and feeding. The boy was born via a spontaneous vaginal delivery without any complications and to a 30-year-old mother. The mother received inconsistent prenatal care throughout her pregnancy. Physical examination is significant for a harsh systolic ejection murmur. A chest radiograph is performed.What is the most probably diagnosis?[cmimg]0/9406627_FHBXETQM.jpeg[/cmimg]', 'A', 'TOF', 'Atrial septal defect', 'Hypoplastic left heart', 'Aortic stenosis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
