(220, 'multiplechoice', 26842214, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', 'Night terrors are a type of parasomnia that occur during the non-rapid eye movement (non-REM) stage of sleep. Night terrors are characterized by episodes of fear, screaming, or crying during which the child cannot be fully awakened. These episodes usually last a few minutes and then the child settles back down to sleep.The next morning, the child usually has no memory of the incident. Night terrors are most commonly seen in children between the ages of 2 and 12 with a peak incidence at 5-7 years old. This parasomnia can be triggered by acute stress, sleep deprivation, illness, or medications that affect the central nervous system. Night terrors usually spontaneously resolve as the child ages.', 'Night terrors are a type of parasomnia that occur during the non-rapid eye movement (non-REM) stage of sleep. Night terrors are characterized by episodes of fear, screaming, or crying during which the child cannot be fully awakened. These episodes usually last a few minutes and then the child settles back down to sleep.The next morning, the child usually has no memory of the incident. Night terrors are most commonly seen in children between the ages of 2 and 12 with a peak incidence at 5-7 years old. This parasomnia can be triggered by acute stress, sleep deprivation, illness, or medications that affect the central nervous system. Night terrors usually spontaneously resolve as the child ages.', 5, 'A previously healthy 5-year-old girl is brought to the physician for evaluation of night awakenings. She has woken up screaming in each of the past three nights about one hour after going to sleep. When her parents go to her room, she is crying, sweating, and looks frightened. She does not respond to her parents and does not seem fully awake. When her parents hold her, she calms down and goes back to sleep. The next morning, she does not recall the incident. She started kindergarten this week and has just begun going all day without taking a nap. On examination, she is afebrile and her vital signs are within normal limits. A complete physical examination is unremarkable What is the most likely diagnosis?', 'D', 'Nightmare', 'Somnambulism', 'Epilepsy', 'Night terrors', 'Benign paroxysmal vertigo', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(221, 'multiplechoice', 26879579, 'Generic Parent', 'Psychiatry', 'No', 'This patient, who exhibits suicidal gestures, self-injurious behaviors, frantic efforts to avoid abandonment, splitting, unstable relationships, unstable/highly reactive mood, and self-described feelings of “emptiness” has borderline personality disorder.Borderline personality disorder is characterized by instability, including unstable mood (intense, reactive moods that change rapidly, never lasting more than a few days), unstable interpersonal relationships (frequent fights, intense and dramatic attachments and breakups), and an unstable sense of self. Other common features include persistent suicidal threats or gestures (especially in an effort to avoid abandonment) and self-injurious behaviors (e.g., cutting). Splitting (e.g., this patient’s description of his new girlfriend as “the one,” while viewing his ex-girlfriends as purely negative) is a common defense mechanism.Incorrect Answers:Answers 1: Bipolar I disorder (BP-I) is characterized by intense mood episodes (mania, and often depression) lasting for at least 1 week (for a manic episode) or 2 weeks (for a depressive episode), in contrast to this patient’s short-lived (1 day) and reactive \"elated\" and \"depressed\" moods.Answer 2: Mood episodes in bipolar II disorder (BP-II) last for at least 4 days (for a hypomanic episode) and 2 weeks (for a depressive episode). Therefore, his moods do not represent hypomania or depression seen in BP-II.Answer 4: Histrionic personality disorder could explain this patient’s exaggerated/shifting emotions, attention-seeking behavior, and overvaluing of relationships as more intimate than they are. However, these are better explained by borderline personality disorder, as are his other symptoms, which are not seen in histrionic personality disorder.Answer 5: As described above, depressive episodes (whether they occur as part of major depressive disorder, BP-I or BP-II) last at least 2 weeks, which this patient’s self-described “depressed” mood does not.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]:Classic features of borderline personality disorder include unstable mood, unstable relationships, unstable sense of self, suicidal threats/gestures, self-harm, and splitting.', 'This patient, who exhibits suicidal gestures, self-injurious behaviors, frantic efforts to avoid abandonment, splitting, unstable relationships, unstable/highly reactive mood, and self-described feelings of “emptiness” has borderline personality disorder.Borderline personality disorder is characterized by instability, including unstable mood (intense, reactive moods that change rapidly, never lasting more than a few days), unstable interpersonal relationships (frequent fights, intense and dramatic attachments and breakups), and an unstable sense of self. Other common features include persistent suicidal threats or gestures (especially in an effort to avoid abandonment) and self-injurious behaviors (e.g., cutting). Splitting (e.g., this patient’s description of his new girlfriend as “the one,” while viewing his ex-girlfriends as purely negative) is a common defense mechanism.Incorrect Answers:Answers 1: Bipolar I disorder (BP-I) is characterized by intense mood episodes (mania, and often depression) lasting for at least 1 week (for a manic episode) or 2 weeks (for a depressive episode), in contrast to this patient’s short-lived (1 day) and reactive \"elated\" and \"depressed\" moods.Answer 2: Mood episodes in bipolar II disorder (BP-II) last for at least 4 days (for a hypomanic episode) and 2 weeks (for a depressive episode). Therefore, his moods do not represent hypomania or depression seen in BP-II.Answer 4: Histrionic personality disorder could explain this patient’s exaggerated/shifting emotions, attention-seeking behavior, and overvaluing of relationships as more intimate than they are. However, these are better explained by borderline personality disorder, as are his other symptoms, which are not seen in histrionic personality disorder.Answer 5: As described above, depressive episodes (whether they occur as part of major depressive disorder, BP-I or BP-II) last at least 2 weeks, which this patient’s self-described “depressed” mood does not.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]:Classic features of borderline personality disorder include unstable mood, unstable relationships, unstable sense of self, suicidal threats/gestures, self-harm, and splitting.', 5, 'A 19-year-old man presents to the emergency room after a suicidal gesture following a fight with his new girlfriend. He tearfully tells you that she is “definitely the one,\" unlike his numerous previous girlfriends, who were \"all mean and selfish” and with whom he frequently fought. During this fight, his current girlfriend suggested that they spend time apart, so he opened a window and threatened to jump unless she promised to never leave him. You gather that his other relationships have ended in similar ways. He endorses impulsive behaviors and describes his moods as “intense” and rapidly changing in response to people around him. He often feels “depressed” for one day and then elated the next. You notice several superficial cuts and scars on the patient’s arms and wrists, and he admits to cutting his wrists in order to “feel something other than my emptiness.” Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis for this patient?', 'C', 'Bipolar I disorder', 'Bipolar II disorder', 'Borderline personality disorder', 'Histrionic personality disorder', 'Major depressive disorder', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(222, 'multiplechoice', 26879630, 'Generic Parent', 'Psychiatry', 'No', 'This patient, who idolizes some coworkers and views others as “totally incompetent” is exhibiting splitting.Splitting is defined as a tendency to view things or other people as all good (e.g., idolizing some co-workers) or all bad (e.g., describing other coworkers as “totally incompetent”). It is an immature defense mechanism and is most classically seen in borderline personality disorder (BPD), though present in other cases as well.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Denial (an immature/primitive defense mechanism) is the refusal to accept an unpleasant reality, instead acting as though it did not exist. This patient does not exhibit clear signs of denial in this scenario.Answer 2: This patient clearly uses humor as a defense mechanism, which entails finding comical aspects of undesirable situations, thereby reducing the stress associated with them. However, humor is a mature defense mechanism (as are sublimation, altruism and suppression).Answer 3: Reaction formation (the enactment of sentiments that are the opposite of what one feels) is an immature/primitive defense mechanism but is not exhibited by this patient.Answer 5: Suppression is a mature defense mechanism that involves consciously (and often temporarily) choosing to not think about something unpleasant at that time, particularly if dwelling on it then would not be productive. Repression is an immature defense mechanism that is similar but subconscious and less adaptive. This patient refusing to talk about his childhood may be an example of suppression (which cannot be the correct answer here, since it is mature) or repression (which is not an answer choice) — more information would be needed to determine this.[color=#0000FF][b]Note[/b][/color]: Splitting is the tendency to view things or people as all good or all bad; it is an immature defense mechanism that is most commonly associated with borderline personality disorder (BPD) but seen in 