(237, 'multiplechoice', 26908339, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'This patient likely has ectopic pregnancy given her abdominal pain, missed menstrual period, and vaginal bleeding (i.e., vaginal spotting). It is imperative that beta-hCG with transvaginal ultrasound is performed to rule out ectopic pregnancy in women of child-bearing age.Ectopic pregnancy is defined as an extrauterine pregnancy. The majority of cases occur at the fallopian tube (96%); other sites include cervical, interstitial, ovarian, intramural, or abdominal. It commonly presents with first-trimester vaginal bleeding, abdominal pain, and possible pregnancy discomforts (e.g., breast tenderness, frequent urination, or nausea). In any woman who is of childbearing age presenting with abdominal pain, it is important to rule out ectopic pregnancy as some cases (e.g., ruptured ectopic pregnancy) are medical emergencies. Beta-hCG is initially performed to diagnose pregnancy and is followed serially to assess for ectopic pregnancy. Transvaginal ultrasound is then performed to assess the location of the pregnancy. Hemodynamic stability should also be assessed immediately in patients with suspected ectopic pregnancy as a ruptured ectopic pregnancy can lead to rapid decompensation. Management includes both medical (i.e., methotrexate) and surgical intervention (e.g., salpingostomy or salpingectomy), depending on the acuity/severity and other criteria.Incorrect Answers:Answer 2: CT of the abdomen and pelvis with IV contrast is the preferred imaging modality for the workup of appendicitis. This patient’s history and presentation are suggestive of appendicitis; however, her lack of laboratory abnormalities (i.e., leukocytosis) and fever makes appendicitis less likely. In addition, a beta-hCG test is warranted prior to CT imaging.Answer 3: Lipase and amylase levels are often elevated in patients with acute pancreatitis. Patients often present with severe epigastric pain, nausea, and vomiting. Alcohol abuse and gallstones are the most common causes in the United States. This patient’s history does not indicate a typical course for acute pancreatitis.Answer 4: Starting the patient on piperacillin and tazobactam is a good measure in terms of empirically covering for gram-negative/intra-abdominal bacteria. However, this patient does not have clinical or laboratory signs of infection (e.g., hemodynamic instability, fever, or leukocytosis).Answer 5: Urinalysis with culture is indicated in this patient as she is complaining of urinary symptoms (i.e., urinary frequency). Urinary tract infections (UTI) can lead to pyelonephritis, which can present with abdominal pain. However, the pain is often concentrated at the flank and is usually accompanied by fever and leukocytosis. In this patient, ruling out an ectopic pregnancy is of a higher priority than diagnosing a possible UTI.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Beta-hCG and transvaginal ultrasound are indicated in all women of childbearing age presenting with abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, and/or missed menstrual period for rule out of ectopic pregnancy.', 'This patient likely has ectopic pregnancy given her abdominal pain, missed menstrual period, and vaginal bleeding (i.e., vaginal spotting). It is imperative that beta-hCG with transvaginal ultrasound is performed to rule out ectopic pregnancy in women of child-bearing age.Ectopic pregnancy is defined as an extrauterine pregnancy. The majority of cases occur at the fallopian tube (96%); other sites include cervical, interstitial, ovarian, intramural, or abdominal. It commonly presents with first-trimester vaginal bleeding, abdominal pain, and possible pregnancy discomforts (e.g., breast tenderness, frequent urination, or nausea). In any woman who is of childbearing age presenting with abdominal pain, it is important to rule out ectopic pregnancy as some cases (e.g., ruptured ectopic pregnancy) are medical emergencies. Beta-hCG is initially performed to diagnose pregnancy