(242, 'multiplechoice', 26909362, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'This patient is presenting with a headache (cerebral involvement) and a systolic blood pressure > 160 mm Hg in the setting of proteinuria suggesting a diagnosis of severe preeclampsia.Severe preeclampsia can be thought of as preeclampsia but with more severe features defined as:1. Systolic blood pressure > 160 mmHg or diastolic blood pressure > 110 mmHg2. Platelet count < 100,000/mm^33. Creatinine > 1.1 mg/dL or doubling of baseline creatinine4. Elevated liver enzymes double baseline/normal values5. Pulmonary edema6. Cerebral/visual symptomsOther signs/symptoms of end-organ damage include epigastric pain, disseminated intravascular coagulation, or oliguria. If no end-organ damage is present, it is possible to monitor the patient in an ICU setting until 32 weeks gestation, when delivery is indicated regardless of end-organ damage. IV magnesium sulfate should be given for seizure prophylaxis and blood pressure control is dire (with agents such as labetalol or nifedipine). Definitive treatment is delivery.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Acute fatty liver disease of pregnancy presents with the same findings in HELLP syndrome in addition to renal failure and signs of liver dysfunction such as hypoglycemia, hyperbilirubinemia, hyperammonemia, and possibly coagulopathy.Answer 2: Eclampsia is essentially preeclampsia/severe preeclampsia plus seizures and should be managed with magnesium and immediate delivery.Answer 3: HELLP syndrome presents with hypertension, proteinuria, hemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and low platelets.Answer 4: Preeclampsia presents with hypertension and proteinuria; however, this patient\'s severely elevated blood pressure (SBP < 160 mmHg) and headache suggest a diagnosis of severe preeclampsia.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Severe preeclampsia presents with severe features including: systolic blood pressure > 160 mmHg or diastolic blood pressure > 110 mmHg, platelet count < 100,000/mm^3, creatinine > 1.1 mg/dL or doubling of baseline creatinine, elevated liver enzymes or double baseline/normal values, pulmonary edema, and cerebral/visual symptoms.', 'This patient is presenting with a headache (cerebral involvement) and a systolic blood pressure > 160 mm Hg in the setting of proteinuria suggesting a diagnosis of severe preeclampsia.Severe preeclampsia can be thought of as preeclampsia but with more severe features defined as:1. Systolic blood pressure > 160 mmHg or diastolic blood pressure > 110 mmHg2. Platelet count < 100,000/mm^33. Creatinine > 1.1 mg/dL or doubling of baseline creatinine4. Elevated liver enzymes double baseline/normal values5. Pulmonary edema6. Cerebral/visual symptomsOther signs/symptoms of end-organ damage include epigastric pain, disseminated intravascular coagulation, or oliguria. If no end-organ damage is present, it is possible to monitor the patient in an ICU setting until 32 weeks gestation, when delivery is indicated regardless of end-organ damage. IV magnesium sulfate should be given for seizure prophylaxis and blood pressure control is dire (with agents such as labetalol or nifedipine). Definitive treatment is delivery.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Acute fatty liver disease of pregnancy presents with the same findings in HELLP syndrome in addition to renal failure and signs of liver dysfunction such as hypoglycemia, hyperbilirubinemia, hyperammonemia, and possibly coagulopathy.Answer 2: Eclampsia is essentially preeclampsia/severe preeclampsia plus seizures and should be managed with magnesium and immediate delivery.Answer 3: HELLP syndrome presents with hypertension, proteinuria, hemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and low platelets.Answer 4: Preeclampsia presents with hypertension and proteinuria; however, this patient\'s severely elevated blood pressure (SBP < 160 mmHg) and headache suggest a diagnosis of severe preeclampsia.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Severe preeclampsia presents with severe features including: systolic blood pressure > 160 mmHg or diastolic blood pressure > 110 mmHg, platelet count < 100,000/mm^3, creatinine > 1.1 mg/dL or doubling of baseline creatinine, elevated liver enzymes or double baseline/normal values, pulmonary edema, and cerebral/visual symptoms.', 5, 'A 25-year-old pregnant woman at 28 weeks gestation presents with a headache.  Her pregnancy has been managed by a nurse practitioner.  Her temperature is 99.0°F (37.2°C), blood pressure is 164/104 mmHg, pulse is 100/min, respirations are 22/min, and oxygen saturation is 98% on room air.  Physical exam is notable for a comfortable appearing woman with a gravid uterus.  [b]Laboratory tests are ordered as seen below-[/b]Hemoglobin: 12 g/dLHematocrit: 36%Leukocyte count: 6,700/mm^3 with normal differentialPlatelet count: 100,500/mm^3  [b]Serum-[/b]Na+: 141 mEq/LCl-: 101 mEq/LK+: 4.4 mEq/LHCO3-: 25 mEq/LBUN: 21 mg/dLGlucose: 99 mg/dLCreatinine: 1.0 mg/dLAST: 32 U/LALT: 30 U/L[b]Urine-[/b]Color: AmberProtein: PositiveBlood: NegativeWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'E', 'Acute fatty liver disease of pregnancy', 'Eclampsia', 'HELLP syndrome', 'Preeclampsia', 'Severe preeclampsia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(243, 'multiplechoice', 26909437, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'This patient is presenting with hemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and low platelets suggesting a diagnosis of HELLP syndrome (hemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and low platelets).HELLP syndrome is a condition that occurs in pregnancy that is thought to be secondary to microvascular endothelial activation and cell injury. This subsequently leads to thrombocytopenia, hemolytic anemia, and liver dysfunction and injury (manifested as an elevated AST and ALT). Patients may present with other features consistent with preeclampsia including hypertension and proteinuria; however, the other laboratory abnormalities differentiate this pathology. Hemolysis can manifest with anemia, jaundice, an elevated LDH and potassium, and a decreased haptoglobin. Endothelial activation and microthrombi formation can shear red blood cells leading to schistocytes on peripheral smear. The treatment of HELLP syndrome is the administration of steroids (for fetal lung maturity if indicated), magnesium, and delivery of the fetus.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Disseminated intravascular coagulation occurs secondary to pathologic activation of the coagulation system causing widespread microthrombi that can lead to ischemia and infarction from blockade of small vessels. Patients will present with diffuse bleeding, an increased PT and PTT, a decreased platelet count, a decreased fibrinogen level, an elevated D-dimer, and schistocytes (secondary to a microangiopathic hemolytic anemia).Answer 2: Eclampsia presents with all the findings in preeclampsia (hypertension, proteinuria, and end organ damage) with the addition of seizures.Answer 3: Fatty liver of pregnancy presents with symptoms of preeclampsia including hypertension, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and an elevated creatinine and BUN. Other symptoms include thrombocytopenia, an elevated AST/ALT, jaundice, hypoglycemia, and hyperammonemia.Answer 5: Preeclampsia typically presents with hypertension, proteinuria, and possible end organ damage manifesting as an altered mental status, abdominal pain, and kidney injury.[color=#0000FF][b]Note[/b][/color]: HELLP syndrome presents with hemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and low platelets.', 'This patient is presenting with hemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and low platelets suggesting a diagnosis of HELLP syndrome (hemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and low platelets).HELLP syndrome is a condition that occurs in pregnancy that is thought to be secondary to microvascular endothelial activation and cell injury. This subsequently leads to thrombocytopenia, hemolytic anemia, and liver dysfunction and injury (manifested as an elevated AST and ALT). Patients may present with other features consistent with preeclampsia including hypertension and proteinuria; however, the other laboratory abnormalities differentiate this pathology. Hemolysis can manifest with anemia, jaundice, an elevated LDH and potassium, and a decreased haptoglobin. Endothelial activation and microthrombi formation can shear red blood cells leading to schistocytes on peripheral smear. The treatment of HELLP syndrome is the administration of steroids (for fetal lung maturity if indicated), magnesium, and delivery of the fetus.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Disseminated intravascular coagulation occurs secondary to pathologic activation of the coagulation system causing widespread microthrombi that can lead to ischemia and infarction from blockade of small vessels. Patients will present with diffuse bleeding, an increased PT and PTT, a decreased platelet count, a decreased fibrinogen level, an elevated D-dimer, and schistocytes (secondary to a microangiopathic hemolytic anemia).Answer 2: Eclampsia presents with all the findings in preeclampsia (hypertension, proteinuria, and end organ damage) with the addition of seizures.Answer 3: Fatty liver of pregnancy presents with symptoms of preeclampsia including hypertension, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and an elevated creatinine and BUN. Other symptoms include thrombocytopenia, an elevated AST/ALT, jaundice, hypoglycemia, and hyperammonemia.Answer 5: Preeclampsia typically presents with hypertension, proteinuria, and possible end organ damage manifesting as an altered mental status, abdominal pain, and kidney injury.[color=#0000FF][b]Note[/b][/color]: HELLP syndrome presents with hemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and low platelets.', 5, 'A 33-year-old woman presents to the emergency department at 37 weeks gestation.  She states that she has had a headache for the past day and generally does not feel well.  Her past medical history is unremarkable, and she is currently taking prenatal vitamins.  Her temperature is 99°F (37.2°C), blood pressure is 175/105 mmHg, pulse is 100/min, respirations are 16/min, and oxygen saturation is 97% on room air.  Physical exam is notable for diffuse discomfort to abdominal palpation.  A spot urine protein to creatinine ratio is 37.  [b]Laboratory values are ordered as seen below-[/b]Hemoglobin: 9 g/dLHematocrit: 30%Leukocyte count: 6,500/mm^3 with normal differentialPlatelet count: 47,000/mm^3  [b]Serum:[/b]Na+: 139 mEq/LCl-: 100 mEq/LK+: 5.3 mEq/LHCO3-: 25 mEq/LBUN: 40 mg/dLGlucose: 99 mg/dLCreatinine: 2.3 mg/dLCa2+: 10.2 mg/dLAST: 112 U/LALT: 150 U/L. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'D', 'Disseminated intravascular coagulation', 'Eclampsia', 'Fatty liver of pregnancy', 'HELLP syndrome', 'Preeclampsia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(244, 'multiplechoice', 26933814, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'This patient has a prior C-section and presents with painless vaginal bleeding, which is highly suggestive of placenta previa. The best next step in management is a transabdominal or transvaginal ultrasound to evaluate for abnormal placentation.Placenta previa, or presence of placental tissue over the internal cervical os, classically presents with vaginal bleeding in the absence of uterine contractions. This is in contrast to placental abruption, which typically presents with painful bleeding. Suspected placenta previa should be evaluated with transabdominal or transvaginal ultrasound even prior to digital vaginal exam. Of note, transvaginal ultrasound is safe despite concerns for placenta previa, as optimal positioning of the probe is 2-3 centimeters away from the cervix.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Digital vaginal exam is contraindicated in suspected placenta previa, as manipulation of the exposed placenta may cause massive hemorrhage. For any woman in whom placenta previa is a possibility, evaluation with ultrasound is the first step.Answer 2: Immediate C-section is not indicated in placenta previa as long as mother and fetus are both stable, though a C-section will eventually be required for delivery and should be scheduled around 37 weeks gestation. In contrast, vasa previa – when unprotected fetal vessels cross the cervical os – is an emergency and requires immediate C-section.Answer 4: Intrasmuscular betamethasone is indicated if delivery is considered imminent within the next 7 days in a woman who is less than 37 weeks gestation. This has been shown to aid lung maturation and prevent intraventricular hemorrhage. In this patient, there is no concern that the fetus will be delivered within the next 7 days, making betamethasone unnecessary.Answer 5: Reassurance and close follow-up would be appropriate if this patient were at a gestational age less than 20 weeks. Placenta previa identified at that time most often resolves throughout the pregnancy and would likely require no further intervention, but if it persists past 20 weeks (as in this patient), it would be inappropriate to manage expectantly.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Transabdominal or transvaginal ultrasound should be performed for evaluation when placenta previa is suspected and digital vaginal exam should be avoided.', 'This patient has a prior C-section and presents with painless vaginal bleeding, which is highly suggestive of placenta previa. The best next step in management is a transabdominal or transvaginal ultrasound to evaluate for abnormal placentation.Placenta previa, or presence of placental tissue over the internal cervical os, classically presents with vaginal bleeding in the absence of uterine contractions. This is in contrast to placental abruption, which typically presents with painful bleeding. Suspected placenta previa should be evaluated with transabdominal or transvaginal ultrasound even prior to digital vaginal exam. Of note, transvaginal ultrasound is safe despite concerns for placenta previa, as optimal positioning of the probe is 2-3 centimeters away from the cervix.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Digital vaginal exam is contraindicated in suspected placenta previa, as manipulation of the exposed placenta may cause massive hemorrhage. For any woman in whom placenta previa is a possibility, evaluation with ultrasound is the first step.Answer 2: Immediate C-section is not indicated in placenta previa as long as mother and fetus are both stable, though a C-section will eventually be required for delivery and should be scheduled around 37 weeks gestation. In contrast, vasa previa – when unprotected fetal vessels cross the cervical os – is an emergency and requires immediate C-section.Answer 4: Intrasmuscular betamethasone is indicated if delivery is considered imminent within the next 7 days in a woman who is less than 37 weeks gestation. This has been shown to aid lung maturation and prevent intraventricular hemorrhage. In this patient, there is no concern that the fetus will be delivered within the next 7 days, making betamethasone unnecessary.Answer 5: Reassurance and close follow-up would be appropriate if this patient were at a gestational age less than 20 weeks. Placenta previa identified at that time most often resolves throughout the pregnancy and would likely require no further intervention, but if it persists past 20 weeks (as in this patient), it would be inappropriate to manage expectantly.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Transabdominal or transvaginal ultrasound should be performed for evaluation when placenta previa is suspected and digital vaginal exam should be avoided.', 5, 'A 39-year-old presents to the obstetric triage center with vaginal bleeding that started one hour ago. She states that she had a positive pregnancy test six months ago but never sought prenatal care. The patient had a prior Caesarean section six years ago for non-reassuring fetal heart tones. During examination, the patient’s temperature is 98.4°F (36.8°C), blood pressure is 121/70 mmHg, pulse is 75/min, and respirations are 14/min. The patient appears comfortable and gravid, with a fundal height of 24 centimeters. Cardiovascular and pulmonary exams are unremarkable, and there is a moderate amount of blood on the patient’s underwear. External fetal monitoring is initiated, and showed no contractions, good variability and accelerations, and no decelerations.Which of the following is the best next step in management?', 'C', 'Digital vaginal exam', 'Immediate C-section', 'Transabdominal ultrasound', 'Intramuscular betamethasone', 'Reassurance and close follow-up', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
