(245, 'multiplechoice', 26933875, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'The patient is presenting with acute-onset, unilateral, lower abdominal pain following physical activity and a pelvic ultrasound that shows free fluid. This is suspicious for a ruptured ovarian cyst.Ruptured ovarian cysts can either be simple or hemorrhagic. Patients often present after physical activity with sudden-onset, unilateral, lower abdominal pain. For large and/or hemorrhagic cysts, blood loss may cause shock. On pelvic ultrasound, a cyst will appear thin-walled but not always be visible depending on when or how the rupture took place. There will be free fluid, most often in the pouch of Douglas or the rectouterine pouch. Conservative symptom management such as analgesics is recommended as long as the patient is hemodynamically stable.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Ectopic pregnancy can cause lower unilateral abdominal pain and guarding. A pelvic ultrasound would show an echogenic mass or free fluid with rupture. A ruptured ectopic pregnancy is an emergency and would present with signs of hemorrhagic shock (i.e., hypotension, tachycardia, or altered mental status).Answer 2: Mittelschmerz is also known as mid-cycle pain, which can present similarly to ovarian cyst rupture (unilateral lower abdominal pain). It can also cause free fluid on pelvic ultrasound. Dissimilarly, mittelschmerz is associated with ovulation, therefore the pain normally occurs 2 weeks following the patient’s last menstrual period and is often recurrent and not related to physical activity.Answer 3: Ovarian torsion similarly presents with sudden-onset, unilateral lower abdominal pain and may also be associated with nausea and vomiting. Diagnosis is made by pelvic ultrasound with Doppler that shows a large, edematous ovary with decreased blood flow. This is a surgical emergency that requires detorsion for viable ovaries.Answer 4: Pelvic inflammatory disease is an infection that spreads beyond the cervix (i.e., uterus, fallopian tubes, and ovaries) most commonly caused by chlamydia and gonorrhea. Patients will present with lower abdominal pain, usually bilateral), signs of infection (i.e., fever and leukocytosis), and abnormal vaginal discharge.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Ruptured ovarian cyst presents with sudden-onset, unilateral abdominal pain following physical activity and a pelvic ultrasound showing free fluid.', 'The patient is presenting with acute-onset, unilateral, lower abdominal pain following physical activity and a pelvic ultrasound that shows free fluid. This is suspicious for a ruptured ovarian cyst.Ruptured ovarian cysts can either be simple or hemorrhagic. Patients often present after physical activity with sudden-onset, unilateral, lower abdominal pain. For large and/or hemorrhagic cysts, blood loss may cause shock. On pelvic ultrasound, a cyst will appear thin-walled but not always be visible depending on when or how the rupture took place. There will be free fluid, most often in the pouch of Douglas or the rectouterine pouch. Conservative symptom management such as analgesics is recommended as long as the patient is hemodynamically stable.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Ectopic pregnancy can cause lower unilateral abdominal pain and guarding. A pelvic ultrasound would show an echogenic mass or free fluid with rupture. A ruptured ectopic pregnancy is an emergency and would present with signs of hemorrhagic shock (i.e., hypotension, tachycardia, or altered mental status).Answer 2: Mittelschmerz is also known as mid-cycle pain, which can present similarly to ovarian cyst rupture (unilateral lower abdominal pain). It can also cause free fluid on pelvic ultrasound. Dissimilarly, mittelschmerz is associated with ovulation, therefore the pain normally occurs 2 weeks following the patient’s last menstrual period and is often recurrent and not related to physical activity.Answer 3: Ovarian torsion similarly presents with sudden-onset, unilateral lower abdominal pain and may also be associated with nausea and vomiting. Diagnosis is made by pelvic ultrasound with Doppler that shows a large, edematous ovary with decreased blood flow. This is a surgical emergency that requires detorsion for viable ovaries.Answer 4: Pelvic inflammatory disease is an infection that spreads beyond the cervix (i.e., uterus, fallopian tubes, and ovaries) most commonly caused by chlamydia and gonorrhea. Patients will present with lower abdominal pain, usually bilateral), signs of infection (i.e., fever and leukocytosis), and abnormal vaginal discharge.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Ruptured ovarian cyst presents with sudden-onset, unilateral abdominal pain following physical activity and a pelvic ultrasound showing free fluid.', 5, 'A 32-year-old female is brought to the emergency room by her friend for acute onset abdominal pain. Her past medical history is significant for chlamydia. She is currently sexually active and does not use contraception. Her menstrual periods occur regularly every 30 days. Her last menstrual period ended 2 days ago. The patient’s vital signs are normal. On physical exam, there is left-sided, lower abdominal tenderness and guarding. Pelvic examination is notable for clear mucous in the vaginal introitus and tenderness of the left adnexa. A pelvic ultrasound with Doppler reveals a large amount of fluid in the rectouterine pouch. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'E', 'Ectopic pregnancy', 'Mittelschmerz', 'Ovarian torsion', 'Pelvic inflammatory disease', 'Ruptured ovarian cyst', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(246, 'multiplechoice', 26933924, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'The patient is most likely experiencing an ectopic pregnancy. The diagnosis of ectopic pregnancy is made with pregnancy testing and transvaginal ultrasound (TVUS).In this vignette, the patient\'s presentation of vaginal bleeding, unilateral lower abdominal pain, and adnexal tenderness is highly suspicious for ectopic pregnancy. Right lower abdominal pain in a female can be due to a variety of causes including endometriosis, ovarian torsion, appendicitis, and nephrolithiasis, but the positive pregnancy test and history of chlamydia should raise suspicion for ectopic pregnancy. In ectopic pregnancy, the embryo implants outside of the uterus. TVUS is used to evaluate whether an intrauterine sac is present. An intrauterine sac can be visualized with TVUS by 5-6 weeks of gestation. An empty uterus in the setting of a positive pregnancy test is diagnostic of ectopic pregnancy. In addition, TVUS can evaluate for presence of a gestational sac at an ectopic site, and for evidence of rupture, which presents as free fluid in the abdomen or pelvic cul-de-sac.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Transabdominal ultrasound is less sensitive than transvaginal ultrasound for detecting intrauterine pregnancy. The earliest that intrauterine pregnancy can be visualized on transabdominal ultrasound is 8 weeks.Answer 2: Dilation and curettage is performed to removed tissue from inside the uterus. It can be used to remove the uterine lining after spontaneous or induced abortion.Answer 4: Methotrexate can be used in the management of stable ectopic pregnancy. However, this patient\'s rigid abdomen is concerning for rupture. She should not be discharged.Answer 5: While this patient may require surgical intervention, she should first receive TVUS to confirm the diagnosis.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: In a female of reproductive age, vaginal bleeding, unilateral abdominal pain, adnexal tenderness and positive pregnancy test are strong evidence of ectopic pregnancy. The diagnosis of ectopic pregnancy is made with transvaginal ultrasound.', 'The patient is most likely experiencing an ectopic pregnancy. The diagnosis of ectopic pregnancy is made with pregnancy testing and transvaginal ultrasound (TVUS).In this vignette, the patient\'s presentation of vaginal bleeding, unilateral lower abdominal pain, and adnexal tenderness is highly suspicious for ectopic pregnancy. Right lower abdominal pain in a female can be due to a variety of causes including endometriosis, ovarian torsion, appendicitis, and nephrolithiasis, but the positive pregnancy test and history of chlamydia should raise suspicion for ectopic pregnancy. In ectopic pregnancy, the embryo implants outside of the uterus. TVUS is used to evaluate whether an intrauterine sac is present. An intrauterine sac can be visualized with TVUS by 5-6 weeks of gestation. An empty uterus in the setting of a positive pregnancy test is diagnostic of ectopic pregnancy. In addition, TVUS can evaluate for presence of a gestational sac at an ectopic site, and for evidence of rupture, which presents as free fluid in the abdomen or pelvic cul-de-sac.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Transabdominal ultrasound is less sensitive than transvaginal ultrasound for detecting intrauterine pregnancy. The earliest that intrauterine pregnancy can be visualized on transabdominal ultrasound is 8 weeks.Answer 2: Dilation and curettage is performed to removed tissue from inside the uterus. It can be used to remove the uterine lining after spontaneous or induced abortion.Answer 4: Methotrexate can be used in the management of stable ectopic pregnancy. However, this patient\'s rigid abdomen is concerning for rupture. She should not be discharged.Answer 5: While this patient may require surgical intervention, she should first receive TVUS to confirm the diagnosis.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: In a female of reproductive age, vaginal bleeding, unilateral abdominal pain, adnexal tenderness and positive pregnancy test are strong evidence of ectopic pregnancy. The diagnosis of ectopic pregnancy is made with transvaginal ultrasound.', 5, 'A 23-year-old female presents to the emergency department with right lower abdominal pain that began suddenly one hour ago. She is writhing in discomfort and has vomited twice since arrival. She has no chronic medical conditions, but states she has had chlamydia two or three times in the past. Temperature is 98.6°F (37.0°C), blood pressure is 105/75 mmHg, pulse is 90/min, and respirations are 18/min. Her abdomen is firm, and she is guarding. Pelvic exam reveals blood pooling in the vagina and right adnexal tenderness. Her last menstrual period was 7 weeks ago. A pregnancy test is positive.Which of the following is an appropriate next step in diagnosis?', 'C', 'Transabdominal ultrasound.', 'Dilation and curettage', 'Transvaginal ultrasound', 'Methotrexate and discharge with strict follow-up instructions.', 'Exploratory laparotomy', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(247, 'multiplechoice', 26933986, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'This patient\'s presentation is most suggestive of placental abruption. Hypertension (either chronic or pregnancy-induced) increases the risk of placental abruption.Additional risk factors for placental abruption include previous placental abruption, abdominal trauma, cocaine use, smoking, premature rupture of membranes, blood-clotting disorders, multiple pregnancy, or age > 40. Placental abruption, the premature separation of a normally implanted placenta, and placenta previa are the two most common causes of third trimester bleeding. Placenta previa presents with painless bleeding, while abruption typically manifests with abdominal pain.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Hyperlipidemia does not have a known association with placental abruption.Answer 3: Although the risk of placental abruption increases with age, a patient\'s risk is not significantly elevated until after age 40.Answer 4: Prior C-section is a risk factor for placenta previa.Answer 5: A singleton pregnancy has the lowest risk for placental abruption; a multiple pregnancy increases the risk of this complication', 'This patient\'s presentation is most suggestive of placental abruption. Hypertension (either chronic or pregnancy-induced) increases the risk of placental abruption.Additional risk factors for placental abruption include previous placental abruption, abdominal trauma, cocaine use, smoking, premature rupture of membranes, blood-clotting disorders, multiple pregnancy, or age > 40. Placental abruption, the premature separation of a normally implanted placenta, and placenta previa are the two most common causes of third trimester bleeding. Placenta previa presents with painless bleeding, while abruption typically manifests with abdominal pain.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Hyperlipidemia does not have a known association with placental abruption.Answer 3: Although the risk of placental abruption increases with age, a patient\'s risk is not significantly elevated until after age 40.Answer 4: Prior C-section is a risk factor for placenta previa.Answer 5: A singleton pregnancy has the lowest risk for placental abruption; a multiple pregnancy increases the risk of this complication', 5, 'A 32-year-old G2P1 female at 30 weeks gestation presents to the emergency department with complaints of vaginal bleeding and severe abdominal pain. She states that she began feeling poorly yesterday with a stomach-ache, nausea, and vomiting. She first noted a small amount of spotting this morning that progressed to much larger amounts of vaginal bleeding with worsened abdominal pain a few hours later, prompting her to come to the emergency department. Her previous pregnancy was without complications, and the fetus was delivered at 40 weeks by Cesarean section. Fetal heart monitoring shows fetal distress with late decelerations. Which of the following is a risk factor for this patient\'s presenting condition?', 'B', 'Hyperlipidemia', 'Hypertension', 'Patient age', 'Prior Cesarean section', 'Singleton pregnancy', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(248, 'multiplechoice', 26936335, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'The patient has signs of intrauterine growth retardation (i.e., fundal height discrepancy) that is symmetric (i.e., proportional reduction in size). One cause of symmetric intrauterine growth retardation is rubella infection.Intrauterine growth retardation (IUGR) may present during pregnancy as fundal height discrepancy. Fundal height should roughly correspond to gestational age between 16-36 weeks. Ultrasound imaging with fetal biometry to measure head/abdominal circumference and femur length can confirm IUGR. Symmetric IUGR is characterized by a proportional reduction in the head, body, and limb size/length. This results from intrinsic (or fetal) factors such as intrauterine infections (i.e., rubella or toxoplasmosis), chromosomal anomalies (i.e., trisomy 18), and congenital organ abnormalities (i.e., renal agenesis or congenital heart disease). Asymmetric IUGR, on the other hand, is caused by extrinsic (or maternal) factors that lead to placental insufficiency and cause the fetus to selectively shunt blood flow to critical areas such as the brain, away from the areas such as the limbs and trunk.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Antiphospholipid syndrome can cause decreased maternal flow to the placenta and is a cause of asymmetric IUGR.Answer 2: Cigarette smoking is a cause of asymmetric IUGR.Answer 3: Gestational diabetes is a cause of asymmetric IUGR.Answer 4: Pre-eclampsia is associated with abnormal placentation implantation, which can lead to placental insufficiency and asymmetric IUGR.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Symmetric intrauterine growth retardation is due to intrinsic/fetal factors such as chromosomal anomalies, congenital infections, and congenital fetal heart disease', 'The patient has signs of intrauterine growth retardation (i.e., fundal height discrepancy) that is symmetric (i.e., proportional reduction in size). One cause of symmetric intrauterine growth retardation is rubella infection.Intrauterine growth retardation (IUGR) may present during pregnancy as fundal height discrepancy. Fundal height should roughly correspond to gestational age between 16-36 weeks. Ultrasound imaging with fetal biometry to measure head/abdominal circumference and femur length can confirm IUGR. Symmetric IUGR is characterized by a proportional reduction in the head, body, and limb size/length. This results from intrinsic (or fetal) factors such as intrauterine infections (i.e., rubella or toxoplasmosis), chromosomal anomalies (i.e., trisomy 18), and congenital organ abnormalities (i.e., renal agenesis or congenital heart disease). Asymmetric IUGR, on the other hand, is caused by extrinsic (or maternal) factors that lead to placental insufficiency and cause the fetus to selectively shunt blood flow to critical areas such as the brain, away from the areas such as the limbs and trunk.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Antiphospholipid syndrome can cause decreased maternal flow to the placenta and is a cause of asymmetric IUGR.Answer 2: Cigarette smoking is a cause of asymmetric IUGR.Answer 3: Gestational diabetes is a cause of asymmetric IUGR.Answer 4: Pre-eclampsia is associated with abnormal placentation implantation, which can lead to placental insufficiency and asymmetric IUGR.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Symmetric intrauterine growth retardation is due to intrinsic/fetal factors such as chromosomal anomalies, congenital infections, and congenital fetal heart disease', 5, 'A 32-year-old G1P0 woman presents to her obstetrician for a prenatal visit. She is 30 weeks pregnant. She reports some fatigue and complains of urinary urgency. Prior to this pregnancy, she had no significant medical history. She takes a prenatal vitamin and folate supplements daily. Her mother has diabetes, and her brother has coronary artery disease. On physical examination, the fundal height is 25 centimeters. A fetal ultrasound shows a proportional reduction in head circumference, trunk size, and limb length. Which of the following is the most likely cause of the patient’s presentation?', 'E', 'Antiphospholipid syndrome', 'Cigarette smoking', 'Gestational diabetes', 'Pre-eclampsia', 'Rubella infection', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(249, 'multiplechoice', 26944485, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'This patient presents with preterm premature rupture of membranes (PPROM), or rupture of membranes remote from delivery and prior to 37 weeks. At a gestational age between 24 and 34 weeks, patients with PPROM should receive two doses of betamethasone for fetal lung maturity.Betamethasone has been shown to decrease respiratory distress syndrome, intraventricular hemorrhage, necrotizing enterocolitis, and sepsis in neonates, and it should be given if delivery is considered imminent in the next 7 days. Late term betamethasone (between 34 and 37 weeks) is optional, but administration at less than 34 weeks is considered standard of care. Patients with PPROM should receive betamethasone, as well as a 7-day course of antibiotics to increase latency to delivery and group B streptococcus prophylaxis. Tocolysis is not typically indicated.Incorrect Answers:Answer 2: Administration of magnesium sulfate for neuroprotection is indicated if the gestational age is less than 32 weeks. This patient is already beyond 32 weeks, and magnesium sulfate has not been shown to protect against cerebral palsy at this gestational age.Answer 3: Administration of misoprostol is a common method of cervical ripening to prepare for induction. Given that this patient is preterm, induction of labor is inappropriate.Answer 4: Discharge home with close follow-up is not a treatment option for PPROM given the risk of preterm labor and infection such as chorioamnionitis. Patients should stay inpatient until they reach 34 weeks, at which time they should be delivered.Answer 5: Cesarean section is not indicated at this time, as the patient is preterm and not in labor. Furthermore, the patient’s history of a hysteroscopic myomectomy is not a reason to have a cesarean section – only a myomectomy with entry into the uterine cavity would necessitate this mode of delivery.', 'This patient presents with preterm premature rupture of membranes (PPROM), or rupture of membranes remote from delivery and prior to 37 weeks. At a gestational age between 24 and 34 weeks, patients with PPROM should receive two doses of betamethasone for fetal lung maturity.Betamethasone has been shown to decrease respiratory distress syndrome, intraventricular hemorrhage, necrotizing enterocolitis, and sepsis in neonates, and it should be given if delivery is considered imminent in the next 7 days. Late term betamethasone (between 34 and 37 weeks) is optional, but administration at less than 34 weeks is considered standard of care. Patients with PPROM should receive betamethasone, as well as a 7-day course of antibiotics to increase latency to delivery and group B streptococcus prophylaxis. Tocolysis is not typically indicated.Incorrect Answers:Answer 2: Administration of magnesium sulfate for neuroprotection is indicated if the gestational age is less than 32 weeks. This patient is already beyond 32 weeks, and magnesium sulfate has not been shown to protect against cerebral palsy at this gestational age.Answer 3: Administration of misoprostol is a common method of cervical ripening to prepare for induction. Given that this patient is preterm, induction of labor is inappropriate.Answer 4: Discharge home with close follow-up is not a treatment option for PPROM given the risk of preterm labor and infection such as chorioamnionitis. Patients should stay inpatient until they reach 34 weeks, at which time they should be delivered.Answer 5: Cesarean section is not indicated at this time, as the patient is preterm and not in labor. Furthermore, the patient’s history of a hysteroscopic myomectomy is not a reason to have a cesarean section – only a myomectomy with entry into the uterine cavity would necessitate this mode of delivery.', 5, 'A 29-year-old at 33 weeks gestation presents to you after experiencing a gush of clear fluid one hour ago. She denies vaginal bleeding, contractions, or changes in fetal movement. Aside from anxiety about her leakage of fluid, she feels well. Her prenatal course has been complicated by gestational diabetes, for which she is managed with insulin therapy. The patient has a past medical history of mild intermittent asthma, for which she uses albuterol every few weeks. She also had a hysteroscopic myomectomy two years ago, and her obstetric history is notable for one induced abortion by medication. On exam, patient\'s vital signs are normal. Other physical examinations are unremarkable. Pelvic exam reveals a cervix that is 0.5 centimeters dilated, 4 centimeters long, and -3 station. There is a pool of clear fluid in the vaginal vault. Which of the following is the best next step in management?', 'A', 'Administration of betamethasone', 'Administration of magnesium sulfate for neuroprotection', 'Administration of misoprostol', 'Discharge home with close follow-up', 'Cesarean section', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(250, 'multiplechoice', 26945216, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'This patient is presenting with hypotension after delivering a child, hyperpigmentation, hyperkalemia, and hyponatremia suggesting a diagnosis of primary adrenal insufficiency.Primary adrenal insufficiency occurs when the adrenal gland is unable to secrete sufficient amounts of aldosterone and cortisol. The decreased production of these hormones (primarily cortisol) leads to hypotension that is typically refractory to vasopressors. Part of the pathophysiology that causes this is a downregulation of alpha-1 receptors on the vasculature thus making the blood vessels less responsive to vasopressors. Administration of steroids can correct the underlying pathophysiology and improve patient response to vasopressors. Other findings in primary adrenal insufficiency that can be seen include hyperkalemia and hyponatremia (from decreased cortisol and aldosterone), and hyperpigmentation (from increased proopiomelanocortin, which is released as a part of the synthesis pathway of ACTH). Any stressful event that requires more cortisol can cause the patient to have a flare or worsening of their symptoms.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Acute kidney injury can occur when there is hypoperfusion of the kidney (such as with significant blood loss which this patient does not have) or after administration of a nephrotoxic agent. The patient’s BUN and creatinine would be elevated, and kidney function would be expected to normalize over a few days without serious sequelae in a young and healthy patient.Answer 2: Mycobacteria tuberculosis is the most common cause of adrenal insufficiency worldwide; however, it is an uncommon etiology in the United States. This patient is not presenting with other sequelae of a tuberculosis infection including fever, chills, weight loss, or pulmonary symptoms.Answer 4: Sheehan syndrome or postpartum pituitary necrosis occur when the pituitary gland is injured secondary to severe blood loss during delivery. It manifests as a sudden cessation of lactation, fatigue, and hypotension (cortisol loss), and a loss of pubic and axillary hair (decreased sex hormones).Answer 5: Withdrawal from prednisone use would be a more likely diagnosis in a patient chronically on steroids for a rheumatic condition such as rheumatoid arthritis. A short 5-day course of steroids with a taper is unlikely to cause any suppression of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Primary adrenal insufficiency can be exacerbated during times of stress and present with hypotension, hyperpigmentation, hyperkalemia, and hyponatremia.', 'This patient is presenting with hypotension after delivering a child, hyperpigmentation, hyperkalemia, and hyponatremia suggesting a diagnosis of primary adrenal insufficiency.Primary adrenal insufficiency occurs when the adrenal gland is unable to secrete sufficient amounts of aldosterone and cortisol. The decreased production of these hormones (primarily cortisol) leads to hypotension that is typically refractory to vasopressors. Part of the pathophysiology that causes this is a downregulation of alpha-1 receptors on the vasculature thus making the blood vessels less responsive to vasopressors. Administration of steroids can correct the underlying pathophysiology and improve patient response to vasopressors. Other findings in primary adrenal insufficiency that can be seen include hyperkalemia and hyponatremia (from decreased cortisol and aldosterone), and hyperpigmentation (from increased proopiomelanocortin, which is released as a part of the synthesis pathway of ACTH). Any stressful event that requires more cortisol can cause the patient to have a flare or worsening of their symptoms.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Acute kidney injury can occur when there is hypoperfusion of the kidney (such as with significant blood loss which this patient does not have) or after administration of a nephrotoxic agent. The patient’s BUN and creatinine would be elevated, and kidney function would be expected to normalize over a few days without serious sequelae in a young and healthy patient.Answer 2: Mycobacteria tuberculosis is the most common cause of adrenal insufficiency worldwide; however, it is an uncommon etiology in the United States. This patient is not presenting with other sequelae of a tuberculosis infection including fever, chills, weight loss, or pulmonary symptoms.Answer 4: Sheehan syndrome or postpartum pituitary necrosis occur when the pituitary gland is injured secondary to severe blood loss during delivery. It manifests as a sudden cessation of lactation, fatigue, and hypotension (cortisol loss), and a loss of pubic and axillary hair (decreased sex hormones).Answer 5: Withdrawal from prednisone use would be a more likely diagnosis in a patient chronically on steroids for a rheumatic condition such as rheumatoid arthritis. A short 5-day course of steroids with a taper is unlikely to cause any suppression of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Primary adrenal insufficiency can be exacerbated during times of stress and present with hypotension, hyperpigmentation, hyperkalemia, and hyponatremia.', 5, 'A 23-year-old woman from Texas is transferred to the intensive care unit after delivering a child at 40 weeks gestation.  The pregnancy was not complicated, and there was some blood loss during the delivery.  The patient was transferred for severe hypotension refractory to IV fluids and vasopressors.  She is currently on norepinephrine and vasopressin.  Her past medical history is notable only for a recent bout of asthma treated with albuterol and a prednisone taper over 5 days for contact dermatitis.  Physical exam is notable for abnormally dark skin.  The patient states she feels extremely weak.  However, she did experience breastmilk letdown and was able to breastfeed her infant.Laboratory values are ordered as seen below-Serum:Na+: 127 mEq/LCl-: 92 mEq/LK+: 6.1 mEq/LHCO3-: 22 mEq/LBUN: 20 mg/dLCreatinine: 1.1 mg/dLCa2+: 10.2 mg/dL Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'C', 'Acute kidney injury', 'Mycobacteria tuberculosis', 'Primary adrenal insufficiency', 'Sheehan syndrome', 'Withdrawal from prednisone use', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(251, 'multiplechoice', 26950561, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'This patient is an athlete who presents with primary amenorrhea, fatigue, feeling cold, and low body mass, which together suggest [b]functional hypothalamic amenorrhea (HA)[/b]. FSH and estrogen levels are the next best tests and would be low due to increased corticotropin releasing hormone and subsequently decreased pulsatile GnRH.HA can cause both primary and secondary amenorrhea. In this patient with thelarche, adrenarche, and a growth spurt but no menarche, it is likely that her hypothalamic function was disrupted after puberty began. She is at risk for the “female athlete triad”:1. Hypothalamic amenorrhea2. Eating disorder3. Osteoporosis due to the loss of estrogenic bone protectionIn this patient, there is also some suggestion of an eating disorder, as constipation, fatigue, thinning hair, and borderline tachycardia may be due to inadequate food/fluid intake and nutritional deficiency. HA is also associated with severe stress and chronic illness. HA is ultimately a diagnosis of exclusion, so this patient’s diagnostic workup should ultimately include all of the listed answer choices to rule out other common causes of amenorrhea. However, a low FSH with low estrogen would be most useful. A progesterone challenge test is a more indirect way to yield the same conclusion. In a woman with a functioning hypothalamic system and a patent outflow tract, progesterone will stimulate shedding of the endometrium. If no withdrawal bleed occurs, a progesterone + estrogen challenge test can be performed. A resulting withdrawal bleed would indicate a problem with the hypothalamic system, as in HA. Of note, an elevated FSH with a low estrogen would suggest a diagnosis of premature ovarian insufficiency or menopause, as these conditions would be due to decreased ovarian production of estrogen with resulting lack on inhibition on pituitary secretion of FSH.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: A pelvic exam may be performed to look for an imperforate hymen or transverse vaginal septum, which often presents with hematocolpos or cryptomenorrhea, respectively, and cyclic abdominal pain. They are relatively common causes of primary amenorrhea and would not affect other pubertal development such as thelarche or adrenarche. Though it is possible for this patient to have either anomaly, her risk factors and physical exam suggest HA instead.Answer 2: Prolactin level is useful for diagnosing a hyperprolactinemia as the cause of primary amenorrhea. It is most commonly due to a functioning pituitary adenoma, which may cause symptoms such as galactorrhea, headache, and bitemporal vision loss from compression of the optic chiasm (late stage presentation). Evaluation includes brain MRI, and surgical resection may be required. Though this patient has migraines, they seem to be longstanding. Furthermore, headaches from a pituitary adenoma should not cause aura.Answer 3: TSH levels would be high in hypothyroidism, which could present with some of this patient’s symptoms: cold intolerance, constipation, fatigue, and hair thinning. It could also lead to primary amenorrhea. However, it generally causes weight gain rather than weight loss, and the patient’s other symptoms and age make HA more likely.Answer 4: Decreased GnRH pulsatility is the underlying cause of this patient’s amenorrhea, but because GnRH is scarce in the peripheral circulation, has a short half-life, and fluctuates widely, it is not routinely tested. Treatment with pulsatile GnRH infusions is one option for patients with HA and infertility.[color=#0000FF][b]Note[/b][/color]: Functional hypothalamic amenorrhea is associated with low body weight and excessive exercise. It results from elevated CRH, which causes decreased GnRH pulsations and subsequently low FSH, LH, and estrogen.', 'This patient is an athlete who presents with primary amenorrhea, fatigue, feeling cold, and low body mass, which together suggest [b]functional hypothala