s 5 feet, 4 inches tall and weighs 100 pounds (BMI 17.2 kg/m^2). On exam, the patient appears pale and has thinning hair. She has Tanner stage IV breasts and Tanner stage III pubic hair. Which of the following would be most useful in determining this patient’s diagnosis?', 'E', 'Pelvic exam', 'Prolactin level', 'TSH level', 'GnRH level', 'FSH and estrogen levels', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(252, 'multiplechoice', 26950647, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'This 33-year-old patient with obesity (BMI 35 kg/m^2) presents with 3 years of oligomenorrhea and 4 months of amenorrhea in the setting of recent weight gain, normal FSH and LH levels, and decreased progesterone levels. Her symptoms are most likely caused by anovulation due to obesity.Anovulation commonly occurs in obese patients due to increased peripheral conversion of androgens to estrogens in adipose tissue. This increased estrogen provides negative feedback to the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal (HPG) axis, decreasing gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) levels, leading to anovulation and irregular menses. This negative feedback loop can also result in reduced progesterone production. Anovulation due to obesity commonly presents with irregular menstruation and infertility. These symptoms often resolve with weight loss. Irregular menstruation can also be treated with hormonal contraception.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Ectopic pregnancy is a pregnancy that is located in an extrauterine site, most commonly the fallopian tube. It may present with amenorrhea, abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, nausea, vomiting, and a positive urine pregnancy test.Answer 2: Hypothyroidism is caused by reduced thyroid gland activity and may present with low energy, constipation, dry skin, increased sensitivity to cold, muscle weakness, and amenorrhea. It is also associated with abnormalities in TSH and T4 levels, particularly low T4 and elevated TSH.Answer 4: Perimenopause is the transition period immediately preceding menopause and may present with hot flashes, night sweats, sleep disturbances, mood alterations, vaginal dryness, and irregular menstrual cycles. Perimenopause most commonly begins between 40-50 years old.Answer 5: Prolactinoma is a benign pituitary tumor that secretes prolactin and may present with irregular menses, milky breast discharge, vaginal dryness, and hirsutism. Elevated prolactin would be seen on laboratory monitoring. Prolactin also reduces FSH and LH production, and therefore lower levels of those hormones would be seen as well.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Anovulation, causing irregular periods or secondary amenorrhea, commonly occurs in obese individuals with low levels of progesterone and normal levels of FSH and LH.', 'This 33-year-old patient with obesity (BMI 35 kg/m^2) presents with 3 years of oligomenorrhea and 4 months of amenorrhea in the setting of recent weight gain, normal FSH and LH levels, and decreased progesterone levels. Her symptoms are most likely caused by anovulation due to obesity.Anovulation commonly occurs in obese patients due to increased peripheral conversion of androgens to estrogens in adipose tissue. This increased estrogen provides negative feedback to the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal (HPG) axis, decreasing gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) levels, leading to anovulation and irregular menses. This negative feedback loop can also result in reduced progesterone production. Anovulation due to obesity commonly presents with irregular menstruation and infertility. These symptoms often resolve with weight loss. Irregular menstruation can also be treated with hormonal contraception.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Ectopic pregnancy is a pregnancy that is located in an extrauterine site, most commonly the fallopian tube. It may present with amenorrhea, abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, nausea, vomiting, and a positive urine pregnancy test.Answer 2: Hypothyroidism is caused by reduced thyroid gland activity and may present with low energy, constipation, dry skin, increased sensitivity to cold, muscle weakness, and amenorrhea. It is also associated with abnormalities in TSH and T4 levels, particularly low T4 and elevated TSH.Answer 4: Perimenopause is the transition period immediately preceding menopause and may present with hot flashes, night sweats, sleep disturbances, mood alterations, vaginal dryness, and irregular menstrual cycles. Perimenopause most commonly begins between 40-50 years old.Answer 5: Prolactinoma is a benign pituitary tumor that secretes prolactin and may present with irregular menses, milky breast discharge, vaginal dryness, and hirsutism. Elevated prolactin would be seen on laboratory monitoring. Prolactin also reduces FSH and LH production, and therefore lower levels of those hormones would be seen as well.[b][color=#0000FF]Note[/color][/b]: Anovulation, causing irregular periods or secondary amenorrhea, commonly occurs in obese individuals with low levels of progesterone and normal levels of FSH and LH.', 5, 'A 33-year-old woman presents with 4 months of amenorrhea. Menarche was at age 13. Previously, her menstrual cycles occurred every 28 days with moderate heaviness. Three years ago, her menses started to become irregular. She is sexually active. After each missed period she has taken a home pregnancy test, all of which have been negative. She endorses significant weight gain in the last 5 years which she attributes to a diet of \"junk food\" and lack of exercise. BMI is 35 kg/m^2. FSH, LH, and prolactin are within normal limits.Other laboratory results are as follows:Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH): 2.50 mIU/LFree thyroxine (T4): 13.0 pmol/LProgesterone: LowUrine pregnancy test: NegativeWhat is the most cause of this patient\'s symptoms?', 'C', 'Ectopic pregnancy', 'Hypothyroidism', 'Obesity', 'Perimenopause', 'Prolactinoma', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(253, 'multiplechoice', 26950773, 'Generic Parent', 'Gynae & Obs', 'No', 'This patient with a history of systemic lupus erythematosus (photosensitive rash, kidney dysfunction, anemia, mood disorder, and recurrent pregnancy losses which suggest a hypercoagulable state) is presenting with menorrhagia (heavy menses occurring regularly). An appropriate first-line agent for this hypercoagulable patient would be a progesterone intrauterine device which would reduce the severity of her vaginal bleeding.Menorrhagia presents with profuse, persistent vaginal bleeding which occurs during menses. Possible causes of menorrhagia should be worked up and ruled out prior to assuming it is merely heavy menstrual bleeding. Possible causes include polyps, adenomyosis, leiomyoma, malignancy, and coagulopathy. Once alternative diagnoses have been ruled out, management involves administering medications that regulate the menstrual cycle and reduce bleeding. The appropriate treatment is dependent upon the side effects of the drug. Oral contraceptive pills and oral progesterone therapy can be used for menorrhagia and will regulate the menstrual cycle; however, they are contraindicated in patients with hypercoagulable states such as a history of deep venous thromboses, pulmonary emboli, or hereditary conditions such as systemic lupus erythematosus or factor V Leiden. A progesterone intrauterine device is also appropriate as it can reduce menstrual bleeding and does not significantly increase the risk of hypercoagulability, thus making it a viable option for this patient. Persistent, severe, and refractory cases may be treated with a hysterectomy if the patient does not wish to have children.Incorrect Answers:Answers 1 & 4 Combined estrogen-progesterone therapy or progesterone oral therapy is appropriate treatment of menorrhagia and can reduce the symptoms a patient experiences during their menses including bleeding and pain. In this patient with systemic lupus erythematosus and a history of recurrent abortions, this likely represents a hypercoagulable state; thus, oral contraceptive pills and oral progesterone should be avoided.Answer 2: Ibuprofen is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug that could improve pain and bleeding in menorrhagia by reducing local prostaglandin levels. It would be contraindicated in this patient who has chronic kidney disease secondary to lupus as it could worsen kidney function by decreasing prostaglandin levels.Answer 5: Tranexamic acid is an antifibrinolytic agent that can reduce menstrual bleeding in menorrhagia. Tranexamic acid increases the risk of thrombosis and should be avoided in this patient with lupus and recurrent pregnancy loss.[color=#0000FF][b]Note[/b][/color]: Intrauterine progesterone devices can be used to prevent menorrhagia and are safe in patients with a history of a hypercoagulable state.', 'This patient with a history of systemic lupus erythematosus (photosensitive rash, kidney dysfunction, anemia, mood disorder, and recurrent pregnancy losses which suggest a hypercoagulable state) is presenting with menorrhagia (heavy menses occurring regularly). An appropriate first-line agent for this hypercoagulable patient would be a progesterone intrauterine device which would reduce the severity of her vaginal bleeding.Menorrhagia presents with profuse, persistent vaginal bleeding which occurs during menses. Possible causes of menorrhagia should be worked up and ruled out prior to assuming it is merely heavy menstrual bleeding. Possible causes include polyps, adenomyosis, leiomyoma, malignancy, and coagulopathy. Once alternative diagnoses have been ruled out, management involves administering medications that regulate the menstrual cycle and reduce bleeding. The appropriate treatment is dependent upon the side effects of the drug. Oral contraceptive pills and oral progesterone therapy can be used for menorrhagia and will regulate the menstrual cycle; however, they are contraindicated in patients with hypercoagulable states such as a history of deep venous thromboses, pulmonary emboli, or hereditary conditions such as systemic lupus erythematosus or factor V Leiden. A progesterone intrauterine device is also appropriate as it can reduce menstrual bleeding and does not significantly increase the risk of hypercoagulability, thus making it a viable option for this patient. Persistent, severe, and refractory cases may be treated with a hysterectomy if the patient does not wish to have children.Incorrect Answers:Answers 1 & 4 Combined estrogen-progesterone therapy or progesterone oral therapy is appropriate treatment of menorrhagia and can reduce the symptoms a patient experiences during their menses including bleeding and pain. In this patient with systemic lupus erythematosus and a history of recurrent abortions, this likely represents a hypercoagulable state; thus, oral contraceptive pills and oral progesterone should be avoided.Answer 2: Ibuprofen is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug that could improve pain and bleeding in menorrhagia by reducing local prostaglandin levels. It would be contraindicated in this patient who has chronic kidney disease secondary to lupus as it could worsen kidney function by decreasing prostaglandin levels.Answer 5: Tranexamic acid is an antifibrinolytic agent that can reduce menstrual bleeding in menorrhagia. Tranexamic acid increases the risk of thrombosis and should be avoided in this patient with lupus and recurrent pregnancy loss.[color=#0000FF][b]Note[/b][/color]: Intrauterine progesterone devices can be used to prevent menorrhagia and are safe in patients with a history of a hypercoagulable state.', 5, 'A 27-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with profuse vaginal bleeding. The profuse bleeding always happens during her menstrual period with an otherwise regular duration of menses with no intermenstrual cycle bleeding. The patient has a past medical history of photosensitive rashes, kidney dysfunction, anemia, mood disorders, and recurrent pregnancy losses. Physical exam reveals a non-tender abdomen with a large amount of blood and clots in the vaginal vault. A transvaginal ultrasound and basic labs including coagulation studies are unremarkable.  Which of the following would be the most appropriate management of this patient?', 'C', 'Combined estrogen-progesterone therapy', 'Ibuprofen', 'Progesterone intrauterine device', 'Progesterone oral therapy', 'Tranexamic acid', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
