(270, 'multiplechoice', 26998794, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'This patient with symptoms of a dry cough and bronchospasm in the setting of diabetes, diabetic retinopathy, hypertension, and lower extremity edema is most likely experiencing a side effect of lisinopril, which was prescribed to manage her diabetic nephropathy.Diabetic nephropathy is a clinical syndrome characterized by glomerular hyperfiltration followed by microalbuminuria. Patients who develop diabetic nephropathy typically have longstanding, poorly-controlled diabetes mellitus and a history of diabetic retinopathy or diabetic neuropathy, hypertension, and/or lower extremity edema secondary to hypoalbuminemia. Treatment for diabetic nephropathy includes angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors (ACEIs) and angiotensin II receptor blockers (ARBs). ACEIs, such as captopril, enalapril, and lisinopril, inhibit angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) to lower the glomerular filtration rate by preventing the constriction of efferent arterioles. ACE inhibition also leads to increased levels of bradykinin, which is responsible for the side effect of cough and bronchospasm. Other side effects of ACEIs include hyperkalemia, fatigue, headaches, rashes, and drowsiness.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Amlodipine is a dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker used as an antihypertensive agent, and can cause side effects of headache, flushing, and peripheral edema.Answer 2: Hydralazine is a vasodilator used as an antihypertensive agent, and can cause side effects of headache and lupus-like syndrome.Answer 3: Hydrochlorothiazide is a diuretic used as an antihypertensive agent, and can cause side effects of hypokalemia, hyperglycemia, hyperlipidemia, hyperuricemia, and azotemia.Answer 5: Losartan is an ARB that is also used in the management of diabetic nephropathy. However, ARBs do not cause a side effect of cough, as seen in the patient in the vignette. Side effects of ARBs include rashes, leukopenia, and hyperkalemia.