us presents to her primary care physician with complaints of headaches, fatigue, dry cough, and frequent episodes of bronchospasm. She was diagnosed with moderate nonproliferative diabetic retinopathy by an ophthalmologist last month. Her blood pressure measured in the clinic is 158/95 mmHg. A 24-hour urine collection is obtained and reveals 9.5 g of protein. On physical examination, the patient has diffuse wheezing, jugular venous distention, and 2+ pitting pretibial edema. Labs are notable for a potassium level of 5.2 mEq/L.  Which of the following medications is most likely contributing to this patient’s current presentation?', 'D', 'Amlodipine', 'Hydralazine', 'Hydrochlorothiazide', 'Lisinopril', 'Losartan', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(271, 'multiplechoice', 27024698, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', 'This patient is presenting with atrial fibrillation on ECG, which should initially be managed with a rapid acting/titratable beta-blocker such as esmolol in the setting of his severe COPD and current wheezing and poor oxygenation.Atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response occurs when irregular, disorganized electrical activity from the atria is conducted via the AV node to the ventricles resulting in a rapid, irregular heart rate. Ischemia is the typical etiology and atrial fibrillation is associated with pathologies such as diabetes, hypertension, dyslipidemia, and COPD. The treatment of atrial fibrillation is typically administration of a beta-blocker or a calcium channel blocker. Beta-blockers could theoretically worsen a patient’s respiratory status in conditions such as COPD and asthma; thus, they should be used carefully or a calcium channel blocker should be used such as diltiazem. Esmolol is a beta-blocker with fast titratability and is preferred if there is any concern a patient may not be able to tolerate a beta-blocker as it is “fast on, fast off” - meaning that it can be discontinued rapidly in case a patient responds negatively.Picture is an ECG without any P waves and irregular QRS complexes suggesting a diagnosis of atrial fibrillation.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Digoxin could be an appropriate AV node blocking agent for atrial fibrillation in a patient who is hypotensive for who there is a concern for dropping the blood pressure further with a beta-blocker or calcium channel blocker. It could also be used as a second-line agent in addition to either a beta-blocker or calcium channel blocker if rate control was not achieved with the initial measure.Answer 3: Metoprolol is a beta-blocker that would be an appropriate treatment for atrial fibrillation; however, given this patient’s history of severe COPD, either a calcium channel blocker or a beta-blocker with fast titratability like esmolol would be preferred.Answer 4: Nifedipine is a calcium channel blocker that can be used to control blood pressure, but would not act at the AV node in contrast to diltiazem or verapamil which would be appropriate in this patient.Answer 5: Synchronized cardioversion and no further medical therapy could be appropriate for a patient who presents in atrial fibrillation and is hemodynamically unstable. It may be appropriate if the patient does not respond to diltiazem or is unable to handle esmolol.', 'This patient is presenting with atrial fibrillation on ECG, which should initially be managed with a rapid acting/titratable beta-blocker such as esmolol in the setting of his severe COPD and current wheezing and poor oxygenation.Atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response occurs when irregular, disorganized electrical activity from the atria is conducted via the AV node to the ventricles resulting in a rapid, irregular heart rate. Ischemia is the typical etiology and atrial fibrillation is associated with pathologies such as diabetes, hypertension, dyslipidemia, and COPD. The treatment of atrial fibrillation is typically administration of a beta-blocker or a calcium channel blocker. Beta-blockers could theoretically worsen a patient’s respiratory status in conditions such as COPD and asthma; thus, they should be used carefully or a calcium channel blocker should be used such as diltiazem. Esmolol is a beta-blocker with fast titratability and is preferred if there is any concern a patient may not be able to tolerate a beta-blocker as it is “fast on, fast off” - meaning that it can be discontinued rapidly in case a patient responds negatively.Picture is an ECG without any P waves and irregular QRS complexes suggesting a diagnosis of atrial fibrillation.Incorrect Answers:Answer 1: Digoxin could be an appropriate AV node blocking agent for atrial fibrillation in a patient who is hypotensive for who there is a concern for dropping the blood pressure further with a beta-blocker or calcium channel blocker. It could also be used as a second-line agent in addition to either a beta-blocker or calcium channel blocker if rate control was not achieved with the initial measure.Answer 3: Metoprolol is a beta-blocker that would be an appropriate treatment for atrial fibrillation; however, given this patient’s history of severe COPD, either a calcium channel blocker or a beta-blocker with fast titratability like esmolol would be preferred.Answer 4: Nifedipine is a calcium channel blocker that can be used to control blood pressure, but would not act at the AV node in contrast to diltiazem or verapamil which would be appropriate in this patient.Answer 5: Synchronized cardioversion and no further medical therapy could be appropriate for a patient who presents in atrial fibrillation and is hemodynamically unstable. It may be appropriate if the patient does not respond to diltiazem or is unable to handle esmolol.', 5, 'A 65-year-old man with a history of severe COPD presents to the emergency department with a sensation of fluttering in his chest.  He states his symptoms started yesterday and have persisted to this morning.  His temperature is 99.2°F (37.3°C), blood pressure is 130/85 mmHg, pulse is 125/min, respirations are 16/min, and oxygen saturation is 79% on room air.  Physical exam is notable for an anxious appearing man with an irregular pulse and bilateral pulmonary wheezes with poor air movement.  An ECG is performed as seen in Figure A.  The patient is given dexamethasone, ipratropium, albuterol, and BIPAP and his oxygen saturation is 97%.  Which of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?[cmimg]0/9406627_ZHI1RBNR.jpg[/cmimg]', 'B', 'Digoxin', 'Esmolol', 'Metoprolol', 'Nifedipine', 'Synchronized cardioversion and no further medical therapy', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(272, 'multiplechoice', 27047665, 'Generic Parent', 'Biostatistic', 'No', '[b]Case fatality rate[/b] = # of deaths from a specific cause / total number of cases with same disease x (multiply by 100) 50/500 (multiply by 100)= 10', '[b]Case fatality rate[/b] = # of deaths from a specific cause / total number of cases with same disease x (multiply by 100) 50/500 (multiply by 100)= 10', 0, 'In a village of 3000 people, 500 get Congo Hemorrhagic fever. 450 eventually recover from the disease in the next 4 weeks while 50 died. What is the case fatility rate for this disease?', 'A', '10', '20', '35', '50', '200', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
