(380, 'multiplechoice', 30710554, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 4-year-old girl is brought to you by her kindergarten teacher. She states that the child has not been well since this morning, vomited once, and complained of central abdominal pain. On examination, the child looks unwell and has a temperature of 39°C. Which one of the following would be most expected in this child?', 'A', 'Numerous pus cells on urine microscopy', 'Inflamed ear drums', 'Neck stiffness', 'Inflamed tonsils', 'Localized tenderness over the right iliac fossa', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(381, 'multiplechoice', 30710572, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 4-year-old boy is brought to your practice by his parents because of what they think to be vertigo. The boy suddenly starts feeling that the world is spinning around him. Each episodes lasts for about 1 to 2 minutes while the child is fully conscious. This has happened once a month for the past 3 months. His past medical history is unremarkable. He has had no headache, nausea or vomiting before, during, or after the attacks. Physical examination including ear exam is normal. Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?', 'B', 'Reassure the parents as this is very likely to be benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV)', 'EEG and CT scan of the head', 'Audiology and ENT referral', 'MRI of the head', 'Psychiatric assessment', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(382, 'multiplechoice', 30710580, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 3-year-old girl is brought to your practice by her mother with complaint of multiple painful small oral ulcers. The child refuses to eat because of the pain. On examination, the child is found to have a temperature of 38°C. Similar ulcers are noted on his hand and feet. Which one of the following is the causative organism?', 'C', 'Herpes simplex virus (HSV)', 'Group B streptococcus (GBS)', 'Coxsackie A virus', 'Adenovirus', 'Coronavirus', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(383, 'multiplechoice', 30710589, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Paul, aged 4 months, is diagnosed with pertussis. The father is an engineer and the mother a housewife. They both have completed childhood vaccination against pertussis. Paul has a 5-year-old sister. Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan to consider for Paul\'s parents regarding pertussis?', 'A', 'Immediate booster immunization against pertussis', 'A 10-day course of erythromycin', 'Scheduling a 3-dose course of pertussis vaccination', 'Nasopharyngeal swabs', 'Immediate immunization with pertussis immunoglobulin', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(384, 'multiplechoice', 30710597, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Kyle, 5 months old, is brought to your practice by his mother for evaluation. He has a runny nose and a fever or 40°( for the past 48 hours, but he was other was quite active and healthy. Today, Kyle\'s temperature dropped to normal but he developed a maculopapular rash on his trunk. He is still in good health. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'E', 'Measles', 'Chicken pox', 'Erythema infectiosum', 'Rubella', 'Roseola infantum', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(385, 'multiplechoice', 30710611, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Tom, 10 years old, is brought to your clinic by his mother who is concerned about his height and weight. She says Tom has always been the biggest boy in his classes since he started school. On examination, his weight and height are on 96 and 97 percentiles, respectively. Which one of the following would be the most important initial evaluation to consider?', 'D', 'TSh', 'Urine cortisol level', 'Bone age', 'Blood sugar', 'MRI of the head', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(386, 'multiplechoice', 30710620, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 6-month-old boy is brought to your office by his mother with persistence bouts of cough for the past 2 weeks. Every bout of cough is associated with cyanosis of the face and usually followed by vomiting. Which one of the following is the next step in management?', 'E', 'Nasopharyngeal aspirate and review in 24 hours', 'Immunization at this visit with dTP and review in 24 hours', 'Start him on clarithromycin and review in 24 hours', 'Trial of salbutamol by mask', 'Admission to the hospital', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(387, 'multiplechoice', 30710633, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Which of the following is regarded as the most imp or t ant clinical exam finding in a child with acute viral bronchiolitis?', 'D', 'Fever', 'Expiratory wheeze', 'Nasal discharge', 'lnspiratory fine crackles', 'Cough with productive sputum', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(388, 'multiplechoice', 30710643, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Which one of the following is the most common cause of painful rectal bleeding in children?', 'C', 'Intussusception', 'Gastroenteritis', 'Anal fissure', 'Meckel\'s diverticulum', 'Hemorrhoids', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(389, 'multiplechoice', 30710657, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Six days after an uneventful tonsillectomy on a 7-year-old boy, he is brought back to the emergency department after coughing up blood 30 minutes earlier. Which one of the following would be the next best step in management?', 'C', 'Packing', 'Oral antibiotics', 'Intravenous antibiotics', 'Take him back to the operating room for exploration', 'Give him ice cream and cold fluids', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(390, 'multiplechoice', 30710668, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A mother has brought her 2-year-old boy to your GP clinic with complaint of chronic constipation. She mentions that her boy opens bowels every 5 days. She is also concerned about her child\'s recent weight loss. Which one of the following piece of information, if in history, will help to make a diagnosis?', 'A', 'Delayed passage of meconium', 'Cystic fibrosis of the mother\'s brother in family history', 'The child is premature at 35 weeks', 'The child\'s weight is on 25th percentile', 'Diarrhea after introducing cow\'s milk', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(391, 'multiplechoice', 30710676, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A mother brings her 7-year-old son who has measles and wants to know if the child needs to be excluded from school. The diagnosis was made when the typical rash developed 6 days ago and he has not attended his class since then. The teacher has informed her that all children in the class has been immunized against measles. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate advice?', 'A', 'No more exclusion is required', 'He should be excluded from school for a total period of 14 days after the rash', 'He should be excluded for another 4 days', 'He should receive MMR vaccine before he can go back to school', 'He can go to school when the rash completely resolves', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(392, 'multiplechoice', 30721686, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 10-year-old boy is referred to your clinic from his school for assessment of probable hearing deficit because he has difficulty in hearing resulting in dropped school performance. You carry out a Rinne test that is positive in both ears. A Weber test shows no lateralization; however, he has symmetrical decreased hearing threshold. Which one of the following options could be the most likely diagnosis?', 'C', 'Presbycusis', 'Otosclerosis', 'Congenital sensorineural deafness', 'Chronic perforation of the tympanic membrane', 'Chronic secretory otitis media with effusion', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(393, 'multiplechoice', 30721693, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Lucy has presented to your office concerned about her 3-years-old daughter. Lucy has past medical history of asthma and eczema and heard that these conditions can run in families. She wants to know about the risk of her daughter developing asthma or eczema as well. In consulting her, which one of the following would be the most appropriate advice you can give to minimize the risk allergic reactions in the child?', 'C', 'Avoid monosodium glutamate in foods', 'Avoid contact with sheepskin clothes', 'Minimizing household dust mites', 'No specific advice is needed', 'Giving the child antihistamines in case allergy develops', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(394, 'multiplechoice', 30721699, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 3-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department with sever stridor and suprasternal notch and chest wall retraction. Based on the history and clinical findings, the diagnosis of croup is established. Which one of the following findings, if present, indicates severe respiratory distress?', 'D', 'Suprasternal notch and chest-wall retraction', 'Use of accessory muscles', 'Loudness of the stridor', 'Restlessness and agitation', 'Oxygen saturation by oximetry', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(395, 'multiplechoice', 30721709, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 3-year-old child is brought to your office by his mother with complaints of diarrhea and colicky abdominal pains for the past three days. Which one of the following can be the most likely diagnosis?', 'B', 'Giardiasis', 'Norovirus gastroenteritis', 'Perforated appendicitis', 'Staphylococcal gastroenteritis', 'Shigellosis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `qustions` (`id`, `Question_Type_multiplechoice`, `Question_Id`, `Parent_Category`, `Category`, `Random_Answers`, `Correct_Feedback`, `Incorrect_Feedback`, `Points`, `Question`, `Correct`, `Answer_A`, `Answer_B`, `Answer_C`, `Answer_D`, `Answer_E`, `Answer_F`, `Answer_G`, `Answer_H`, `Answer_I`, `Answer_J`) VALUES
(396, 'multiplechoice', 30721721, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 7-year-old boy is brought to your clinic with a 2-week history of paroxysms of cough and vomiting at the end of coughing episodes during school holidays. Cough is dry and is worse at night. His mother is worried whether he should go to school, which is going to start in 2 days. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate approach regarding this situation?', 'A', 'No exclusion is required', 'Exclude from school', 'Exclude from the school and start antibiotics', 'The child can go to school after antibiotics are started', 'The decision depends on the child\'s immunization status', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(397, 'multiplechoice', 30721725, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 5-week-old female infant is brought to your office by her parents because of \'feeding problems\'. Parents tell you that their child has been vomiting after many of her feeds for the past week or so. They mention that this is a new problem, and she was previously quite healthy. For the first time, the baby\'s vomit was projectile and forceful last night. On examination, a mass is palpated in the epigastric area. Which one of the following, can the most likely metabolic profile in this infant?', 'D', 'Increased pH, increased K, increased Cl, increased pCO2, and increased HCO3', 'Decreased pH, decreased K, decreased Cl, increased pCO2, and decreased HCO3', 'Increased pH, increased K, decreased. Cl, increased pCO2, and decreased HCO3', 'Increased pH, decreased K, decreased Cl, increased pCO2, and increased HCO3', 'Increased pH, decreased K, decreased Cl, decreased pCO2, and decreased HCO3', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(398, 'multiplechoice', 30721738, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Parents of a 14-month-old boy has brought him for evaluation because they think their baby lags behind language development milestones because he does not speak any words and only babbles. He is the outcome of an uneventful pregnancy and was born through an uncomplicated vaginal delivery. He has not had any medical problems to date except few episodes of upper respiratory tract infections. He started rolling over at the age of 4 months, can sit without support from the age of 8 months and has started unaided walking recently. He transfers objects from one hand to the other and plays and enjoys peak-a-boo. Which one of the following this child have?', 'C', 'Language delay', 'Social delay', 'Normal development', 'Fine motor delay', 'Gross motor delay', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(399, 'multiplechoice', 30721746, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 4-year-old boy is brought to your practice with a second urinary tract infection (UTI) in the past 4 months. Last time, an ultrasound scan revealed a grade II vesicoureteral reflux (VUR). In addition to treatment of the current infection, which one of the following would be the most important action to take for prevention of further UTls?', 'D', 'Intermittent antibiotics', 'Practicing good hygiene', 'Surgical correction of the VUR', 'Continuous antibiotics', 'Circumcision', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(400, 'multiplechoice', 30721753, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'You are called by the nurse on duty to assess a 24-hour old female neonate in the neonatal ward. Physical examination is remarkable for the knees being at unequal levels when the hips and knees are flexed, asymmetric gluteal folds, and limited abduction of the right hip. The history is significant for breech delivery. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'C', 'Osgood-Schlatter disease', 'Slipped capital femoral epiphysis', 'Developmental dysplasia of the hip', 'Femoral head fracture', 'Legg-Calve-Perth es disease', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(401, 'multiplechoice', 30721759, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 4-year-old child is brought to your practice with a 2-week history of harsh cough, fever, runny nose and dyspnea. He is short of breath on examination. Which one of the following would be the next best step in management?', 'C', 'Nasopharyngeal aspiration for pertussis', 'Pertussis serology', 'Chest X-ray', 'Pulmonary function tests', 'Blood culture', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(402, 'multiplechoice', 30721766, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 13-year-old boy is brought to your practice with fever and malaise for the past 2 days. On examination, he has a temperature of 38° C. There rest of the exam is inconclusive. In an attempt to find the source of the infection, you order a set of laboratory tests including urinalysis (UA). The UA is positive for 1 + proteinuria and RBCs 30/hpf. No white blood cells are present. The urine is negative for nitrates. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate step in management of this patient in terms of the abnormal UA?', 'B', 'Renal ultrasonography', 'Repeat UA after fever settles', 'Urine culture', 'Start him on antibiotics', 'Renal biopsy', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(403, 'multiplechoice', 30721774, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A five-year-old boy is brought for evaluation by his parents with the concern of unusual behavior. He loves Popeye cartoon and always remembers when it is shown on TV. At that time he turns on the TV. He becomes very upset and irritated if he misses the cartoon. He has a goldfish and spends several hours staring at it with curiosity and fascination. His favorite toy is wooden building blocks that he uses to make towers, break them and build them again. He did not say his first word until the age of 2.5 years and was not able to use communicative phrase at the age of 3 years. He does not play with his peers and is not interested in making friends. During the examination he adamantly avoids eye contact. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'B', 'Asperger syndrome', 'Autism', 'Mental retardation', 'Delayed developmental milestones', 'Obsessive-compulsive disorder', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(404, 'multiplechoice', 30721788, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 20-month-old male infant is brought to the Emergency Department, by his parents, with complaints of cough and shortness of breath. On examination, there is bilateral wheezing over lung fields on auscultation. Which one of the following could be the most likely diagnosis?', 'D', 'Bronchiolitis', 'Croup', 'Epiglottitis', 'Asthma', 'Foreign body aspiration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(405, 'multiplechoice', 30721790, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'An eight-month-old male infant is brought to your office with history of vomiting and diarrhea. Urine dipstick examination suggests urinary tract infection. The child is not dehydrated but seems slightly ill. Which one of the following is the next best step in management?', 'B', 'Give antibiotics', 'Give antibiotics and refer for ultrasound', 'Investigate for a sexually transmitted infection', 'Notify child protection services', 'Oral rehydration and discharging home', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(406, 'multiplechoice', 30721805, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Parents of an 11-year-old boy have brought him to your clinic for assessment because they believe he is obese. On examination, his weight and height are on 90 and 50 percentiles for sex- and age­matched growth charts respectively. Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to consider for him?', 'C', 'GH', 'FSH and LH', 'TSH', 'Bone age', 'Reassure he has normal growth and investigation is required', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(407, 'multiplechoice', 30721811, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 2-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department by his parents, who are concerned about his fever and difficulty breathing. The fever has started this afternoon. On examination, he looks ill and pale and is grunting. He has a temperature of 39.6° ( and his respiration is shallow with a rate of 38 breaths per minute. Chest auscultation is normal. Which one of following could be the most likely diagnosis?', 'A', 'Lobar pneumonia', 'Acute bronchitis', 'Atypical pneumonia', 'Bronchiolitis', 'Foreign body aspiration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(408, 'multiplechoice', 30721817, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'An unvaccinated 3-year-old child has had severe paroxysms of cough with inspiratory whoop for the past 4 weeks. Bouts of the cough have been followed by vomiting. Cough bouts occur more at night. Physical examination is normal. Laboratory investigations is significant for lymphocytosis. Which of the following is not true regarding this condition?', 'E', 'Antibiotics at this stage are not likely to reduce the communicability of the disease', 'Antibiotics often do not improve the symptoms of the patient', 'School exclusion for him is not necessary anymore', 'A 7-day course of antibiotics is recommended for all household and other close contacts regardless of the immunization status', 'No antibiotic prophylaxis for his household is required at this stage', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(409, 'multiplechoice', 30721825, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'You order an ultrasound scan for a 9-year-old girl, who has been brought for treatment of urinary tract infection for the second time this year. On the ultrasound, the right kidney is reported smaller than the left beyond the normal discrepancy. Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to consider for assessment of renal status?', 'A', 'DMSA', 'DTPA scintigraphy', 'Urea and electrolytes', 'Abdominal CT scan', 'Urine culture', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(410, 'multiplechoice', 30721942, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Mother of a 6-month-old boy brings him for evaluation after she felt a hard mass in the left hypochondrium while she was bathing him. The mass is non-tender. Which one of the following could be the most likely diagnosis?', 'B', 'Wilms tumor', 'Neuroblastoma', 'Polycystic kidney disease', 'Ureteropelvic junction obstruction', 'Hepatoblastoma', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(411, 'multiplechoice', 30721954, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Caleb, 7 years old, is brought to your clinic by his mother with complaint of bilateral leg pain for the last couple of days. The pain is more prominent on the right side and is felt in the thighs behind the knee and in the calves. The pain occurs intermittently and more often in late evening and in the night and sometimes wakes him up. Caleb had an upper respiratory tract infection 10 days ago presenting with sore throat, mild fever and runny nose. He is otherwise healthy and has had no serious medical problem to date. His vaccination is up to date. On physical examination, the only remarkable finding is mildly-tender cervical lymphadenopathy. Hip, knee, and ankle joints of the right leg are normal with no swelling, warmth, or tenderness, and have preserved range of motion. 1 He walks normally without limp. Which one of the following could be the most likely diagnosis?', 'C', 'Perthes disease', 'Slipped capital femoral epiphysis (EFCS)', 'Growing pains', 'Transient tenosynovitis', 'Septic arthritis of the hip', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(412, 'multiplechoice', 30721960, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 6-month-old male infant with Tetralogy of Fallot (TF) is brought to your clinic by his mother with history of nasal discharge, low-grade fever, feeding difficulty, wheezy breathing, and I cough for 3 days. The infant\'s father smokes a pack of cigarettes per day at home. Physical examination is significant for inspiratory crackles and expiratory wheeze. Respiratory rate is 60 breaths per minute and oxygen saturation is 92 % on room air. Which one of the following is the next best step in management?', 'B', 'Reassure the mother and educate about minimal handling and frequent feed', 'Admit the baby to the hospital and consider symptomatic care with supplemental oxygen, minimal handling and use of intravenous fluid', 'Start corticosteroid therapy immediately', 'Start nebulized ribavirin and monitor the response', 'Start the child on nebulized saline 3% immediately', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(413, 'multiplechoice', 30721966, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 3-year-old Aboriginal boy is presented to you after he sustained a fit at home 20 minutes ago. According to his mother, the fit started with the boy falling on the ground and having jerky movements of the arms and legs. He was unresponsive during the attack. He never had such an episode before. On examination, the boy looks lethargic but oriented. His temperature is 37.2° C. The rest of examination is inconclusive. Of the following options, which one is most likely to reveal the cause of this seizure?', 'A', 'Vitamin D level', 'EEG', 'CT scan of the brain', 'Chest X-ray', 'Toxicology screen', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(414, 'multiplechoice', 30721977, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'For which one of the following children with urinary tract infection (UTI) hospital admission is indicated?', 'D', 'An infant younger than 12 months of age', 'A 6-year old male child with family history of urinary tract infection', 'A 5-year old female child with family history of urinary tract infection', 'An infant younger than 2 months of age', 'A 2-year old child with allergy to penicillin', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(415, 'multiplechoice', 30721984, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 7-month-old child is brought to your practice with paroxysmal cough and vomiting for 2 weeks and relative wellness and health in between paroxysms. You suspect he may have whooping cough (pertussis). He has already been started on azithromycin. He lives at home with his mother, father and older brothers, aged 3 and 5 years. Neither of his brothers have been immunized against pertussis. Which one of the following options is the most appropriate next action to take?', 'C', 'Arrange to have the child admitted to hospital, and isolated immediately', 'Report the family to the child protection agency in your state for failing to immunize their children', 'Immediately vaccinate his brothers', 'Prescribe azithromycin for the whole family', 'Take no action', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(416, 'multiplechoice', 30721992, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A mother has brought her four-year-old son with complaint of nighttime bed wetting. According to her, he wets his bed 3-4 time a week at night despite achievement of daytime continence at the age of two years. He is otherwise asymptomatic. Physical examination is unremarkable. Which one of the following is the most appropriate management regarding this complaint?', 'D', 'Bed wetting alarms', 'Nasal desmopressin', 'Amitriptyline', 'Waiting for spontaneous resolution', 'Ultrasonography of the bladder, ureters and kidneys', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(417, 'multiplechoice', 30722002, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 5-year-old boy is presented to your GP clinic by his parents with intermittent abdominal pain and vomiting usually lasting for 12 hours. The last painful episode was felt in the left flank. Physical examination is quite inconclusive. You order a urine analysis and culture, the results of which are negative. Which one of the following investigations is most likely to reveal the underlying cause of this presentation?', 'E', 'Plain abdominal films', 'Small intestine barium meal and follow-through', 'Serum creatinine and BUN', 'serum electrolytes', 'Ultrasound scan during a painful episode', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(418, 'multiplechoice', 30722011, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Tanya has brought her 2-year-old son to your clinic, disgruntled and annoyed by the child\'s condition. She tells you that 2 months ago, she started to wean the child onto solid foods and currently his diet includes breastfeeding 3 times a day 5 minutes from each of her breasts and a bowl of cereal and rice every morning. The child has dropped from the 50th to 25th percentile. The child\'s past medical history is remarkable for one episode of admission due to bronchiolitis. Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this baby\'s diminished weight gain?', 'C', 'Cystic fibrosis', 'Celiac disease', 'Low calorie intake', 'Child abuse', 'Normal physiologic response to weaning', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(419, 'multiplechoice', 30722019, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 2-year-old boy is brought to your clinic due to a 3-day history of fever with occasional cough and coryza. On clinical history, viral upper respiratory tract infection is suspected. On physical examination, the patient is noted to have down-slanting of palpebral fissures, eyes that are apart more than usual and low-set ears. The height of the patient is smaller than the standard. Which one of the following is not consistent with this condition?', 'B', 'Pulmonary valve stenosis', 'Myopia and ectopic ocular lens', 'An autosomal disorder involving mutation in chromosome 11', 'Webbed neck', 'Abnormalities in cardiac conduction and rhythm', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(420, 'multiplechoice', 30722028, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 5-month-old child is brought to your practice with a 10-day history of cough paroxysms followed by inspiratory whoop and vomiting. There is no cyanosis associated with bouts of cough, and the child is well between the attacks. Which one of the following is the most appropriate action now?', 'C', 'Reassure', 'Prescribe a 5-day course of antibiotics and discharge the child home', 'Admit the child to the hospital for observation', 'Chemoprophylaxis of the household', 'Vaccinate the household', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(421, 'multiplechoice', 30722037, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A mother brings her 3-week-old male baby to the Emergency Department because of his loose bloody bowel motions. The mother says the diarrhea has started 2 days ago after she started her son on formula milk. The mother is lactose-intolerant and does not use dairy products. On examination, the child is mildly dehydrated and has an eczematous rash on his right cheek. He is not febrile. The rest of the exam is inconclusive. Family history is remarkable for atopy including asthma and eczema in his father and older sister. Mother is concerned that his son may have the same allergy to milk and dairy product she has. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'E', 'Lactose intolerance', 'Gastroenteritis', 'Galactosemia', 'Fructose intolerance', 'Cow\'s milk protein intolerance', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(422, 'multiplechoice', 30722046, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 5-year-old child is brought to your practice by his parents with complaints of fever and ear pain. On examination, he is in mild distress and has a fever of 38.3°C. Otoscopic examination reveals a red bulging tympanic membrane on the right side with decreased mobility. Which one of the following is more likely to have caused this presentation?', 'B', 'Hemophilus influenza', 'Streptococcus pneumonia', 'Staphylococcus aureus', 'RSV virus', 'Moraxella catarrhalis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(423, 'multiplechoice', 30722054, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 6-year-old girl is brought to your practice by her parents with a 4-day history of bilateral knee and ankle pain. On examination, she has a temperature of 37.6 C. Her joints are tender but there is no swelling, inflammation or synovial thickening. The full range of motion of the joints is preserved. Palpable purpuric rashes are noted on her legs and buttocks with some ecchymoses around her ankles. Full blood count, blood urea, electrolytes and liver function tests are normal. ESR is 10mm/hr. which one of the following is a known complication of this girl\'s condition?', 'C', 'Pleurisy', 'Fasciitis', 'Nephritis', 'Thrombocytopenia', 'Diabetes mellitus ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(424, 'multiplechoice', 30722064, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 3-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department with complaints of fever and shortness of breath. His symptoms began 2 days ago with mild fever and rinorrhea. Today, he has a fever of 39°C, nasal flaring, tracheal tug and intercostal recession. He has a harsh cough as well. Which one of the following would be the next best step in management of this child?', 'B', 'Nebulized salbutamol', 'Nebulized budesonide', 'Intramuscular adrenalin', 'Intravenous penicillin', 'Oxygen by nasal prongs', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(425, 'multiplechoice', 30722068, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A mother brings her 10 month old boy to the Emergency Department with fever, nausea and vomiting. She mentions that she has used fewer nappies in the past 48 hours because he has been less wet. She also mentions that his urine has an offensive odor. A urine analysis is performed that is positive for nitrite and leukocytes consistent with urinary tract infection (UTI). This child has never had an UTI before. Which one of the following is the next best step in management?', 'B', 'Antibiotics and ultrasound of kidneys, ureter and bladder', 'Antibiotics, intravenous fluids and ultrasound scan of the kidneys, ureter and bladder', 'Antibiotics, oral fluids and discharge home once the child improves', 'Refer to pediatrician', 'Antibiotics', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(426, 'multiplechoice', 30722073, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 6-year-old boy is brought to your practice by his mother with complaints of pain in the right knee and limping. He has had flu-like symptoms 1 O days ago. On examination, he has a temperature of 38 °C. Hip movements are limited in all directions, but limitation of internal rotation and abduction are more pronounced. An ultrasonography of the right hip is arranged that reveals widening of the right hip joint space. Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?', 'E', 'Start him on antibiotics', 'Start him on analgesics', 'Immobilize the affected joint', 'Start him on systemic corticosteroids', 'Bed rest', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(427, 'multiplechoice', 30722079, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A previously-healthy 18-month boy is brought to the Emergency Department with wheezing and cough starting 24 hours ago. On examination, he has a respiratory rate of 35 breaths per minute. Bilateral wheezing is evident on chest auscultation, as well as mildly diminished breath sounds of the left hemithorax. There is family history of asthma as well as allergy in history. Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management of this child?', 'C', 'Nebulized salbutamol 4-hourly', 'Amoxicillin', 'Admission and administration of oxygen', 'Chest physiotherapy', 'Chest X-ray (CXR)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(428, 'multiplechoice', 30722086, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Emily, 18 months old, is brought to your clinic by her parents for a routine health visit. They are new to then town and this is the first time you visit her. She is the result of an uneventful pregnancy and has had no major medical problem so far. On examination, you hear a cardiac murmur. Which one of the following clinical findings suggests that the murmur is an innocent murmur?', 'D', 'The murmur is diastolic', 'The murmur is pansystolic', 'The murmur is associated with a thrill', 'The murmur increases when the child is positioned supine', 'The murmur is associated with reduced exercise tolerance', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(429, 'multiplechoice', 30722095, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 4-year-old is boy is brought to your attention with complaints of intermittent abdominal pain. Each episode lasted for a maximum of 2 to 3 hours before it completely subsided. He has been quite asymptomatic in between the episodes. This time, however, the pain has lasted for 12 hours. On examination, he is afebrile but a mass is palpated in the right upper quadrant (RUQ). The mass is not tender. Which one of the following could be the most likely diagnosis?', 'C', 'Hepatoblastoma', 'Neuroblastoma', 'Wilms tumor', 'Pyelonephritis', 'Pancreatic tumor', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(430, 'multiplechoice', 30722102, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Parents of a 7-year-old girl has brought her to you for assessment because she frequently soils her underwear. In the past 2 months, they have received calls from her school about her problems there. She is easily irritated, and becomes angry and aggressive with her classmates and other children at school. At home, they have found her soiled underwear hidden. She becomes angry, cries and fights with her older brother when he calls her \'smelly\'. This happens several times a week. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'B', 'Conduct disorder', 'Oppositional defiant disorder', 'Regression', 'Delayed developmental milestones', 'Depression', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(431, 'multiplechoice', 30722120, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A male neonate born at 36 weeks gestation is noted to have many clinical features suggestive of Down syndrome. Six hours after birth, he starts vomiting. The vomit contains caseated milk and green material suggestive of bile. On examination, the abdomen is mildly distended. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'B', 'Hirschsprung disease', 'Duodenal atresia', 'Necrotizing enterocolitis', 'Large bowel volvulus', 'Meconium plug syndrome', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(432, 'multiplechoice', 30722132, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'During physical examination of a 3 kg full-term male newborn, you notice that the baby\'s oxygen saturation decreases when he is laid. The fall in oxygen saturation is sometimes associated with mild cyanosis. However, when the baby starts crying the oxygen saturation increases again. Which one of the following will be the next best step in management?', 'A', 'Rigid nasogastric tube', 'Chest X-ray', 'Surgery', 'Intubation and ventilation', 'Oxygen via nasal cannula', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(433, 'multiplechoice', 30722152, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 15-year-old girl presents with upper respiratory tract infection (URTI). On examination, she has a temperature of 38.1 °C and an erythematous pharynx with no exudate. She is otherwise healthy. A urine dipstick is positive for blood for which you order a urinalysis (UA). UA is reported back significant for red blood cells, 1 + proteinuria , no WBCs and negative for nitrite. Which one of the following would be the next best step in management?', 'B', 'Repeat UA after the U RTI resolves', 'Urine culture', '24-hour urine exam', 'Ultrasonography', 'Start her on corticosteroids', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(434, 'multiplechoice', 30722157, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Kim, 3 years old, is brought to the Emergency Department by her parents reporting that their daughter is not feeling well at all. According to them, she developed a fever this morning and started to refuse food and crying and throwing it out when she was fed. A short while later she became miserable and inconsolable, started drooling, and her breath became noisy. On examination, she has a pulse rate of 140 bpm, respiratory rate of 34 breaths per minute with expiratory strider, and a fever of 39.1 °C. She maintains her neck extended. Lungs are clear on auscultation. Which one of the following could be the most likely diagnosis?', 'D', 'Croup', 'Acute bronchiolitis', 'Retropharyngeal abscess', 'Acute epiglottitis', 'Bacterial pharyngitis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(435, 'multiplechoice', 30722195, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 13-year-old boy presents to his general practitioner, accompanied by his mother, complaining of poorly localized pain in his knee for the past 6 weeks. His mother has observed a limp for the same period of time. He walks with his foot externally rotated. Examination of the knee is normal. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'D', 'Osteochondritis dissecans of the knee', 'Perthes disease of the hip', 'Undiagnosed congenital dislocation of the hip', 'Slipped capital femoral epiphysis (SCFE)', 'Osgood-Schlatter osteochondritis of the knee', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(436, 'multiplechoice', 30722200, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 5-year-old boy is brought to your clinic with generalized petechial rash and bruises all over his body. He had an episode of upper respiratory tract infection (URTI) 3 weeks ago. On examination, he is otherwise healthy. His blood tests is only significant for a platelet count of 74,000/mm3. Red blood cells and white cells are within normal range. Which one of the following is the most appropriate management option in this child?', 'A', 'Strict bed rest', 'Intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG)', 'Steroids', 'Antibiotics', 'Plasma exchange', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(437, 'multiplechoice', 30722209, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 16-month-old child is brought to your attention by his parents because of their concerns about their child\'s language delay. He was born at 36 weeks through normal vaginal delivery with a birth weight of 2500 g. At 8 months of age, a \'mother and child health screening test\' for hearing was performed that was completely normal. The parents say that he babbles but has not spoken any words so far. On physical examination, the child appears quite normal. Which one of the following will you recommend?', 'C', 'Reassure the parents that this is a normal variant', 'Arrange for formal audiometry testing', 'Reassess the child at 18 months of age', 'Repeat the \'mother-child health\' hearing-test', 'Check for dysmorphic features', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(438, 'multiplechoice', 30722215, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A mother comes to your clinic because she is concerned about her 5-year-old son. He has started soiling his underwear every night since he entered school 3 months ago. His teacher also has asked her to come for a discussion about his behavior that seems inappropriate for his age at school. On examination, the boy seems small for his age. Which one of the following can be the most likely cause of the soiling?', 'A', 'Constipation', 'Autism', 'Cystic fibrosis', 'Hirschsprung disease', 'Hirschsprung disease', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(439, 'multiplechoice', 30722247, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 2-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department, at 11 pm, by his parents with complaints of a harsh barking cough. On examination, he is febrile with a temperature of 39°( and has a respiratory rate of 32 breaths per minute. There is inspiratory stridor as well as scattered crackles over both lung fields. He is easily irritated but can be consoled by her parents. Which one of the following is most important to give him first?', 'D', 'Intravenous prednisolone', 'Nebulized adrenaline', 'Nebulized salbutamol', 'Oral steroids', 'Antibiotics', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(440, 'multiplechoice', 30722256, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A mother brings her 7-year-old son 6 days after eruption of a generalized rash that, based on the history and clinical findings, is found to be measles. She asks if her son is required to be excluded from school. She also mentions that according to the class teacher, all students in the class have complete vaccination against measles. Which one of the following would be the appropriate advice regarding exclusion from school for this boy?', 'A', 'No exclusion is required', 'Exclusion for 4 days', 'Exclusion until the rash completely disappears', 'Exclusion is required only if there is an immunocompromised child in the class room', 'Exclusion for 6 days', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(441, 'multiplechoice', 30722261, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A mother brings her 8-year-old daughter for consultation because the girl avoids school and goes to games and parlors. Her parents were advised by her teachers to seek medical help. When you talk to the girl, she becomes tearful and looks withdrawn. Which one of the following is most suspected from the history?', 'B', 'Separation anxiety', 'Truancy', 'Depression', 'Conduct disorder', 'ADHD', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(442, 'multiplechoice', 30722269, 'Generic Parent', 'Paediatrics', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 5-year-old boy is presented to your practice with headache and vomiting for the past 6 weeks. On examination, he has a temperature of 37.8°C. A non-tender lymph node is palpated in the posterior triangle of the neck. Which one of the following is the investigation to consider at this stage?', 'E', 'Blood culture', 'CT scan of the head', 'Urine culture', 'Lumbar puncture', 'Fine needle aspiration of the lymph node', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(443, 'multiplechoice', 30738681, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, '. A 49-year-old woman presents to your GP clinic with progressive low back pain that is shooting and radiates to her left buttock. She denies any preceding trauma or sprain. Her past medical history is significant for breast cancer treated with mastectomy, chemotherapy, and radiotherapy six year ago and osteoarthritis of the lumbosacral spine. On examination, there is tenderness over the L4/L5 area, a positive straight leg raise (SLR) test on the left side. Which one of the following features in the clinical assessment is an indication for further assessments of this patient?', 'E', 'Absence of a preceding trauma or sprain', 'Osteoarthritis of the lumbosacral spine', 'Positive SLR test', 'The radicular nature of her pain', 'Past history of breast cancer', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(444, 'multiplechoice', 30738690, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 72-year-old man was brought to the emergency department after he sustained a fracture of his left hip following a fall at home. Initial pain management was considered and the operation carried out with intramedullary nail placement. Today, he is being discharged. Which one of the following is the most important management\'\"\"\' option to consider for him on discharge?', 'A', 'Painkillers', 'Walker', 'Crutches', 'Low molecular weight heparin', 'Warfarin', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(445, 'multiplechoice', 30738724, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Laura, 56 years old, presents to the Emergency Department with an acutely painful left index finger shown in the following photograph. On examination, she is afebrile, and the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint of the right index finger is red, warm and extremely tender to touch with decreased motion due to pain. She has had four episodes of such incident in the past two years in the same finger diagnosed as recurrent gouty arthritis. She is currently on prophylactic dose of colchicine and allopurinol 100mg daily. She is also a known case of long-standing hypertension, controlled on hydrochlorothiazide and metoprolol, and also a known case of hypertensive nephropathy. Which one of the following would you consider for her as the first-line treatment option at this stage?[cmimg]0/9406627_OWG5IO5P.jpg[/cmimg]', 'A', 'Cessation of allopurinol', 'Cessation of allopurinol', 'Celecoxib', 'Prednisolone for 10 days', 'Increasing the dose of allopurinol to 150 mg, daily', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(446, 'multiplechoice', 30738732, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'While getting off the car, a 40-year-old man developed sudden-onset severe low back pain and got locked in the middle of the way, according to him. He is now in the emergency department for evaluation, complaining of lower back pain, shooting sharp pain in the right leg and foot, and restricted and painful lumbar movements. He runs a grocery store and has been otherwise fit. He drinks alcohol on social occasions and smokes 3 to 4 cigarettes a day. His past medical history is insignificant. On examination, he has stable vital signs and tenderness over the L4-L5 region. Except for positive slump test and straight leg raise test, neurological exam findings are inconclusive with no motor or sensory deficits. Which one of the following is the most I appropriate management option for him?', 'E', 'Obtaining a lumbosacral spine X-ray', 'Obtaining a lumbosacral spine CT scan', 'Obtaining a lumbosacral spine MRI', 'Obtaining a lumbosacral spine MRI', 'Observation', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(447, 'multiplechoice', 30738781, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 67-year-old man presents to your office with complaints of reduced dexterity of his right hand and difficulty grasping objects. His hand is shown in the following photograph. Which one of the following investigations will confirm the diagnosis?[cmimg]0/9406627_WV966QAI.jpg[/cmimg]', 'A', 'X-ray of the hand', 'X-ray of the hand', 'Ultrasonography of the hand', 'CT scan of the hand', 'Blood sugar level', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(448, 'multiplechoice', 30738825, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 37-year-old man presents to the emergency department with fever, malaise and cough for the past 10 hours. He mentions that he has had 4 similar episodes before, but he is quite well in between the episodes. On examination, he has a blood pressure of 130/90 mmHg, pulse rate of 110 bpm, respiratory rate of 24 breaths per minute and temperature of 38.2 C. On chest examination, bilateral crackles are heard. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'D', 'Asthma', 'Asbestosis', 'Allergic bronchitis', 'Extrinsic allergic alveolitis', 'Left ventricular failure', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(449, 'multiplechoice', 30738828, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Which one of the following is the most common complication of Calles fracture?', 'A', 'Malunion', 'Nonunion', 'lschemic Volkmann contracture', 'lschemic Volkmann contracture', 'Wrist joint stiffness', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(450, 'multiplechoice', 30738836, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A patient with anterior dislocation of the shoulder is unable to perform which one of the following actions? ', 'B', 'A patient with anterior dislocation of the shoulder is unable to perform which one of the following actions? ', 'Combing hair', 'Taking a knife from the table', 'Shaking hand', 'Wrist extension', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(451, 'multiplechoice', 30738847, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 57-year-old man presents to the emergency department with severe shortness of breath and tachypnea. As a part of emergency evaluation, an arterial blood gas (ABG) analysis is performed, the result of which are as follows:• PH: 7.2 (normal 7.35-7.45)• PaCo2: 48 (normal 35-45 mmHg)• PaO2: 50 (normal 80 -100 mm Hg)Which one of the following is the next best step in management?', 'D', '100% oxygen by Hudson mask', '28% oxygen by Venturi mask', 'Intubation and ventilation', 'Positive pressure ventilation', 'Oxygen 6 litres/minute by nasal prongs', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(452, 'multiplechoice', 30738855, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Mary is 32 years old and 36 weeks pregnant. She has had an uneventful pregnancy to date and has attended her antenatal care regularly. At today visit, fetal auscultation is significant for bradycardia. A CTG confirms a persistently decreased fetal heart rate of 67 bpm. Due to risk of fetal jeopardy, emergency cesarean section is considered and performed. The neonate has still bradycardia at the rate of 70 bpm. Which one of the following antibodies is most likely-to have contributed to such presentation?', 'A', 'Anti-Ro antibody', 'Anti-La antibody', 'Anti-La antibody', 'Anti-Sm (Smith) antibody', 'U1-ribonucleoprotein', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(453, 'multiplechoice', 30738871, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 67-year-old woman presents to your clinic with complaints painful hips and shoulders and headache. She relates that the muscle pain is felt on both arms and hips. She feels that her shoulders are stiff and the hips cannot move when she wakes up. It almost takes 40 minutes of painful physical activity for the stiffness to relent. Her appetite is decreased and she has lost 5 kg. \'\'To make me even more miserable, the terrible headaches has just been started\", she mentions. The headache is felt on the right side and is throbbing with no response to analgesics. On physical examination, she is noted to have painful restricted movements of shoulder and hip joints bilaterally. Her right temple is tender to touch. She is not febrile and the rest of the exam is inconclusive. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?', 'C', 'Check serum creatine kinase (CK) level', 'Check rheumatoid factor', 'Check ESR', 'Check ESR', 'Star the patient on prednisolone', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(454, 'multiplechoice', 30738884, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 60-year-old man is brought to the emergency department by paramedics because of severe shortness of breath. On his arrival, a bedside pulse oxymetry shows an 02 saturation of 85% on room air. His son states that this is the fifth time he is admitted to the emergency department due to the same problem. On further inquiry, he is found to have smoked 60 packs per year for the past 30 years. He is given oxygen 28% by Venturi mask. 30 minutes later an arterial blood gas (ABG) reports his PaO2 and PaCO2 68 mmHg and 60 mm Hg respectively. The 02 saturation is 88% while on oxygen. Which of the following is the next best step in the management of this patient?', 'B', 'Stop oxygen and check ABG after 30 minutes', 'Continue oxygen until normal PaO2 is achieved', 'Immediate intubation and ventilation', 'Provide immediate antibiotic coverage against gram negative bacteria', 'Start intravenous aminophylline infusion', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(455, 'multiplechoice', 30738893, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 76-year-old woman presents with painful and stiff shoulders that she has had for the past 2 months. The stiffness is worse in the morning and improves after 30-60 minutes of physical activity. She denies headaches, visual problems, or symptoms such as fever or weight loss. Initial laboratory tests results are:• RBC: 5x106 cells/mm3 (4.5-6.5x106)• Hb: 115g/L (130-180)• MCV: 85 fl (76-96)• WCC: 9000 cells/m m3 (4000-11000)• Platelet: 500,000/mm3 (150,000-400,000)• Metabolic panel: normal• ESR: 65mm/h• CRP: positive• RF: negative• ANA: negativeWhich one of the following would you consider for treatment of this patient?', 'B', 'Paracetamol', 'Prednisolone', 'Antibiotics', 'Antibiotics', 'Physical therapy', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(456, 'multiplechoice', 30738914, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Ashley is brought to your clinic by his mother. He is a 9-year-old boy, who has been diagnosed with asthma 2 years ago. He is on inhaled salbutamol on an as­needed basis. His mother mentions that he has had to use his medication more freguently recently. Moreover, he has developed night coughs at least 2-3 times a week. Examination reveals diffuse wheezing over the lung fields. Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?', 'D', 'Start him on inhaled fluticasone and salmetrol', 'Start him on inhaled fluticasone', 'Start him on a 14-day course of oral steroids', 'Start him on montelukast', 'Start him on sodium cromoglycate', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(457, 'multiplechoice', 30738917, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 51-year-old man presents to your practice for back pain. He was diagnosed with ankylosing spondylitis 20 years ago and has had mild back pain all this time. He had received no medical treatment and has been on exercise program on an on-and-off basis. The patient suffers from peptic ulcer disease and has been treated for the condition several times. Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?', 'A', 'Paracetamol', 'Naproxen', 'Methotrexate', 'Methotrexate', 'Infliximab ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(458, 'multiplechoice', 30738943, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 12 year-old boy is brought to the emergency department by his mother with complaints of cough and wheezing. He has had previous episodes in the past, and has not any specific treatment so far. On examination, he has a respiratory rate of 40 breaths per minute and a temperature of 37.5°C. On chest auscultation, widespread wheeze is noted bilaterally. The rest of the exam is inconclusive. Which one of the following is most likely to make a diagnosis now and in the emergency setting?', 'D', 'CT scan of the chest', 'Chest X-ray (CXR)', 'Spirometry', 'Improvement with salbutamol', 'Measurement of peak expiratory flow (PEF)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(459, 'multiplechoice', 30738946, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 32-year-old man presents to your office with complaint of low back pain in the setting of ankylosing spondylitis (AS), which he has had for the past 5 years. He has been on treatment with naproxen 500 mg, 3 times a day, for the past few years with no significant improvement. An X-ray of the lumbosacral area is obtained and is shown in the following photograph. Which one of the following is the most appropriate management option for this patient?[cmimg]0/9406627_LXOEUVOW.jpg[/cmimg]', 'C', 'Start him on sulfasalazine', 'Start him on methotrexate', 'Start him on infliximab', 'Start him on cyclosporine', 'Double the dose of naproxen', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(460, 'multiplechoice', 30738952, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'While gardening, a 45-year-old woman develops sudden onset low back pain. She is in the Emergency Department for evaluation now. Her past medical history is significant for breast cancer 10 years ago that was treated with breast-preserving surgery, adjuvant chemotherapy and radiotherapy. She has been disease-free since then. On examination, there is tenderness over the L4/L5 region, and painfully restricted flexion, extension and rotation. Neurological exam is unremarkable. Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?', 'C', 'Physiotherapy', 'MRI of the lumbosacral spine', 'X-ray of the lumbosacral spine', 'Advise that she continue daily activities', 'Advise strict bed rest for 48 hours and analgesic', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(461, 'multiplechoice', 30738962, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 66-year-old man presents to your practice with complaints of left­sided cheek swelling, joint pain and fatigue for the past 2 months. He has a 20-year history of type II diabetes mellitus. He also mentions eye and mouth dryness for the past 6 months. On examination, there is non-tender swelling of the left parotid gland, several dental carries and reddened eyes. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'B', 'Left salivary duct stone', 'Sjogren syndrome ', 'Parotid gland carcinoma', 'Chronic parotiditis', 'Behcet\'s syndrome', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(462, 'multiplechoice', 30738964, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Sue, 56 years old, presents to the emergency department with acute onset right knee pain starting three hours ago and worsening gradually. On examination, she has a BMI of 32, blood pressure of 158/105 mmHg, pulse rate of 90 bpm, and temperature of 37°C. A joint aspirate excludes septic arthritis but with the presence of birefringent crystals is highly suggestive of gouty arthritis. Her medical history is remarkable for chronic kidney disease due to long-standing hypertension. Laboratory tests are ordered, of which a serum uric acid of 0.6 mmol/L (normal: 0.12-0.42 mmol/L) and a GFR of 30 (normal: 90-120 ml/min/1.73m2) are remarkable. Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment to consider for her?', 'D', 'Paracetamo', 'Naproxen', 'Codeine', 'Colchicine', 'Colchicine', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `qustions` (`id`, `Question_Type_multiplechoice`, `Question_Id`, `Parent_Category`, `Category`, `Random_Answers`, `Correct_Feedback`, `Incorrect_Feedback`, `Points`, `Question`, `Correct`, `Answer_A`, `Answer_B`, `Answer_C`, `Answer_D`, `Answer_E`, `Answer_F`, `Answer_G`, `Answer_H`, `Answer_I`, `Answer_J`) VALUES
(463, 'multiplechoice', 30738965, 'Generic Parent', 'Medicine', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'A 48-year-old man presents to the emergency department with complaints of sudden onset chest pain that worsens on respiration and shortness of breath. On physical examination, he has a blood pressure of 110/85mmHg, a pulse rate of 1_10 bpm and a respiratory rate of 24 breaths per minute. His jugular vein is distended and a prominent \'a\' wave of the jugular vein is noted. On heart auscultation, there is an S4. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 'A', 'Pulmonary embolism', 'Infectious endocarditis', 'Congestive heart failure', 'Rheumatic fever', 'Myocardial infarction', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(464, 'multiplechoice', 30738974, 'Generic Parent', 'Ortho & Rheumato', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Jane is 37-year-old woman who has presented to your clinic for the first time. She has a facial rash shown in the following photograph. According to her the rash is more prominent when she is exposed to sunlight. She also complains of 4-kg weight loss in the past 3 months, occasional low-grade fever and fatigue. She has had intermittent painful and mildly swollen wrists and knees to which recent finger pain has been added. On examination, oral ulcers that she has never noticed before are found. You order laboratory tests the result of which are remarkable for mild normocytic, normochromic anemia; mild thrombocytopenia; an elevated ESR of 110; positive ANA, and positive ds-DNA antibody. Which one of the following is the most appropriate long-term treatment option for her?[cmimg]0/9406627_AH0Q602H.jpg[/cmimg]', 'C', 'Naproxen', 'Systemic corticosteroids', 'Hydroxychloroquine ', 'Methotrexate', 'Cyclophosphamide', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
